<FIRST>r a AM-MissingCouple 3rdLd-Writethru a0402 11-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Couple, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0402,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Exec, Wife, Found Shot to Death in Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs last 2 grafs to change to past tense.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. executive
and his wife were found shot to death, their bodies dumped in a
park, after their home was ransacked and robbed Friday, police and
FBI agents said.
   Glenn E. and Wanda Tarr's neighbors reported a possible break-in
about 5:30 a.m. Friday. The couple was not there, and police said
it appeared they had had been abducted.
   Their bodies were discovered by a woman walking her dog in a
park in nearby Pontiac later Friday. Each had been shot several
times.
   ``We do not believe they were shot at the home,'' said Hal
Helterhoff, who heads FBI operations in Michigan. ``They were shot
somewhere between the house and the park.''
   Investigators believe Mrs. Tarr may have abducted during an
outing Thursday evening, forced to withdraw cash from the couple's
bank account at a 24-hour teller machine and then taken to her home
by her assailants, Helterhoff said. After the house was ransacked,
the Tarrs were abducted, he said.
   There was no forced entry at the house, he added. Deputies found
no signs of violence or a struggle, police Sgt. Joe Quisenberry
said.
   The couple's two cars, a 1989 Geo Prizm and a 1988 Chevrolet
Cavalier, were missing. Guns, liquor, jewelry and part of a coin
collection were believed taken from the home, Helterhoff added.
   Helterhoff said the FBI was questioning neighbors and relatives
and had talked with two of the couple's children, college students
who weren't at the home Friday.
   Glenn Tarr was assistant manager of marketing information and
research for GM's Chevrolet Division headquarters in Warren, said
GM spokesman Jim Crellin.
   Ralph Kramer, director of public relations for GM's Chevrolet
Division, said Tarr supervised the collection and analysis of sales
data from across the country for Chevrolet.
</TEXT>
