<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-10 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists will honor a farmer who
won a battle of wits with bugs.
   James M. Szynal, a farmer in the western Massachusetts town of
Florence and chief mechanic at Woods Enterprises, will be presented
on Saturday with an award from the Massachusetts Audubon Society
for a homemade device that vacuums bugs off potato plants.
   He developed the ``Beetle Eater'' two years ago at the request
of another farmer, who didn't want to use pesticides. It can suck
potato beetles off four rows of plants at one time as it is towed
through a field.
   The machine can clean 50 to 70 acres of potatoes in a day and
removes 75 to 95 percent of the beetles, according to Szynal.
   ``This farmer walked into my garage ... and said, `You've got to
invent something to take the bugs off the plant. The spray's
killing me,''' Szynal said Thursday. ``Ten days later I had a
machine rolling.''
   The key to the machine is a blower that dislodges the beetles; a
vacuum hose then scoops them up.
   ``The Colorado potato beetle likes to play dead as soon as it
senses any noise or movement, that's why we had to add the blower
to shake them up,'' Szynal said.
   Szynal has other inventions for the farm. There's a vacuum
device that debugs strawberry plants, a plastic cutter that makes
round holes in plastic ground covers for corn plants, and an
automatic pickle picker.
   ``It used to be I'd put my whole week's pay into my inventions
and be broke by Wednesday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who reeled in a cat from an old
water well say their feat is no fish story.
   Charles Wolfinger and Terry Johnson, reserve officers for the
Vanderburgh County Sheriff's Department, said workers at a truck
stop heard a cat's meows from a well.
   The attached a towel to a hook and dropped fishing line 45 feet
down an 8-inch water pipe. The cat clawed on to the towel, and the
men pulled it to safety.
   ``I thought that by instinct they like to claw things and I
thought that if I could get a piece of cloth down to it, it would
grab on,'' Wolfinger said.
   He said someone apparently had dropped the cat in the well
because a heavy hinged lid over the opening had been closed.
   A worker took the cat home.
</TEXT>
