<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Cannibalism     11-10 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Cannibalism,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three To Be Tried for Cannibalism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBREVILLE, Gabon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men and a woman alleged to have
eaten human flesh during a ritual initiation ceremony will be tried
on charges of murder and cannibalism, the national news agency said.
   The Gabonese Press Agency said Thursday that Mba Ntem, Raymond
Mve Owono and Sabine Benga are charged with clubbing and stabbing
to death Andre Ondo Ndong in the suburban community of Owendo.
   The trio then allegedly ate Ndong's stomach, liver, heart,
lungs, tongue and genitals in a ritual ceremony led by Ntem.
   The news agency did not give further details about the type of
ceremony. Murder and cannibalism are both punishable by death in
this West African country.
   The three will be tried Nov. 23.
</TEXT>
