<FIRST>r i PM-FirstCrossings     11-10 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-First Crossings,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berliners Stroll To The Other Side For First Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torsten Ryl had been a Berliner all 24 years of
his life. But until early today, he had never seen the other half
of the divided city.
   Suddenly, all it took was a flash of his identity card.
   ``At the stroke of midnight, they told us, `The procedure has
been shortened, and all you need is a stamp,''' said Ryl, a waiter,
still awestruck at his sudden crossing into the West through
Checkpoint Charlie.
   ``It's not my intention to stay here, but we have to have the
possibility to come over here and go back again,'' Ryl said. ``I
have my apartment and my car over there.''
   A middle-aged West German reached over, gave him 20 marks ($11)
and said with a grin: ``Why don't you go get yourself a beer
first?''
   In what seemed like a fantasy, thousands of Berliners today
strolled through the other half of the city where Communist East
Germany had denied them free passage for 28 years.
   Helmut and Katarina Erdmann said they briefly left their three
sleeping children at home in East Berlin.
   ``We just wanted to go for a stroll,'' Helmut Erdmann said.
``It's crazy.''
   West Berliners also crossed eastward. Germans from both sides
held impromptu dances atop the wall, hoisting people up from both
sides to join them.
   Thomas Moll said he was allowed to cross into West Berlin in
less than five minutes.
   ``I just can't believe it,'' he said. ``A lot of people thought
it was just another trick.''
   Moll, 21, said he also intended to return home after having a
look around West Berlin.
   He reluctantly gave his name to reporters. ``You're not from
Stasi, are you?'' he asked, referring to the East German state
security service.
   It seemed as if each East Berliner who crossed the demarcation
line was greeted with cheers _ many by hugs and kisses _ by the
crowd at Checkpoint Charlie.
   Traffic jams built up on the western side of the checkpoint, and
people with sparklers and champagne bottles streamed out of the
Kochstrasse subway stop on the West Berlin side to join the party.
   Thousands celebrated on the Kurfuerstendamm, a boulevard in West
Berlin's upscale shopping district.
   East German Trabant cars were welcomed by cheers and honking
horns as they slowly wended their way down the boulevard, which for
one night was the scene of the wildest celebrations since the
Berlin Wall was born in the Cold War.
   ``This is a historic day!'' one man yelled. ``We're going to be
able to tell our children about this!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
