<FIRST>r a AM-RapeIndictment     11-10 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Indictment,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Acquitted in Florida Rape Case to Face Georgia Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose rape acquittal in Florida
gained national attention when jurors criticized the woman's
clothing is now facing attempted rape charges in his home state of
Georgia.
   Steven Lamar Lord, 26, was indicted Wednesday on one count each
of false imprisonment, aggravated assault with intent to commit
rape, criminal attempt to commit rape and robbery in an attack on a
Gwinnett woman Sept. 21, 1988.
   The 24-year-old woman says she was raped a knifepoint.
   Lord was first indicted in the case in January, but Assistant
District Attorney Scott Smeal said a new indictment was issued to
change the language of the aggravated assault charge.
   A six-member jury in Broward County, Fla., found Lord innocent
of charges last month that he raped a 22-year-old woman at knife
point after abducting her from a Fort Lauderdale restaurant parking
lot in November 1988.
   Several jurors said the woman enticed Lord with skimpy clothing,
including a lace miniskirt with no underwear.
   ``She was obviously dressed for a good time, but we felt she may
have bit off more than she could chew,'' juror Mary Bradshaw said
following the verdict, which unleashed outrage around the nation
from sexual assualt counselors and women's groups.
   The woman, wearing various disguises, has appeared on several
national talks shows to discuss the case.
   During the trial, Lord's attorney told jurors that the woman
agreed to have sex with Lord in exchange for $100 and cocaine.
</TEXT>
