<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gasoline-Cancer Bjt   11-10 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline-Cancer, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Vapors Unhealthy, Consumer Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group is calling for tighter
controls on toxic gasoline vapors, saying that motorists who pump
their own gas are being exposed to unhealthy levels of
cancer-causing benzene and other pollutants.
   Citizen Action, a Washington-based organization that focuses on
consumer and environmental issues, accused the oil companies
Thursday of ignoring health concerns by increasing levels of
benzene and other aromatic hydrocarbons in unleaded gasoline to
boost its octane rating.
   The American Petroleum Institute issued a statement that
disputed the claims and accused Citizen Action of raising
``unwarranted fears about motorists' exposure to gasoline.''
   The Environmental Protection Agency acknowledged that toxic
vapors from gasoline at the pump are a health concern, but an
agency spokesman suggested the claims raised by Citizen Action on
health impact may be exaggerated.
   Nevertheless, said EPA spokesman David Ryan, the Bush
administration proposal for tightening federal air quality laws
calls for better vapor-capturing devices such as sleeves or hoods
on gasoline pumps. It also would require oil companies to produce
gasoline that releases less vapor pollutants.
   Several localities already require vapor-control hoods on
gasoline pumps, but the devices have been controversial because
they have been found to be cumbersome and unpopular in many cases.
   Benzene, which has been shown to cause leukemia, appears in
petroleum products such as gasoline and its vapors. It also is
generated during combustion and releases through motor vehicle
tailpipes.
   The report by Citizen Action claimed that motorists are exposed
to benzene levels of more than 1 part per million when refueling
their cars _ a level expected to result, according to several
studies, in at least two additional cancer cases over a lifetime
per 1 million people exposed. It said a California study suggested
even higher exposures.
   ``Despite the scientific evidence demonstrating that human
exposure to benzene increases the risk of contracting cancer, oil
companies have neither adequately warned consumers, nor acted to
responsibly reduce benzene levels,'' said the citizen group.
   Ed Rothschild, energy and environmental policy director for
Citizen Action, said the EPA ``has sat on its hands for the last 13
years and has done nothing to regulate mobile sources of benzene,''
although it recently announced regulations to curb benzene releases
from industrial facilities and storage tanks.
   The American Petroleum Institute, the oil industry's trade
group, denounced the Citizen Action claims, calling the allegations
``a disservice to the consumers it purports to represents.''
   Gus Ensz, a spokesman for the American Petroleum Institute, said
consumers' exposure to benzene at service stations is for ``only a
few minutes a week (and) typically to low levels.''
   The trade group accused Citizen Action of trying ``to raise
unwarranted fears'' among motorists.
   The Environmental Protection Agency recently announced tighter
controls on benzene emissions from a variety of sources from
industrial plants to storage facilities because chronic exposure is
believed to cause leukemia. But the new regulations do not cover
emissions from motor vehicles, which the agency says accounts for
about 80 percent of the benzene releases.
   Most of the releases from gasoline occur through vehicle
tailpipes during fuel combustion, but a substantial amount also is
released through gasoline vapors with exposure being greatest at
service stations when motorists are refueling, environmental
studies have said.
   Citizen Action is a Washington-based federation of citizen
groups that claims more than 2 million members in 25 states. It
focuses on a variety of consumer, environmental and health issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SmokingBan Bjt   11-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking Ban, Bjt,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Adopts Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of smoking aboard airliners are on
the verge of winning their fight to forbid passengers from lighting
up on practically all U.S. flights.
   The Senate by voice vote Thursday passed a prohibition against
cigarette smoking on all but a handful of domestic flights.
Tobacco-state lawmakers, long convinced they were badly
outnumbered, made no comments on the prohibition.
   The House approved the ban, included in a $12 billion
transportation bill for the new fiscal year, on Oct. 31. The Senate
will continue debate on the spending measure Tuesday and will send
it to President Bush for his signature if no changes in the
legislation are made.
   ``Approval of this law is a milestone in the efforts to protect
those who don't want to put themselves at risk by inhaling other
people's smoke,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., the measure's
sponsor.
   The new restrictions permanently forbid smoking on all routes
within the continental United States, and on all flights to and
from Alaska and Hawaii scheduled for six hours or less.
   The current ban _ which expires next April _ applies only to
routes lasting two hours or less, covering 80 percent of all
flights.
   Smoking would remain legal on only about 28 of the 17,500 daily
scheduled U.S. flights, according to the House sponsor of the
measure, Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill. Uncovered would be 24 flights
each day to Alaska and Hawaii and four to Guam.
   Lautenberg and his allies, citing studies by the surgeon
general's office and other sources, have argued that it is
unhealthy to breathe cigarette fumes from smokers.
   Tobacco industry supporters insist cigarette smoke is only one
chemical in airline cabin air, which is recirculated. They have
argued Congress should not act until the Department of
Transportation completes a study next year on the components of
cabin air.
   ``The Congress has essentially acted in an informational
vacuum,'' said spokesman Walker Merryman of the Tobacco Institute,
the cigarette industry's trade group.
   Cigar and pipe smoking aboard airliners has been illegal since
1983.
   The bill also provides $3.2 billion for anti-drug programs; $40
million to begin building a new airport in Denver, the nation's
first new airport in 15 years; and $14 million to develop new
bomb-detection machines.
</TEXT>
