<FIRST>r w PM-ChildCare Bjt   11-10 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, Bjt,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Child Care Confrontation Looms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate Democrats, with the help of a
maverick Republican senator, are setting the stage for a new
showdown with President Bush over child care subsidies.
   Negotiators from the two congressional bodies reached agreement
Thursday night on legislation that would increase direct federal
child care subsidies to low- and moderate-income families by $1.2
billion in 1990 and by up to $8.5 billion over the next five years.
   The accord was struck after Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, dropped
his demand that states be allowed to issue vouchers for a new $300
million program to pay for keeping schools open longer hours to
provide day care and establish a new education-driven program for
pre-school tots.
   ``At least we have a running shot now with a bill that the
president might not veto,'' said Hatch, who angered the
administration, Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole and conservative
groups by joining with liberal Democrats last spring in putting
together the basic package.
   In exchange, House Democrats agreed to allow more of the money
to go to rural areas at governors' discretion and let states issue
vouchers that parents could use to pay for day care services
provided by churches.
   A separate group of House and Senate negotiators still must
reach accord on another provision included in the child care
package that would increase tax credits for poor families with
children by $500 to $750 a year.
   But House and Senate Democratic leaders instructed the chairmen
of their tax-writing committees Thursday to try to settle
differences over that portion by Monday night in a drive to get a
House vote by the end of next week.
   ``We're going to move on the child care bill as a separate item
... and we hope to see an early enactment of it,'' said House
Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash.
   His counterpart in the Senate, Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, said the same effort will be made there, but acknowledged
it will be more difficult to accomplish before adjourning for
Thanksgiving, under Senate rules.
   ``Our problem is there's Republican opposition,'' Mitchell said.
``They're opposed to passing it any time, this year or next.''
   The Senate approved its version of the bill by a 63-37 margin in
June over fierce opposition from the administration and Senate GOP
Leader Bob Dole. A companion measure was approved by the House last
month as part of a bill aimed a bringing down the federal deficit
in fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1.
   With public opinion polls indicating a large majority of
Americans favor federal aid for child care, Democrats and Hatch
hope that Bush would not veto the bill.
   But if he does, said Rep. Gus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the
House Education and Labor Committee, Congress will pass the same
measure again early next year at the opening of the 1990 election
cycle.
   ``It's going to be pretty damned hard to get anybody in 1990 to
vote against child care,'' said Hawkins.
   No one knows exactly how much of the federal block grants to
states are now spent on child care subsidies, but estimates range
from $400 million to $1 billion a year.
   Under the compromise reached Thursday, those block grants would
be augmented with a new $750 million program of child care
subsidies with a mandate that states regulate care providers.
   Another $150 million would be added to the Head Start pre-school
program that now reaches about half a million 3- and 4-year-olds
each year with the aim of turning those facilities into all-day,
year-round child care centers.
   Bush has adamantly opposed making states regulate day care
centers and has insisted that any new aid be limited to tax credits
for poor families with children under age 4 and a slight expansion
of Head Start funding.
</TEXT>
