<FIRST>r a PM-Alzheimer's-Symptoms     11-10 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alzheimer's-Symptoms,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Symptoms of Alzheimer's Disease</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Alzheimer's Disease, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alzheimer's disease usually progresses in three
broad stages, according to the American Medical Association. Here
are typical symptoms, as described by the AMA and Dr. Bruce
Naughton of Northwestern University Medical School:
   _Forgetfulness, frequently going unnoticed but causing anxiety
or depression in the person affected.
   _Severe memory loss, with victims unable to remember recent
visitors or what they saw on television, though they can remember
long-ago events. Accompanying this stage may be a tendency to get
disoriented in time or space, to lose one's way or wander, and to
lose the capacity to care for themselves.
   Also apparent may be an exaggeration of existing personality
traits _ extreme anger if the person is normally hot-tempered,
extreme passivity if the person is normally placid; or an extreme
tendency to wander if the person is normally an ``on-the-go'' type.
   _Severe confusion and disorientation, with possible
hallucinations or delusions. The sufferer may forget to eat, may
lose control of bladder and bowel functions and may be bedridden
and prone to repeated infections.
   A person usually lives five to 10 years after developing
Alzheimer's disease, though the course of the uncurable illness may
run from one to 20 years, Naughton said.
</TEXT>
