<DOCNO> AP891110-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-DemocraticConvention     11-10 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Democratic Convention,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Consider Five Cities For '92 Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five cities are making their pitches to host
the 1992 Democratic National Convention and party chairman Ron
Brown says the decision will be based on facilities, not electoral
politics.
   A selection committee of the Democratic National Committee was
finishing a two-day meeting today to hear formal presentations from
the five cities in the running.
   They are Cleveland, with its suburb of Brook Park, Ohio;
Detroit; Houston; New Orleans; and New York.
   The panel may pare the list to three or four and the members
will visit those finalists.
   But Brown said he would regard the committee's final choice only
as a recommendation and that he will make the final decision.
   ``I want a city that has facilities that will allow us to have a
first-class convention, that will be able to nominate the next
president of the United States,'' Brown said. ``It is principally
what kind of facilities, what kind of financial package, the local
support that we're going to have.
   ``There has been no decision made yet on where this convention
is going to be,'' Brown told the committee. ``It is truly an open
process.''
   Seattle, Miami and Atlanta have withdrawn their bids. Several
other major cities, including Los Angeles, San Francisco, Dallas
and Chicago, declined to make a bid.
   Most cited the requirement that the party have unlimited access
to the convention hall for three months before the convention as
the reason for withdrawing or not bidding. The party also said each
city would have to be prepared to invest $15 million.
   The Democrats met last year in Atlanta and the Republicans met
in New Orleans. Detroit was the site of the 1980 GOP convention,
and the Democrats met in New York in 1976 and 1980.
   Brown told reporters he didn't feel any need to look in one
particular region as a symbolic selection and didn't believe
selection of a city would make much difference in Democratic
chances of carrying that state or region in 1992.
   ``It certainly hasn't been the case in the past,'' he said. ``It
is not going to be a principal consideration in these
deliberations.''
</TEXT>
