<FIRST>r w PM-Education-Governors     11-10 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education-Governors,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Push Toward Education Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors say they will seek help
from members of Congress and experts in the business and education
fields in keeping their promise to set up national education goals
by the end of February.
   Emerging from a White House meeting with Bush administration
officials Thursday, governors said they will also hold a Dec. 7
Task Force on Education meeting in Washington and are seeking state
hearings and discussions in December and January.
   ``We promised in Charlottesville to put this national education
goals on the front burner for the governors, on the front burner
for the White House, and we're keeping it on a very very fast
track,'' said Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, a Democrat.
   The drive for national goals came from the education summit
President Bush and the nation's governors held in late September at
the University of Virginia in Charlottesville.
   Clinton said the governors will seek the views of Congress and
other educational experts before recommending targets for the
nation's schools.
   ``Before the summit, we let the leadership of both parties of
Congress know that we needed their help and support and their
involvement in order to do anything meaningful to restructure the
schools and to get greater flexibility in the expending existing
federal programs,'' said Clinton.
   Congress and educators were excluded from the two-day summit
that concluded nationwide goals are needed to improve learning.
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell, a Republican, said
governors want to ``form a true coalition between the Congress, the
states and the executive branch of the White House in trying to
build a consensus to improve education in the country.''
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad, chairman of the National Governors
Association and a Republican, said Congress will be asked to begin
immediately to work on legislation that would bring more
flexibility to regulations attached to many federal education
programs.
   Looser restrictions on federal funding was discussed at the
summit. Other summit goals were to improve early childhood
programs, restructure school systems to make educators more
accountable, keep drugs out of schools, bolster on-the-job
education, improve literacy and reduce the national dropout rate.
   Branstad led the group of governors who met at the White House
with chief of staff John Sununu; Roger Porter, the president's
domestic policy adviser; budget director Richard Darman; and
Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos.
   After the Dec. 7 Washington meeting of education experts, the
governors will hold state hearings and discussions in their
respective states in December and January, said NGA Vice Chairman
Booth Gardner of Washington state.
   Once the goals are adopted, said Campbell, governors will focus
on strategies for reaching them and ``tackling the rest of the
ambitious agenda we set at the summit.''
   ``Goals are the essential first step toward what the governors
are really after _ results in the classroom and in the workforce,''
said Campbell.
</TEXT>
