<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSHealthWorkers     11-10 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Health Workers,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC to Survey AIDS Risk for Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Centers for Disease Control wants to
undertake a major survey of the AIDS risk among surgeons as part of
its effort to determine the particular risks in health care
professions.
   ``It's very delicate,'' said Dr. David M. Bell of the CDC in
Atlanta, explaining negotiations with members of the surgical
profession. He said surgeons are concerned that patients, for
example, could demand the results of AIDS tests for all patients.
   He said the method of conducting the test is in place if the
agreement can be made.
   Bell mentioned the proposed study Thursday when asked to comment
on allegations made at a congressional hearing that government
health officials are grossly understating the possible risk of
contracting AIDS.
   Dr. Lorraine Day, chief of orthopedic surgery at San Francisco
General Hospital, said the government fears health care workers
will deny treatment to HIV-infected patients if all the risks are
known.
   She told the House Education and Labor subcommittee on health
and safety that CDC and others have been off the mark in their
assessment of the AIDS risk. She said the same argument used now
that AIDS is not transmitted by saliva was used in 1983 to rule out
transmission of the virus by blood transfusions, and the number of
documented cases in each instance was the same: five.
   ``There are more things we need to do,'' Bell acknowledged, but
said there are ``huge masses of data indicating what the risks
are.''
   He said health care professional need to ensure that instruments
and techniques are not ``inherently hazardous.''
   Three surgeons in the last 10 years who engaged in none of the
high-risk behavior associated with AIDS have contracted the
disease, he said. ``We have the feeling that while its true that
these are cases of AIDS and not HIV infection, we have the feeling
that after 10 years we would see more than three surgeons. It's a
feeling,'' he said.
   The subcommittee is conducting hearings on proposed federal
regulations to limit the spread of blood-borne pathogens such as
the AIDS and hepatitis B viruses.
   Day said the same reluctance to look at possible AIDS infection
through contact with unbroken skin and saliva is cheating the
public of important knowledge.
   The government says AIDS is spread through sexual contact,
needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products and from infected pregnant women to their offspring.
   Day said the growing risk of AIDS cases prompted her to resign
effective Feb. 1, 1990, from the hospital. The hospital has San
Francisco's only trauma center and is one of the foremost AIDS
research centers in the country.
   ``I personally know 13 surgeons who are HIV positive from
occupational exposure,'' she said, adding patients have a right to
know if their physicians are infected.
   Bell said as for possible transmission of AIDS through contact
with unbroken skin, ``We just don't see that.''
   He said there is nothing to suggest that transmission through
the high-speed tools used in an operating room is a risk.
   One study cited by Day showed that the AIDS virus lived seven
days outside the body. But Bell said that involved higher
concentrations than in any operating room or the ``worst AIDS
patient.''
</TEXT>
