<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Shamir     11-10 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Shamir,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Issues Last-Minute Invitation for Bush-Shamir Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will be meeting with Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir next week, after all.
   The invitation for next Wednesday's meeting was issued Thursday
_ almost two months after Israel first sought it while making
arrangements for Shamir's visit to address Jewish groups in
Cincinnati and Los Angeles.
   Shamir arrives in New York on Monday and his aides had been
holding his schedule open in hopes that Bush would invite him to
meet with him.
   Israeli officials were upset and mystified by the U.S. delay,
believing that Israel had appeased U.S. requirements by adopting
Secretary of State James A. Baker III's proposal to begin making
arrangements for Palestinian elections in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   But Baker, speaking to reporters aboard a plane whic brought him
Wednesday from Australia, said he had made clear to Israel that he
rejected the assurances it sought regarding the talks with a
Palestinian delegation.
   ``It's all very curious. Did the Israelis misunderstand or is
Baker trying to send some sort of signal?'' said one State
Department official.
   A White House statement on next Wednesday's meeting said Bush
wanted to talk with Shamir about steps to advance the Middle East
peace process.
   Israel gave its qualified approval to Baker's blueprint on
Sunday but asked for his assurances on several matters, including
the exclusion of the Palestine Liberation Organization from any
talks.
   The State Department said Thursday that another in a series of
meetings between U.S. Embassy officials and PLO representatives was
held in Tunis on Tuesday to discuss the election proposal. It did
not elaborate.
   The United States is still awaiting word from Egypt, which has
also been speaking for the PLO, on whether the Baker plan has been
accepted.
   The plan calls for elections to pick Palestinian delegates who
would negotiate with Israeli authorities for self-government in the
West Bank and Gaza.
   The crux of the problem concerns the makeup of the Palestinian
delegation that will discuss the election procedures with Israel, a
U.S. official said Thursday.
   To win the PLO's backing for the plan, Baker has proposed that
some of the delegates be Palestinians living in exile. But Israel,
fearing that any exiled Palestinian would be a de facto PLO member,
is insisting that only Palestinians from the territories be
permitted to take part.
   Two weeks ago presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a
Bush-Shamir meeting was likely. But later in the day, his office
issued a terse statement saying no decision had been made on such a
meeting and that Shamir would be here on a private visit.
   Bush, asked at a news conference earlier this week whether he
would meet with Shamir, said he would be willing to consider such a
meeting as long as the two sides have ``something positive to talk
about.''
   It would have been highly unusual for an American president to
refuse to meet with an Israeli leader. Israel is the largest
recipient of U.S. aid, getting $3 billion each year, and is one of
Washington's top allies.
</TEXT>
