<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Berlin-Party Bjt   11-10 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin-Party, Bjt,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berlin Has Its Biggest Party Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was, quite simply, the biggest party that
fun-loving Berliners ever had.
   Hours after East Germany opened the wall it built in 1961 to
keep the two Berlins apart, thousands of East and West Berliners
reunited in an outpouring of joy that lasted well into this morning.
   Hordes of East Berliners poured across the Berlin Wall, crossing
in their tiny Trabant cars, on foot, or on packed subways.
   ``Madness! Madness!'' cried a 44-year-old East Berlin woman who
gave her name as Inge. ``To think that I'm seeing all this after 28
years.''
   She and her husband Werner were already in their nightclothes
when they heard the border was open.
   ``We were up and dressed with our son in a second,'' her husband
said. ``But even we couldn't get across in the car, there were so
many people. So we just left it there and pushed our way across.''
   At the Invalidenstrasse crossing to East Berlin, police appealed
frantically to the crowd to clear the path for hundreds of East
Berliners crossing to raucous cheers from the Westerers.
   ``This is a historic day, and because it is such a historic
moment we ask you to keep the crossing clear,'' a policeman
repeatedly told the crowd.
   Few listened.
   ``We were here when the Wall went up in 1961,'' beamed West
Berliner Helga Zuballa, 53. ``We're so happy. If it keeps on like
this, we'll have nothing left to wish for.''
   Champagne corks popped, and some West Berlin bars _ the only
ones in Germany which never close _ offered free beer to the
arriving hordes of East Berliners. Other West Germans offered money
to the newcomers.
   West Berlin authorities ordered city subways to run all night to
cope with the unprecedented mass of people moving around in the
city.
   ``I promised him I'd take him across if they opened up the
border,'' said Uwe Scheiderat as he and his 17-year-old son, Erich,
gazed in wonder at the electronics on show in a display window on
the Kurfuerstendamm, one of Europe's most elegant shopping streets.
   Hundreds of West Berliners took a journey themselves, heading in
the opposite direction to catch a glimpse of the East.
   ``For the first time in my life, I had tears in my eyes when I
listened to the TV news,'' said Peter Huber, one of thousands of
West Berliners who flooded toward the Invalidenstrasse crossing.
   ``What joy! This is the best thing that happened in 100 years!''
yelled another West Berlin man.
   ``It's crazy! It's crazy!'' shouted a young man from the back
seat of a car.
   In the delirium, few seemed to notice that East German radio had
announced visa-free entrances would stop this morning.
   In East Berlin, however, hundreds of people jammed the House of
Travel on the Alexanderplatz, already lining up for visas that
would allow them to cross today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
