<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     11-10 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston, UMW In First Joint Session with Supermediator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers and the Pittston
Co. will begin intensive bargaining next week in an effort to
resolve the 7-month-old strike against the coal company, the
government's supermediator says.
   ``I'm absolutely convinced that both sides want a contract,''
mediator W.J. Usery said Thursday after he hosted the first
face-to-face negotiating session involving UMW President Richard
Trumka and Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas.
   Usery and other participants said the 75-minute session was
largely spent setting ground rules for the negotiations but
included a brief discussion of the broad issues in the strike,
which has idled 1,700 miners in Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky since April.
   ``We weren't dealing with substance,'' said Trumka.
   Among the rules, said Usery, was an agreement that specifics of
the negotiations to begin Monday will not be disclosed to the media.
   ``We don't want to mediate in the press,'' the former labor
secretary and veteran mediator told reporters. Usery said
negotiations would go on ``day and night if necessary'' and he held
out hope the bitter and sometimes violent strike could be over by
Thanksgiving.
   The biggest issue in the dispute is over Pittston's payments of
health and retirement benefits, a fight whose outcome could have
far-reaching effects in the coal industry.
   The company withdrew from a national compact among coal
producers that guarantees retired miners health and pension
benefits. The union believes that if Pittston is successful in
trimming those benefits, other companies will attempt to do so.
   Usery said he did not ask Trumka and Douglas to attend Monday's
session and would not request their presence unless he believed an
agreement was within reach.
   Douglas pledged his support for the mediation, saying he would
do ``whatever I can do to help with the process.'' He also praised
for Usery, saying he was ``very impressed'' with the man Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole tapped two weeks ago in hopes of resolving
the strike.
   Trumka said, ``If anyone can get this job done I think Bill
Usery can.''
</TEXT>
