<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseBill 1stLd-Writethru a0455 11-10 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Restores dropped matter at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers are complaining that the
House-approved $305 billion defense bill is a weak response to
major political changes worldwide and amounts to nothing more than
a jobs program.
   ``The Warsaw Pact is crumbling before our eyes and we're
building weapons of destruction,'' said Rep. Ronald Dellums,
D-Calif., a member of the House Armed Services Committee and a
longtime opponent of military buildup.
   Although both proponents and opponents criticized the defense
bill _ a compromise package worked out by House and Senate
conferees after nearly two months of contentious negotiations _ the
House on Thursday adopted the legislation, 236-172.
   The bill, which goes to the Senate, slashes $1.1 billion from
President Bush's request for the Strategic Defense Initiative but
provides much of the money for two land-based nuclear missiles and
the B-2 stealth bomber.
   The legislation also continues two programs Bush sought to kill
_ the Navy's F-14D Tomcat jet fighter and the AHIP helicopter _ for
one more year, and postpones a decision on the Marine Corps' V-22
Osprey and the Phoenix missile.
   The Osprey, the tilt-rotor aircraft that takes off like a
helicopter but can fly like a plane, will receive about $255
million in research and development money in fiscal 1990 but no
funds for procurement.
   The legislation includes money for 18 F-14D jet fighters but
requires the manufacturer, Grumman Corp., to sign a termination
agreement ending all future production.
   Salvaging weapons programs _ and jobs in many districts _ drew
the ire of a number of lawmakers.
   ``The defense pork bill passed the Congress today. Congress made
no hard choices,'' said Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a member of the
House Armed Services Committee. ``The relationship between national
security and the defense authorization bill is just about
coincidental.''
   The complaints came as East Germany opened the Berlin Wall and
its other borders Thursday and allowed citizens to cross freely to
the West for the first time in 28 years.
   ``Peace is breaking out and we're going to have four legs of the
triad instead of three,'' said Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a
member of the Armed Services panel.
   Another committee member, Rep. Larry Hopkins, R-Ky., said, ``The
winds of change are sweeping across every part of our world. We
have an opportunity to set a course to take this nation forward.''
   Instead, Hopkins said, Congress was ``corrupted by parochial
avarice.''
   The defense budget, according to Dellums, ``continues to pursue
the same tired old path of no change, military expansion, more and
more brand-new conventional and nuclear weapons systems at a time
when the world is crying out for change and the world is crying out
for peace.''
   Among the legislation's provisions are $4.3 billion for the B-2,
$430 million less than the administration requested for the fiscal
year that began Oct. 1. The bill provides money for two bombers in
fiscal 1990, one less than the administration sought. However, the
legislation accepts Bush's proposal for components for five bombers
in fiscal 1991.
   The bill provides $3.8 billion for SDI _ also known as Star Wars
_ about $279 million less than was spent in fiscal 1989 and the
first decrease since President Reagan proposed the anti-missile
shield six years ago. Bush had sought $4.9 billion for the program.
   Approximately $1.1 billion is included for two land-based
nuclear missiles: the multiple-warhead, rail-garrison MX and the
single-warhead, truck-based Midgetman. The bill trims about $150
million from the administration's request for the two weapons and
adds House language imposing a 50-missile cap on the MX.
   Also Thursday, House and Senate negotiators reached agreement on
a $288 billion military spending bill for fiscal 1990 that largely
tracks the defense authorization bill on the major strategic
weapons, said lawmakers and congressional sources, who requested
anonymity.
</TEXT>
