<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--GaySex     11-10 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Gay Sex,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharp Rise in Gonorrhea Could Signal Return to Unsafe Sex, Feds Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of gonorrhea among homosexual men in
Seattle could signal a ``risky relapse'' from AIDS-prompted ``safe
sex'' practices among homosexual men, health officials warned.
   Researchers with the national Centers for Disease Control said
Thursday that a study reported 79 gonorrhea cases in the first 10
months of this year at a public health clinic in Seattle. If the
rate continued, the clinic would report about 100 cases this year,
compared with 27 last year.
   The surprising increase follows a 96 percent decline in
gonorrhea cases at the clinic over the previous six years.
   Widespread publicity about the spread of the deadly disease
among homosexuals has led to changes over the last decade in the
sexual practices of many homosexual men who previously may have had
many partners. Gonorrhea, like AIDS, is sexually transmitted.
   The latest increase might be an isolated occurrence among
homosexuals who have continued to practice unsafe sex, the CDC said
in its weekly report. But the outbreak could mean that, eight years
after the discovery of AIDS, ``some homosexually active men may
have relaxed behaviors regarding sexual safety.''
   ``These really profound changes _ celibacy, monogamy _ may be
remarkably difficult, more difficult to maintain as time passes,''
said William Whittington, a CDC specialist in sexually transmitted
diseases. ``If this is indeed true, we in this business may need to
look at things we can try to help people sustain these kinds of
changes over time.''
   The notion of a ``risky sexual relapse'' was put forth in June
at an AIDS conference in Montreal, as researchers said they had
seen signs of riskier sexual behavior among homosexuals in San
Francisco.
   The new findings came from the Seattle-King County Department of
Public Health STD clinic, where patients are classified on the
basis of sexual orientation.
   The decade-long decline of gonorrhea in homosexual and bisexual
men has been attributed to concern over the spread of AIDS, which
was first reported in 1981.
   About 589,000 gonorrhea cases have been reported nationwide thus
far this year, down from an average of 713,000 at this point in the
five preceding years.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the
body's defenses against disease, exposing the victim to
life-threatening infections and cancers.
   The virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is
believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared
hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants
before or during birth.
</TEXT>
