<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LooseBombs     11-10 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loose Bombs,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Accidentally Dropped for Years Outside Military Range</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy pilots accidentally dropped hundreds of
bombs for years outside a military bombing range in central Nevada,
and state officials are angry they never were told about it.
   Navy officials, in a sweep that began Oct. 30 and should be
completed by mid-November, have found some bombs on public lands
used by hunters, hikers and off-road-vehicle enthusiasts.
   The Navy has recovered up to 2,000 live and dead bombs dropped
outside the 22,000-acre bombing range at Fallon Naval Air Station.
   ``I'm just appalled this has occurred,'' Gov. Bob Miller said
Thursday.
   He called it the latest in a ``string of broken promises from
the Navy.''
   ``There is absolutely no reason why we cannot expect them to
stay within the boundaries that were given them,'' Miller said.
   Miller ordered the closure of state Route 839, an 18-mile road
that parallels Navy bombing areas starting 60 miles east of Reno.
   He also said the Bureau of Land Management agreed to his request
to close 35,000 acres of public land surrounding the ranges until
the Navy completes its cleanup.
   Citizen Alert called for an indefinite halt to bombing at Fallon
pending an investigation into why the bombs were allowed to fall
outside the 22,000-acre range for years without public knowlege.
   ``This is something they should have notified the public about a
long time ago,'' said Bob Fulkerson, executive director of the
Reno-based environmental group.
   Capt. Rex Rackowitz, Fallon's commanding officer, said the
search and cleanup operation, code-named Operation Ugly Baby, is a
routine exercise to ensure people's safety. The public wasn't
informed of the effort to keep away onlookers, he said.
   Some of the ordnance is so dangerous is must be detonated on
site.
   Some explosives were found a mile or so outside the military
ranges and some appeared to have been there for up to 30 years,
``and the Navy has done nothing in that time,'' the governor said.
   Miller told military officials he was concerned some people
might take live ammunition on public lands as souvenirs.
   U.S. Sens. Harry Reid and Richard Bryan, both D-Nev., have
written Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett demanding full
disclosure about where the bombs are and why they were allowed to
sit for years.
   Base spokeswoman Susan Reinhardt said information about the
search by the Navy's Explosive Ordnance Disposal detachment was
released after Reno television station KTVN reported the sweep.
   Fallon Mayor Robert Erickson said the Navy ``has always been a
good neighbor'' and he's glad to see the recovery effort.
   ``Most of the bombs are in remote areas and I'm glad to see the
Navy identify a problem and take care of it,'' he said.
   Rackowitz said the current cleanup involves helicopters and
ground crews patrolling areas just outside the Navy's Bravo 17
range. The Navy plans another routine search for loose ordnance
next spring near the Bravo 16 and Bravo 19 ranges, he added.
   No accidents have been reported from people finding bombs.
   Rackowitz said the bombs were dropped outside the ranges because
of system malfunctions or by training pilots who made mistakes.
</TEXT>
