<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0455EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil     11-10 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Show Host Off Presidential Ballot in Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular TV game show host who appeared
tied for the lead in Brazil's presidential race lost his chance
when an electoral court ruled he violated election guidelines and
could not be on the ballot.
   The decision Thursday by the Supreme Electoral Tribunal ended
the nine-day candidacy of Silvio Santos, whose late entry into the
race rocked Brazil's first free presidential vote since 1960.
   It came the same day a Gallup poll was published showing Santos
virtually tied for the lead with center-rightist candidate Fernando
Collor de Mello. The poll showed Santos had 21.6 percent of the
vote.
   News reports speculated that President Jose Sarney engineered
Santos' entry into the race to undermine Collor de Mello, who has
tried to distance himself from the highly unpopular government and
create an image as a fighter of corruption.
   Sarney, who is not a candidate in the Wednesday's election,
denied it.
   All seven members of the electoral court ruled Santos was
ineligible to run because he violated a 1970 election law requiring
each candidate to leave the directorship of a government-licensed
business _ such as TV stations and networks _ three months before
the election.
   Santos' lawyers contended he merely owned controlling stock in
the SBT television network. But the court decided Santos actively
ran the nation's second-largest network.
   The court also unanimously ruled Santos' tiny Municipalist Party
did not fulfill election registration guidelines requiring at least
nine state conventions, and declared the tiny party defunct.
   Santos can appeal the decision to the Supreme Court, said the
court president, Jose Francisco Rezek.
   Santos, 58, refused comment on the ruling Thursday night.
   ``Mr. Santos told me to tell all of you reporters that he had a
headache and went to bed,'' said his maid, Narilia Lopes.
   The TV entertainer, who is popular among Brazil's poor, had been
widely criticized by other presidential candidates since he
declared his candidacy.
   Santos, born Senor Abravanel of Greek immigrant parents, rose
from selling wallets on streetcorners 35 years ago to become a
multimillionaire executive and owner of more than 30 businesses.
   Most candidates welcomed the court's decision.
   ``Santos' campaign was doomed from the start,'' said Luis Inacio
Lula da Silva of the Marxist-oriented Workers' Party.
   ``Now the campaign can get back to normal,'' said Sen. Mario
Covas of the left-of-center Brazilian Social Democracy Party. ``Now
all of those votes will come back to the true candidates of the
campaign.''
   Leonel Brizola, of the left-of-center Democratic Labor Party,
said those who backed Santos ``benefited from the dictatorship and
don't want to lose their accumulated privileges.''
   He was referring to Brazil's military rule that began in 1964
and lasted until Sarney, a poet, became president in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
