<HEAD>Horowitz Leaves Most of Estate to Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pianist Vladimir Horowitz left nearly all of his
estate, valued at $6 million to $8 million, to his wife, Wanda
Toscanini Horowitz.
   Horowitz died in New York on Nov. 5 at age 85.
   His nine-page will, dated Nov. 1, 1985, and filed Thursday in
Surrogate's Court in Manhattan, also leaves his personal property
to his wife, daughter of conductor Arturo Toscanini.
   Horowitz left $300,000 to the Juilliard School of Music to
establish scholarships for needy piano students.
   The Yale University School of Music will receive his
memorabilia, musical scores, correspondence, recital transcripts,
photographs, awards and trophies, along with programs relating to
his musical career. All of this is to go into the school's Horowitz
archives, established Aug. 14, 1987.
   A longtime employee of the Horowitzes, Giuliana B. Lopes of
Queens, was left $200,000. Horowitz described her as ``my friend
and companion.''
