<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-A-7Corsair     11-10 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-A-7 Corsair,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>A-7 Corsairs Have Long Combat History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Military Jet Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY65 of Nov. 9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A-7 Corsair attack jets like the one that
exploded in air and crashed into an apartment complex Thursday
night have been part of the U.S. arsenal since 1965.
   The subsonic, single-engine aircraft has been used for a variety
of bombing missions on land and at sea, and was part of the
American air armada in the Vietnam War.
   The single-seat A-7E, the version of the aircraft that went down
in this north Atlanta suburb, has a 20mm gun and can carry up to
15,000 pounds of bombs and missiles. It was built by LTV Corp.
   The first version of the Corsair, the A-7A, made its initial
flight on Sept. 27, 1965, according to Jane's All The World's
Aircraft. It has been extensively modernized over the years,
particularly in the areas of flight control, navigation and
targeting equipment.
   Corsair IIs were part of the two-carrier battle group that
conducted a strike on Libyan terrorist-related targets in 1986.
A-7Es and FA-18s used anti-radar missiles to neutralize air
defenses.
   The airplane has also been used by the Greek and Portuguese air
forces.
   Two years ago, a crippled A-7D Corsair slammed into the lobby of
the Ramada Inn-Airport in Indianapolis, killing 10 people.
   The Air Force fighter was making an aborted emergency landing
attempt on Oct. 20, 1987, when it crashed into the hotel 1{ miles
from the runway moments after the pilot ejected.
   Maintenance records show that the A-7D had numerous oil system
problems in the month before the 1987 crash. The plane had been
brought in twice for dead-stick landings when its engine shut down
in midair.
   Pilots who were interviewed after that crash said the plane is
noted for its bombing accuracy, but also for unfortunate
aerodynamics.
   ``It's not an easy plane to fly,'' one Navy pilot said at the
time. ``It's underpowered to begin with and if you lose the engine,
there's not much glide left in the old bird.
   ``This is a seat bolted to a jet engine and without power,
you've got the aerodynamics of a rock. We used to joke that if you
got in trouble, you'd drop three feet for every foot you moved
forward.''
   LTV no longer produces the plane, but the company received a
contract from the Air Force in 1987 to rebuild two A-7s into ``A-7
Plus'' aircraft that would incorporate a stretched fuselage, a new
engine that would give it supersonic capability and aerodynamic
improvements.
   The Air Force would ultimately like to rebuild many of its A-7s
to the new Plus configuration, extending the planes' life into the
next century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
