<HEAD>TV Show Inspires Young Bomb-Makers; Accident Takes Fingers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two youths inspired by a television show
created a bomb using a shotgun shell and a pipe, and both lost
fingers when the device exploded in their hands, police said.
   ``They told us they'd watched that show `MacGyver' recently and
they wanted to try and build one like they'd seen on there and set
it off in a field,'' state trooper S.A. Lawrence said.
   Kenneth Price, 19, and Mark Paul, 11, were in fair condition at
Charleston Area Medical Center's Women &amp; Children's Hospital,
nursing supervisor Darla Brumfield said Thursday. Price also
received facial burns in Wednesday's accident.
   Paul's father, Edward, drove the boys to the hospital, said
Lawrence.
   The youths removed the shell's pellets and powder and placed the
material inside the pipe. They set off the explosion by drilling a
hole in the pipe to try to make room for a fuse, Lawrence said.
   ABC-TV's ``MacGyver'' stars Richard Dean Anderson as someone who
outwits criminals with his scientific knowledge, including by
fashioning explosives out of everyday materials.
   Calls to the network's office in Los Angeles went unanswered,
and a receptionist at its New York offices said no one was
available to comment Thursday night.
