<HEAD>Even East German Guards Put on Party Faces</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Change is coming even to East Germany's once-dour
guards at the Berlin Wall, who are better known for blocking trips
to the West _ sometimes with gunfire _ than for ushering people
across the border.
   ``The sun is shining, and the people are in a good mood,'' said
a smiling, husky East German guard this morning at the
Invalidenstrasse crossing of the Berlin Wall.
   East German authorities opened the crossings and other borders
to the West Thursday after weeks of pro-democracy protests and a
mass flight of refugees to West Germany.
   Today, the East German guard stood shoulder-to-shoulder with a
West Berlin police officer.
   Both tried good-naturedly, if unsuccessfully, to control the
crowd of West Berliners who gathered at the checkpoint to greet
newcomers from East Berlin.
   Throughout East Berlin, there were reports that border guards
were putting aside their forbidding demeanor in favor of a more
friendly look.
