<FIRST>r a PM-Teacher-Marijuana     11-10 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teacher-Marijuana,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia State Board Upholds Firing of Teacher of Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Education upheld the dismissal
of an award-winning teacher even though she was acquitted of
charges stemming from the discovery of marijuana growing on
property she shared with her husband.
   The board said Vicki Sherling's immorality could be inferred
without proof of criminal purpose or intent.
   The state board voted 4-3 Thursday to uphold Colquitt County's
decision not to reinstate Mrs. Sherling, who was fired in May. The
local board contended there was sufficient evidence to conclude
that Mrs. Sherling at least knew her husband had possessed
marijuana.
   Mrs. Sherling, who was named 1989 Teacher of the Year in the
south Georgia county, was arrested with her husband, Michael, after
marijuana plants were found in a makeshift greenhouse in their back
yard in May.
   A test detected no trace of marijuana in her blood, and her
husband, who was sentenced to three years prison after pleading
guilty to possessing and manufacturing marijuana, testified that
Mrs. Sherling had no knowledge of the plants.
   Attorney William Norwood said Mrs. Sherling will file a lawsuit
in Colquitt County to appeal the state board's decision, and he may
file a federal case charging civil rights violations. He did not
elaborate.
   The board's action does not revoke Mrs. Sherling's teaching
certificate, and she remains eligible to teach in any Georgia
district that will hire her.
   The Georgia Association of Educators backed Mrs. Sherling,
paying legal fees for her appeal.
</TEXT>
