<HEAD>Mild Weather Over Much of Nation; Alaska Freezes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mild and pleasant weather was expected to settle over much of
the lower 48 states this weekend, replacing a week of stormy
weather from the Gulf Coast to the Midwest. Alaska's deep freeze,
though, was expected to stay put.
   Bitter, cold air across Alaska's interior dropped temperatures
Thursday to minus 39 in Fairbanks and minus 51 in Nenana. A high
pressure system was forecast to continue to build into the first
part of the weekend. Forecasters said the cold air wasn't expected
to move south soon.
   On Thursday, unseasonably warm temperatures hovered over the
Northwest and Florida. Record highs included Lewiston, Idaho, with
66 degrees, and Hollywood, Fla., 90. In Montana, two record highs
were tied: Billings, 65 degrees, and Helena, 62.
   Temperatures were cool across the Atlantic states, with
temperatures early today in the 30s and 40s from the mid-Atlantic
states to New England; over the weekend temperatures were expected
in the 40s to the 60s.
   The high temperature for the nation Thursday was 91 degrees at
the North Dade County Airport near Miami.
   Reports at 4 a.m. EST today:
   _EAST: Albany, N.Y., fair; Atlanta 44 fair; Boston 44 fair;
Buffalo 38; Charleston, S.C., 50 fair; Chattanooga 49 fair;
