<FIRST>r a PM-MargarineHeiress-Cocaine     11-10 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Margarine Heiress-Cocaine,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Margarine Heiress, Colombian Found Guilty Of Distributing Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heiress of a margarine fortune and her
Colombian co-defendant were convicted of cocaine distribution and
conspiracy and face a maximum sentence of life in prison.
   Prosecutors said Sandra Filbert Amos, the granddaughter of the
founder of Mrs. Filbert's Margarine, helped her live-in boyfriend
set up the drug ring because she loved him and wanted to overcome
his feeling that the disparity in their incomes harmed their
relationship.
   Sentencing, ironically, was sent for Valentine's Day, Feb. 14.
   ``She cut a pretty sympathetic figure with the jury,''
prosecutor Breckenridge Willcox said. ``She's young, she's
attractive, she's an heiress, if you will, so this was not someone
we assumed we were going to have a slam-dunk case on.''
   Also convicted Thursday was Guillermo Moran, a Colombian living
in New York City. Amos' boyfriend, Jeremiah Dennis Case, had
already pleaded guilty to drug charges and is awaiting sentencing.
   Amos and Moran each were convicted of two counts of distribution
of cocaine and one count of conspiracy to distribute more than five
kilograms of cocaine.
   Amos, 35, who inherited $2 million of the Mrs. Filbert's
fortune, was accused of participating in a distribution ring that
operated out of her home on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
   Defense attorney Russell White argued that Amos was guilty only
of cocaine possession, spending as much as $2,000 a week to support
her drug habit.
   The conspiracy charge carries a minimum sentence of 10 years,
but prosecutor Lisa Griffin said the sentence could be lightened
depending on Amos' knowledge of the size of the distribution ring.
</TEXT>
