<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Bases     11-10 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Bases,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Rally at U.S. Embassy in Manila</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-wielding police today drove
hundreds of protesters from the U.S. Embassy, where they were
demanding the closing of U.S. military bases. At least two people
were injured.
   Protesters carried placards denouncing President Corazon
Aquino's meeting Thursday in Washington with President Bush.
   ``President Aquino's meeting with Bush is a sign of her
treacherous selling of her country's sovereignty in exchange for
the bases,'' said Philip Hernandez, a union official who spoke at
the Manila rally.
   Police initially stood by as about 100 militant workers
protested in front of the embassy to demand the six U.S. bases be
closed.
   However, when about 500 marchers led by the League of Filipino
Students arrived to join the protest, police arrested student
leader Nathaniel Santiago.
   The students began hurling stones, and police fired warning
shots in the air. They then charged the group, scattering
protesters into sidestreets.
   At least one photographer and a policeman were injured by flying
stones.
   In Olongapo, home of the U.S.-run Subic Bay naval base,
thousands of residents turned out today to show support for
maintaining the bases after their lease expires in September 1991.
   The demonstration took place as two Philippines Senate
committees held a joint hearing in Olongapo, 50 miles west of
Manila, on the future of the bases.
   U.S. and Filipino negotiators are expected to begin talks in
Manila next month on extending the lease. Any agreement must be
approved by two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition is
strong.
   Olongapo, with a population of about 50,000, depends on Subic
Bay for its economic livelihood. During the Senate hearing,
speakers argued for keeping the bases because of their economic
benefits.
   U.S. officials say the facilties pump about $1 billion a year
into the Philippine economy through salaries, purchases of local
supplies and spending by the 40,000 U.S. troops, civilians and
military dependents.
</TEXT>
