<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-10 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied in European trading today
while traders debated the impact of East Germany's decision to
permit free travel for its citizens.
   Gold was slightly lower in quiet trading.
   The immediate impact of German developments, said Peter Kane,
chief corporate dealer at Credit Suisse in London, was to create
uncertainty about the consequences for the West German economy and
thus undermine the Deutsche mark.
   ``Where there is uncertainty, there tends to be weakness,'' Kane
said.
   Analysts said a flood of East Germans into West Germany would
have a mixed impact, raising unemployment but perhaps easing
pressure on inflation as new arrivals accept lower wages.
   ``It may take months or years for problems to show through,''
said Chris Furness of Hill, Samuel &amp; Co. Ltd. in London. ``What
still is unclear is if any other of the major countries is going to
do any better.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed Friday at 142.75 yen, barely changed
from Thursday's close of 142.70. Later in London, the dollar traded
at 142.78 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8524 West German marks, up from 1.8475
   _1.6255 Swiss francs, up from 1.6212
   _6.2825 French francs, up from 6.2545
   _2.0913 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815
   _1,352.75 Italian lire, up from 1,351.50
   _1.1680 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1675
   In London, the pound sterling traded at $1.5850, down from
$1.5863 late Thursday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommend price of
$386.45 bid per troy ounce this morning, up from $386.25 a troy
ounce late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $386.40 per troy ounce at noon today,
down from $387.30 bid late Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong closed at $386.24 today, down 48 cents from
late Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded at $5.27 bid per ounce, retreating from a
four-month high of $5.33 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
