<FIRST>r a PM-BridgesTrial     11-10 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridges Trial,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mistrial Declared Over Remaining Assault Charge Against Actor Todd
Bridges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Todd Bridges, acquitted this week of
attempted murder in the shooting of a drug dealer, left jail for
the first time since February after a mistrial was declared on the
lone assault charge facing him.
   Bridges, best known for his role in the former NBC-TV series
``Diff'rent Strokes,'' was released from jail on $25,000 bail
Thursday after the jury could not reach a unanimous verdict on the
charge of assault with a deadly weapon.
   Bridges, 24, was acquitted of attempted murder and attempted
voluntary manslaughter Tuesday.
   He had been in custody since his arrest in early February,
accused in the close-range shooting of Kenneth ``Tex'' Clay, a drug
dealer's henchman working out of a Los Angeles house where crack
cocaine was peddled.
   Clay survived the attack and testified that Bridges was highly
intoxicated the night of the shooting. Bridges said in tearful
testimony he had been on a four-day cocaine binge at the time and
did not remember pulling the trigger.
   Superior Court Commissioner Florence-Marie Cooper declared the
mistrial after jurors announced they remained deadlocked 8-4 in
favor of acquittal.
   Bridges ``was gratified, real pleased,'' defense attorney
Johnnie L. Cochran Jr. said Thursday. ``He just wanted to get out.
He wants to put his life back together.''
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney William Hodgman, said
he was surprised and disappointed by the acquittals and mistrial.
He said the district attorney's office likely will decide next week
whether to retry Bridges on the assault charge.
   Juror Maxine Hall said ``it was a sloppy case'' and that Bridges
``never should have been charged with attempted murder. There was
no problem finding him not guilty of attempted murder at all.''
   The prosecution had argued that Bridges shot Clay eight times at
close range in a dispute over the actor's BMW automobile.
   Clay denied he had stolen the car in his testimony during
Bridges' preliminary hearing but reversed himself during the trial.
   Cochran characterized Bridges as ``a babe in the woods'' out of
his element in the mean streets of South Central Los Angeles, and
said the actor had fired in self-defense.
</TEXT>
