<FIRST>r a PM-Drownings     11-10 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drownings,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Killing His Children Allegedly Tried to Blow up House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with drowning his four children by
driving his car into the Detroit River admitted trying to blow up
his home in 1982 while his wife and infant son slept, the
prosecutor said.
   A motion filed by the Wayne County prosecutor's office alleges
that Lawrence DeLisle of Lincoln Park admitted lighting a candle
next to a dryer that was leaking gas in the basement of the
family's town house in Taylor in an attempt to kill his family. The
gas did not ignite.
   DeLisle, 29, faces first-degree murder charges in the drowning
deaths of his four children; Bryan, 8, who was a baby at the time
of the drying incident; Melissa 4; Kathryn, 2; and Emily, 9 months.
The children were trapped inside the family station wagon when it
plunged into the Detroit River on Aug. 3.
   DeLisle's wife, Suzanne, 32, was in the car but survived. He
also faces a charge of attempted murder.
   DeLisle originally claimed that a leg cramp was responsible for
the accident. Under police questioning he later said he
deliberately drove into the river, but then he recanted that
confession and said police obtained it by duress.
   Defense attorney Frank Eaman said he will try to prevent
DeLisle's statement about the dryer from being used in the case,
saying the incident isn't pertinent. He maintains that statement
also was coerced by police.
   A hearing on the motion to have the dryer incident admitted as
evidence is scheduled for Dec. 8. DeLisle's trial is scheduled to
begin Jan. 16.
   Mrs. DeLisle has maintained her husband's innocence.
</TEXT>
