<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany-Charlie     11-10 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Charlie,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Rush to Checkpoint Charlie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of East Germans converged on Checkpoint
Charlie today to cross through the Berlin Wall to the West for the
first time in their lives.
   Tens of thousands more virtually stormed police stations across
the country to get the visas that will take them West. But West
German news media quoted some travelers as saying they found that
formal visas weren't even necessary to join the wave of visitors to
the West.
   ``Can't take it in,'' muttered Helmut Imhof as he stood in line
at Checkpoint Charlie for a visa that would take him to West Berlin
through the weekend. Communist authorities on Thursday began
allowing citizens to travel freely to the West for the first time
since the wall was erected in 1961.
   ``I've worked right here next to the Wall for 20 years,'' Imhof
said, jerking a thumb in the direction of East Berlin. ``You looked
across once in a while. But the fact that we can go through, it's
just unbelievable.''
   On the Western side of the Wall, East German construction
workers still wearing their work overalls and hard hats drank beer
and toasted their first experience of West Berlin, watched by about
200 curious Westerners and immortalized by a host of photographers.
   Back in the East, more hard-hatted workers filled out the
uncomplicated forms that guaranteed them a brief visit to West
Berlin.
   ``Everybody wanted to go so we decided to do it in shifts,''
said a young worker who declined to give his name. ``But we're
still fulfilling our quota of work,'' he assured a reporter.
   The crowd waiting to go across included three Soviets, who said
they missed the chance to go through Thursday when the news broke.
   ``But we must try now. Just to see it once,'' said a Russian
worker who said he lived in East Berlin but declined to give his
name.
   Rene, a 20-year-old factory worker who declined to give his last
name, was one of the uncounted tens of thousands who surged across
to West Berlin without waiting for the official visa on Thursday
night.
   ``I think it's simply great,'' he said on East Berlin's
Leipziger Strasse this morning just after getting the stamp that
will allow him unlimited trips to West Berlin for six months.
   ``I was over there for an hour last night,'' he said. ``I didn't
see much, it was dark. But the way the people greeted us _ that was
wonderful. And I saw enough to know that it's something quite
different over there. It's a once-in-a-lifetime feeling.''
   At one East Berlin police station, about 3,000 people were
waiting for the new visas by the time the police station opened at
8 a.m., witnesses reported.
   Police stations were ordered to remain open through the weekend
to cope with the crowds, the official news agency ADN said.
   At the Checkpoint Charlie, the famed spot where East and West
have exchanged spies for nearly three decades, as well as the
Invalidenstrasse and Bornholmer Strasse crossings into West Berlin,
people were being waved through after simply filling out a form for
a one-day visit. Some didn't even have to do that.
   Neither West Berlin nor East Berlin authorities had any real
idea of how many tens of thousands of East Berliners into West
Berlin Thursday night and early today in a delirious, spontaneous
outburst of joy. However, the Sender Freies Berlin radio station
estimated the number at more than 50,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
