<DOCNO> AP891110-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-EastEurope-Glance     11-10 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-East Europe-Glance,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Year of Upheaval in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the tumultuous year in East Europe, where
governments and their citizens are grappling with the wave of
reforms unleashed by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLAND:
   The Communists began negotiating with the outlawed Solidarity
trade union in February to halt labor unrest and enlist the
opposition group's help in instituting austerity measures. On April
17, the Communist government grants Solidarity legal status and
allows limited opposition participation in elections. Solidarity
wins virtually every seat it is allowed to seek, then puts together
a legislative majority with two minor parties that were once
thought to be puppets of the ruling Communists.
   The Communists are unable to form a legislative majority or a
government. On Aug. 18, Communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski
approves the concept of a Solidarity-led government. A week later,
Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a former Solidarity activist, becomes the first
non-Communist prime minister of a Soviet bloc nation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA:
   Although it has the highest standard of living in the East bloc,
the Communist government is among the most resistant to
Soviet-style reforms. The government jails playwright and activist
Vaclav Havel, freeing him four months later after worldwide
condemnation. Police attack demonstrators in January. They launched
a similar assault on demonstrators in August during a rally marking
the Soviet-led invasion of 1968, which crushed the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms that presaged Gorbachev's own initiatives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION:
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who fathered the reforms sweeping the East
bloc when he came to power in 1985, turns inward to settle a series
of ethnic disputes and labor unrest spurred by his tolerance of
dissent. Ethnic clashes between Armenians and Azerbaijans, strikes
in key mining regions and nationalist movements in the Baltic
republics threaten Gorbachev's ability to improve the nation's
economy.
   Gorbachev, however, proceeds with major political reforms that
include the creation of a new, stronger and more vocal Parliament.
Citizens vent their displeasure with the Communist old guard by
voting out scores of Communists in the Soviet's first competitive
elections. Dissident physicist Andrei Sakharov is among government
critics elected to a place in the new legislature.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HUNGARY:
   Politburo reformer Imre Poszgay stuns the nation by calling the
1956 revolt against Soviet rule a ``popular uprising'' rather than
a counterrevolutionary revolt. After a remarkable series of
soul-searching meetings in February, the Communist Party endorses
democratic elections.
   In May, Hungary begins removing border fortifications with
Austria to symbolize its quest for close economic and political
ties with its capitalist neighbors. What transpires is an abrupt
deluge of citizens from East Germany who have been looking for a
quick and easy way to West Germany. On Oct. 7, Hungary's Communist
Party dissolves itself at a historic meeting, then reconstitutes
itself as the Hungarian Socialist Party, espousing democratic
ideals in a bid to do well in next year's democratic elections.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BULGARIA:
   The nation Todor Zhivkov has led for 34 years has been slow to
embrace change. Human rights abuses and police repression are
reported with increasing frequency as dissidents grow bolder. Last
week, about 9,000 people gathered in the capital, Sofia, in the
first known pro-democracy rally in the country's Communist history.
Witnesses said the demonstrators chanted ``democracy'' and
``glasnost,'' Gorbachev's word for his policies of greater openness.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY:
   Hard-line leader Erich Honecker, in power for 18 years,
denounces the Soviet-style reforms embraced in Poland and Hungary.
But Hungary's decision to open its border to Austria triggers a
flood of tens of thousands of East Germans heading to West Germany,
where they are granted automatic citizenship. Hundreds of thousands
of others begin holding demonstrations demanding free elections and
unrestricted travel. Honecker begins loosening reins on his rigidly
controlled society, and on Oct. 18 steps down.
   He is replaced by Egon Krenz, who, though also considered a
hard-liner, tries to placate the unruly masses and stop the
hemorrhaging of emigres at its borders. Krenz holds talks in Moscow
with Gorbachev and announces East Germany has much to learn from
Kremlin-style reforms. He says on Nov. 3 that he would support a
law ensuring free and democratic elections, then completely throws
open the borders to the West _ in essence eliminating the reason
for the 28-year-old Berlin Wall.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ROMANIA:
   President Nicolae Ceausescu rules so harshly that any opposition
is crushed at the outset. Romania remains the most repressive of
the Warsaw Pact nations. Ceausescu's efforts to rid the nation of
its foreign debt has left it financially strapped. Huge food and
power shortages are the norm. Last week, Ceausescu fired the
planning chief of the state-run economy. At one point this year,
Ceausescu suggested the Warsaw Pact military alliance block the
Solidarity takeover in Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     11-10 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Appears Still Powerful At Meeting With Kissinger; Zhao Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deng Xiaoping met former U.S. Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger among the official trappings of the Great Hall of
the People today, a day after he announced his retirement from his
last party post.
   Deng on Thursday gave up his last official job as chairman of
the Communist Party's Central Military Commission.
   The 85-year-old Deng today noted with a hearty laugh that
Kissinger was the first foreign guest he had met since retirement,
but he said he will continue to play his ``dual role'' as citizen
and party member.
   The meeting at Beijing's Great Hall, the seat of government,
reinforced the general feeling that Deng will remain dominant,
though he no longer holds official titles.
   After Deng made reference to his retirement, Kissinger said:
``You will never be without great influence.''
   ``Are you opposed to it?'' Deng asked.
   ``I am for it,'' Kissinger said.
   Deng commented that Kissinger is no longer secretary of state
``yet you are still busy working in international affairs.''
   Kissinger is making what is believed to be his 15th trip to
China since a secret visit in 1971 that set the stage for
normalization of relations with the United States.
   Deng referred to his advanced age and his stutter but said he
was ``quite healthy,'' adding, ``My mind is quite clear.''
   He was replaced on the military body by Jiang Zemin, Communist
Party chief.
   Former Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang continued to be
pilloried in the official press even while a just-concluded party
meeting refrained from further attacks on the once-powerful
reformer.
   This week's edition of the Newspaper-Magazine Digest, a weekly
review of the official press, accused Zhao of ``violent treachery''
in the 1988 demise of the party ideological magazine ``Red Flag.''
   Zhao, 70, was purged from all his party posts on June 24 at a
party Central Committee meeting that accused him of supporting the
pro-democracy demonstrations crushed by the military earlier that
month.
   Zhao, believed to be under house arrest, has been under constant
attack since then and there has been speculation he might face
criminal charges.
   However, the party Central Committee, in a communique issued
Thursday, failed to mention the former party chief, indicating
either that the Zhao case has been put to rest or party leaders
were unable to agree on how to deal with him.
   Jiang said in an interview with Japan's Jiji Press today that an
investigation into Zhao's actions has not been completed and as a
result his case had not been taken up at the party meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany-Chronology 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0415,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recent Events in East Germany Political Upheaval</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS today's developments.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major events in East Germany during nearly three
weeks of unprecedented political and social upheaval:
   Oct. 18 _ Hard-line Communist Party leader Erich Honecker, who
supervised the building of the Berlin Wall in 1961, is replaced by
Egon Krenz after 18 years in power. Two other members of the ruling
Politburo are fired.
   Oct. 23 _ About 300,000 people march for democratic reforms in
Leipzig.
   Oct. 24 _ Krenz is installed as head of state and chief of the
military. Demonstrators in East Berlin take to the streets to
demand free elections and to protest Krenz's uncontested candidacy.
   Oct. 26 _ Politburo member Guenter Schabowski meets with two
leaders of the New Forum in the first contact between the
government and the opposition.
   Oct. 27 _ Krenz announces a general amnesty for those convicted
of fleeing to the West and appeals to East Germans to return home.
He promises a new law will be drafted to allow East Germans greater
freedom of travel to the West.
   Oct. 30 _ Hundreds of thousands hold rallies in cities around
the country.
   Nov. 1 _ Krenz holds talks in Moscow with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and announces East Germany has much to learn from
Kremlin_style reforms.
   Nov. 3 _ East German officials announce that East Germans who
want to go West can do so over the Czechoslovak frontier, spurring
a new surge in a 2-month-old exodus. Krenz announces five more
hard-line Politburo members will be fired.
   Nov. 4 _ About 1 million protesters jam East Berlin in the
largest pro-reform rally in the nation's 40-year history.
   Monday _ More than 750,000 people stage pro-reform rallies
across the nation. There are rising calls within the Communist
Party for sweeping top-level changes. Government publishes draft of
a travel law that would allow 30 days of travel abroad every year.
   Tuesday _ East Germany's 44-member Council of Ministers
announces its resignation. The travel law draft is rejected by a
key parliamentary committee as too narrow and restrictive. West
German officials say more than 33,000 East Germans arrive since the
route through Czechoslovakia was opened.
   Wednesday _ The Communist Party's ruling Politburo resigns. The
21-member body is replaced by an 11-member Politburo featuring four
new members, including reformers. About 40,000 people demonstrate
in East Berlin for free elections and an end to one-party rule.
Interior Ministry accepts application by the main opposition group,
New Forum, to register as a legal organization. West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl offers aid to East Germany in exchange for
democratic reforms and changes in its state-planned economy.
   Thursday _ West German officials say more than 50,000 East
Germans have arrived through Czechoslovakia since Nov 4. Krenz
proposes free and democratic elections. East Germany throws open
its borders to the West and thousands swarm across the Berlin Wall
in a mass celebration of their newly won freedom.
   Today _ Kohl cuts short trip to Poland and heads for West
Berlin. East Germans continue to pour into the West, many for
one-day visits, and celebrate the border openings. Ruling Communist
Politburo sacks one of its new members.
