<FIRST>r w PM-Republicans-Ravenel 1stLd-Writethru a0435 11-10 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Republicans-Ravenel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Give Angry Colleague Committee Seat He Demanded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs to explain that Ravenel had difficulty getting
on the committee because the senior GOP member of the panel was blocking
his appointment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disgruntled House Republican from South
Carolina is going to get a seat on the Merchant Marine and
Fisheries Committee after saying he could ``just as easily be a
Democrat.''
   Rep. Arthur Ravenel of South Carolina insisted he had not
actually threatened to bolt his party. But GOP Chairman Lee Atwater
and House Republican leaders got him on the panel anyway.
   House Republican leaders Bob Michel of Illinois and Newt
Gingrich of Georgia, after consulting with Atwater, hurriedly
arranged Ravenel's appointment Thursday.
   The behind-the-scenes jockeying took place after the State
newspaper in Columbia, S.C., quoted unidentified sources as saying
Ravenel felt out of step with his party and was considering
crossing over to the Democrats.
   But what had been irking Ravenel was his inability to get on the
committee he called ``extremely important to the health and wealth
of the 1st Congressional District'' of South Carolina.
   Atwater is a native of South Carolina and congressional sources
said Ravenel's defection could have proved embarrassing to him. GOP
spokeswoman Leslie Goodman said the party chairman discussed the
problem at breakfast Thursday with Ravenel and Gingrich.
   Atwater, who has known Ravenel since he was a volunteer for
Ravenel's mayoral candidacy in Charleston in 1970, said he spoke
with Gingrich and Michel about the seat for Ravenel.
   ``It was those two who lobbied and got the votes on the
committee,'' said Atwater, adding ``it makes sense'' to have a
congressman from the coastal city of Charleston on the committee.
   Earlier Thursday, Ravenel had dismissed speculation in his home
state that he was prepared to leave the GOP.
   ``If I was going to switch parties, I would hold a press
conference and I would tell the people at home I was switching
parties and why,'' the lawmaker said. ``I wouldn't make a switch
unless I had a compelling reason.''
   In an interview earlier this week, Ravenel said he had been
criticized by conservatives in South Carolina for his recent
support of funding for abortion in cases of incest or rape and for
backing some spending measures.
   ``I'm just not a right-winger. I'm a moderate, and it just
drives some of the Republicans back home up the wall,'' Ravenel was
quoted as saying. ``I could just as easily be a Democrat as a
Republican.''
   But Ravenel said Thursday those comments were nothing new and
``that's a lot of old stuff I've been saying for a long time.''
   Michel and Gingrich had to lobby Rep. Don Young of Alaska, the
senior Republican on the Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee,
to remove his objections to Ravenel's joining the panel.
   Ravenel had said Young was blocking his appointment because he
opposed Young's stance in favor of opening the Alaska National
Wildlife Refuge to oil exploration.
   C.J. Zane, Young's administrative assistant, confirmed that
Young fought Ravenel's appointment because Ravenel refused to
pledge to support Young's position on the Alaska National Wildlife
Refuge issue.
   Zane said Young ``went along'' with the requests of the party
leadership to seat Ravenel out of concern for party unity.
   ``There was a big push from Michel and other Republicans,
including Atwater, because they didn't want to deal with losing a
guy to another party at this time,'' the aide said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
