<HEAD>City Mourns Death Of Fatal Shooting Victim's 2-Week-Old Son</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast. Picks up 3rd graf, `Dr. Steven...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boy born two months premature after his mother
was fatally shot by a robber has died at the age of 2 weeks,
officials said.
   ``It's a tragedy for a mother and a baby and it's a tragedy for
all the families of innocent victims who have suffered violence in
our society,'' Mayor Raymond Flynn said after Christopher Stuart's
death Thursday afternoon at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
   Dr. Steven Ringer, head of the hospital's neonatal intensive
care unit, said the infant died of respiratory failure from his
premature and traumatic birth.
   The baby had been in intensive care since his delivery by
emergency Caesarean section shortly after his mother, Carol Stuart,
was shot Oct. 23.
   Charles Stuart, 29, who was critically wounded in the attack,
was brought by ambulance from Boston City Hospital to be at his
son's bedside along with family members.
   Mrs. Stuart, 30, who was seven months pregnant, was shot and
killed by a gunman who held up the couple in their car after they
left Brigham and Women's Hospital.
   ``Everybody in the city of Boston was really praying beyond hope
that Christopher would make it,'' Flynn said.
   But family members said the baby, who was delivered two months
prematurely, may have suffered serious brain damage. He weighed 3
pounds, 13 ounces at birth and had neither grown nor gained weight.
   The infant had been on a life-support system and suffered
repeated convulsions since birth, family members said.
   The assailant in the case is still at large.
</TEXT>
