<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     11-10 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three White Guerrillas Go to Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three whites who proudly
admitted to being guerrillas of the African National Congress were
sentenced on terrorism charges today to prison terms of up to 25
years.
   Supporters in the courtroom threw yellow daisies at the
defendants when the sentence was announced. One defendant, Iain
Robertson, yelled, ``Long Live The ANC!'' as police pulled him away.
   The two men and one woman acknowledged they were from the
military wing of the predominantly black movement, which has waged
a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961 to end white rule and
apartheid.
   They were arrested in May 1988 at a farmhouse outside
Johannesburg where police seized a large cache of Soviet-made
weapons. It included a SAM-7 missile, hand grenades, mortar bombs,
assault rifles and pistols, and was described as one of the largest
caches ever seized in South Africa.
   Damian de Lange, 31, a former journalist and leader of the cell,
was sentenced today to 25 years in prison. Robertson, 35, received
a 20-year sentence and Susan Westcott, 25, a native of Swaziland
whose parents are British, was sentenced to 18 years.
   Magistrate W.J. van den Bergh, in issuing the sentences, said
the defendants ``were indifferent to loss of life.
   ``They are entitled to their own political views and beliefs. It
is their transgressions of the law that must be punished,'' he said.
   The Human Rights Commission, an independent anti-apartheid
monitoring group, condemned the sentences as harsh and said
apartheid was to blame for the ANC's decision to use violence.
   David Soggott, the defense attorney, said an appeal might be
filed.
   Ms. Westcott's mother, Margaret Westcott, said afterwards: ``We
stand by our daughter _ she's done a very brave thing for this
country.''
   The chief prosecutor, Frans Roets, had asked for sentences of
125 years for de Lange, 110 years for Robertson and 90 years for
Ms. Westcott.
   ``They wanted to intimidate the population with cowardly
attacks,'' Roets said in his summary earlier this week in Pretoria
Regional Court.
   Prosecutors said de Lange detonated a bomb last year that
damaged a bus carrying military personnel to work. No one on the
bus was seriously hurt.
   The three were held in solitary confinement for seven months
after their arrest. They first appeared in court in January, and
all three pleaded guilty to terrorism charges in June.
   Throughout the sentencing procedures, the courtroom gallery was
packed with Arican National Congress supporters. Many wore the
gold, green and black colors of the guerrilla movement.
   One session was attended by Walter Sisulu and three other ANC
leaders who were freed on Oct. 15 after 26 years in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
