<FIRST>r w PM-Iowa-Looting 1stLd-Writethru a0493 11-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa-Looting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailors Tell of Looting Aboard USS Iowa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds last two grafs on Oakar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors on the USS Iowa were looting
possessions while their crewmen battled the explosion in a gun
turret that killed 47 shipmates April 19, a published report says.
   As many as 10 sailors were involved in looting that day,
although their names were withheld from their shipmates for fear of
reprisals, crew members told The Washington Times in a story
published in today's editions.
   The Navy has denied that any looting took place while crew
members were fighting the fire in gun turret No. 2.
   ``It is absolutely false,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Craig Quigley, a Navy
spokesman. ``There was nobody caught. There was no break-in. There
was no evidence of looting.'' Quigley said the lockers of the 47
victims were sealed that day and no possessions were taken.
   However, The Times reported it received a letter from an officer
currently assigned to the USS Iowa who was on the battleship the
day of the blast. ``You are correct that there was looting while
the damage control efforts were ongoing on 19 April ...'' the
officer, who was not identified, wrote The Times.
   ``Those who did the looting were punished either at captain's
mast or at special court martial,'' the sailor added.
   Two other sailors also have told The Times they heard while on
board the ship that looting occurred, although they had not
actually witnessed the thefts.
   ``The bad part is they (the looters) tried to break into lockers
of those that were killed,'' said former gunner's mate David James,
who said he was informed of the looting by a master at arms. Two
other former shipmates, who asked not to be identified, confirmed
James' account.
   The Naval Investigative Service in its report on the Iowa
disaster described a locker break-in in the berthing area that
housed those killed in Turret 2.
   The Navy investigation concluded that gunner's mate Clayton
Hartwig of Ohio ``most likely'' caused the April 19 explosion by
inserting some type of detonator between bags of gunpowder in one
of the ship's 16-inch guns.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, said Thursday she is asking Navy
Secretary Lawrence Garrett III to explain why Iowa Capt. Fred P.
Moosally is being made eligible for another major command.
   ``I realize that consideration and possible selection of Capt.
Moosally does not commit the Navy to consider him for sequential
major command, but I question the propriety of such action while
there are several congressional and Navy investigations ongoing,''
Oakar said.
</TEXT>
