<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionRallies     11-10 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rallies,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Advocates Plan Protests in Every State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion rights activists plan to stage nearly 1,000 pro-choice
events this weekend _ from a sunrise rally in Maine to a sunset
gathering in California _ to remind lawmakers that limiting
abortion access could be politically harmful.
   ``Since the emphasis in reproductive choice has shifted from the
federal level to the state legislative level, we feel it's
important to have demonstrations in each state,'' said Sally Tyler,
executive director of the Georgia Abortion Rights Action League,
which is planning a demonstration at an Atlanta park.
   Organizers of the campaign, called Mobilize for Women's Lives,
said the demonstrations, panel discussions and other activities in
towns and on college campuses are to remind legislators they
represent the views of the majority of the U.S. public. Abortion
opponents said they would stage counterdemonstrations at some
locations.
   Representatives of both sides said they plan to turn out for
two-block march on the state capitol in Jackson, Miss.
   ``People for choice have been invisible because of legalized
abortion,'' said Brenda Henson, president of Sister Spirit, a
women's resource center in Gulfport, Miss. ``We haven't been
threatened until now. Now we need to stand up and say `We already
fought this battle once, and we won't give up.'''
   Henson was referring to the U.S. Supreme Court decision on July
3 that stopped short of reversing the Roe vs. Wade decision that
legalized most abortions in 1973 but gave states more power to
limit abortions.
   Sunday's events will begin with a sunrise rally in Kennebunk,
Maine, and wind up with a sunset rally in San Francisco. In
Washington, a rally is planned at the Lincoln Memorial in
Washington.
   At some events, pro-choice participants will wear purple
clothing or purple bows, the color of the women's suffrage movement
decades ago.
   Samuel Lee, legislative chairman for Missouri Citizens for Life,
said his group would hold a news conference in the Capitol in
Jefferson City shortly before pro-choice demonstrators were due to
hold a rally outside.
   Asked if the purpose of the conference was to share in the news
coverage, he said, ``I wouldn't deny that at all. It's a
convenience for the media people, too, for us to all be in one
place.''
   It was a case from Missouri that led to the recent Supreme Court
decision.
   India McCanse, an organizer of the pro-choice demostration in
the Missouri Capitol, said the expected turnout of thousands ``will
be significant, because a lot of people in this country have
written off Missouri as being totally anti-choice. We want to
demonstrate that is absolutely wrong.''
</TEXT>
