<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Kohl 3rdLd-Writethru a0506 11-10 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Kohl, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0506,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Cuts Short Polish Visit at German News, Bound for Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with Kohl planning to attend
ceremony in West Berlin; picks up 5th pvs: Hans Klein ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
interrupted his visit to Poland and flew to Berlin after East
Germany's historic decision to open its borders to the West.
   Kohl has said he would like to meet with new East German leader
chief Egon Krenz, but there was no official word on whether such a
session would take place.
   The state PAP news agency reported in a brief dispatch that Kohl
left Warsaw in the early afternoon.
   Other top West German officials planned to join Kohl for a
ceremony in front the Schoeneberg City Hall in West Berlin, the
spot where President John F. Kennedy made his famous ``Ich bin ein
Berliner'' speech in 1963.
   Hans Klein, Kohl's spokesman, told reporters the chancellor
would return to Poland on Saturday to conclude his visit.
   East Berlin announced suddenly Thursday it was opening its
borders and allowing its citizens to leave. Thousands of East
Germans immediately swarmed into West Germany through the open
Berlin Wall and at other crossings.
   Earlier Thursday, Kohl said West Germany ``could be ready to
offer significant economic aid if the will to reform manifested
itself in East Germany.''
   In addition to opening his country's borders, Krenz said the
country would hold democratic elections, but it was not clear if
the elections would include parties competing with the ruling
Communists.
   Kohl also said he had discussed with U.S. officials the
possibility of housing mounting numbers of East German refugees in
U.S. facilities in West Germany.
   His six-day visit here was intended to move the World War II
enemies closer to reconciliation. The developments in East Germany,
however, drew attention away from the economic issues expected to
be the focus of the summit.
   The developments have fueled Polish fears about German
reunification and have forced long-simmering border issues to the
forefront of Kohl's visit.
   ``Creation of a superpower in the heart of Europe is not a
neutral concern for the future of a whole Europe,'' said Polish
deputy goverment spokesman Henryk Wozniakowski.
   ``Certainly Poland is now looking more seriously on the
possibility'' of German reunification, he said.
   Wozniakowski said Poland recognizes the sovereign rights of both
German states, ``but the question of reunification is not just a
German question. It is also a European question,'' he said.
   Combined with Polish fears of a new economic superpower were
worries over recent comments by West German conservatives that
reunification should be sought within the 1937 borders of the
German Reich. Those borders include large areas of what is now
Poland.
   A 1970 treaty between West Germany and Poland recognizes the
Oder and Neisse rivers as the western boundary of Poland, but a
reunified Germany would not be bound to those terms.
   Malgorzata Niezabitowska, spokeswoman for Prime Minister Tadeusz
Masowiecki, said the prime minister ``stressed that Polish people
must have certainty that the question of borders be settled
permanently.''
   Kohl also met with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, the driving
force behind the trade union movement's rise to control of the
government.
   The West German leader came to Poland with a billion-dollar
economic package that is crucial for the new government to make the
difficult transition toward a market-oriented economy.
   Mazowiecki's government has asked for huge amounts of Western
economic aid, saying it is needed to safeguard the transition to
democracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Historic     11-10 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Historic,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Architectural Preservationists Fear Needless Demolitions After Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the beloved Victorian buildings
that give the city its charm are in jeopardy, say preservationists
battling to have the quake-damaged structures repaired instead of
razed.
   Hundreds of the beauties that survived the 1906 quake may not
make it through 1989, the preservationists charged Thursday, saying
city regulations aimed at getting unsafe buildings torn down may
force property owners to take ``precipitous action.''
   Mark Ryser, executive director of the Foundation for San
Francisco's Architectural Heritage, criticized the city's procedure
for inspecting damaged buildings. He spoke at a news conference in
front of Saint Dominic's Church, where workers were removing a
tower damaged in the Oct. 17 quake,
   He said owners are not being given time to consider
rehabilitation in lieu of demolition, and said structural engineers
doing voluntary inspections for the city may lack the expertise to
adequately assess building hazards.
   City officials defended the inspection and notification process.
   ``We haven't torn down that many buildings, only those that pose
an imminent life hazard or are a danger to adjacent property,''
said Public Works Director Richard Evans. ``I'm tired of people
taking potshots at the process, because it's a good process.''
   Although some buildings were razed immediately after the quake,
Deputy Mayor of Housing Brad Paul said recent efforts have focused
on rehabilitation.
   More than 1,400 housing units are in buildings that have been
``red-tagged'' by the city, requiring owners to promptly shore up
or demolish the buildings, Paul said.
   An additional 3,647 units are in buildings with limited access,
he said, adding that total replacement costs are estimated at close
to $200 million.
   Kathryn Burns of the National Trust for Historic Preservation
estimated that up to 500 historic buildings may be threatened in
the seven-county area hit by the quake, which measured 7.1 on the
Richter scale.
   Fewer than 200 buildings in San Francisco are designated
landmarks, but about 2,000 more are in designated historic
districts, said Ryser.
   To help increase options for property owners, the Trust has
established a special low-interest loan program for owners of
quake-damaged historic buildings. The funds would be available to
stabilize buildings while rehabilitation assessments are made, she
said.
   Emergency legislation to prevent the demolition of any buildings
not in imminent danger of collapse was signed by Gov. George
Deukmejian on Monday.
   ``Natural disasters cannot serve as a pretext for rash decisions
to destroy important relics of California history,'' said State
Sen. Milton Marks, who sponsored the legislation.
   Preservationists are worried about residential neighborhood
buildings as well as public buildings.
   As an example, Ryser cited a 1908 building on Front Street that
he said was needlessly razed. Although the front of the building
was a public hazard and had to be removed, the entire structure did
not have to be demolished, he said.
   Unnecessary demolitions may occur because owners are not aware
of rehabilitation options, cannot get qualified engineers to
inspect the property within city-ordered time limits, or believe
demolition is mandatory, Ryser said. He conceded that some owners
may be looking for a ``convenient rationale'' to tear down unwanted
property.
   A new city ordinance allows tenants who fear that landlords are
unfairly trying to remove rental units from the market to call in
an independent structural engineer to assess quake damage, Paul
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
