<FIRST>r i PM-Jordan-Election     11-10 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jordan-Election,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Gain Largest Bloc In Jordan's Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem fundamentalists, many of them
campaigning under the slogan ``Islam is the solution,'' won the
biggest bloc of seats in Parliament during this kingdom's first
general election in 22 years.
   The result was an apparent setback for King Hussein, who urged
voters not to mix religion with politics in Wednesday's vote.
   Fundamentalist candidates captured 34 of the 80 seats in
Parliament, according to results announced Thursday.
   About 20 seats were won by pro-government candidates, while
leftists, Arab nationalists, tribal leaders and others took the
rest. The breakdown gave opposition forces a clear majority over
strict loyalists.
   For the first time, women were allowed to vote and seek office,
but none of the 12 females among the 647 candidates won a seat.
   ``The people want Islam, and it is not strange for our country
and our people to have such a large number of Moslem candidates
winning,'' said Ziad Abu Ghanimeh, a spokesman for the Moslem
Brotherhood, the largest Islamic organization.
   The Brotherhood called for more social welfare programs to help
the poor and for a Palestinian state on Israeli territory.
   Its 26 declared and several undeclared candidates held the
largest rallies in the campaign, including one in Amman attended by
about 5,000 people.
   Though the fundamentalists have often allied themselves with
Hussein, they have also prodded him to embrace a stricter version
of Islam with restrictions on Western-type entertainment, more
social welfare programs and greater separation of the sexes.
   The new Parliament seems certain to be more assertive than the
legislature dissolved last year, although Hussein retains ultimate
power.
   Parliament must approve all laws and can dissolve Cabinets. But
the king can dissolve Parliament and rule without it, and he has
done so for much of the past 15 years.
   The winners included Mansour Murad, who was convicted of
participating in a 1969 attack on an Athens office of the Israeli
state airline El-Al. The attack killed a Greek child and wounded 11
people.
   He was freed in 1970 in an exchange for 55 hostages aboard a
hijacked Olympic Airways jetliner.
   During the campaign, many candidates who went on to win seats
demanded prosecution of former officials accused of corruption and
economic mismanagement.
   The nation has a foreign debt of $8.3 million, and financial
hardship led to four days of rioting in April.
   The election formalized Jordan's separation from the West Bank,
which held half the seats in the Parliament that was elected two
months before Israel captured the territory in 1967.
   Last year, Hussein renounced Jordan's claims to the West Bank in
favor the Palestine Liberation Organization and dissolved
Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
