<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-East Germany, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0522,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Spokesman Welcomes Opening of Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Shevardnadze comment; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet spokesman said today that East Germany's
decision to open its borders was well received in the Soviet Union,
but he reiterated the Kremlin's opposition to reunification of
Germany.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, chief spokesman for the Soviet Foreign
Ministry, called the East German government's throwing open of its
borders ``a sovereign act'' of East Germany, reiterating the
Kremlin's determination not to interfere in the internal affairs of
its East Bloc partners.
   But he reminded Soviet and foreign reporters at a Foreign
Ministry briefing, ``The border still remains, though some might
think it ceased to exist.''
   East Berliners streamed into West Berlin today following joyous
overnight celebrations after East Germany opened its borders.
Thousands of East Germans also crossed into West Germany along the
nations' frontier.
   Gerasimov cited a statement by East German leader Egon Krenz at
a Nov. 1 press conference in Moscow at which Krenz said the border
exists ``due to other reasons'' and not for the purpose of
interfering with contacts between people.
   Krenz pointed out then the Berlin Wall marks the division
between political systems as well as between the military alliances
of East and West.
   Gerasimov said the border opening was part of the ``wide
democratization of life'' taking place in East Germany, where the
recent replacement of hard-line communist leader Erich Honecker
touched off a popular rush toward reform.
   ``These are not separate acts but full-scale measures embracing
the whole of life of the GDR (East Germany) and its contacts with
the outside world,'' the Soviet spokesman said. ``The measures that
have been taken were welcomed'' in East Germany, ``and there was
also a positive reaction abroad, including in the Soviet Union.''
   But Gerasimov said West Germany ``should take into account that
policies aimed at reconsidering borders would not suit any
government in Europe and would cause only mistrust.''
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnandze today also welcomed
the opening of East Germany's border to the West, Swedish
journalists meeting with the envoy in Moscow reported.
   Shevardnadze was quoted as saying the Kremlin had nothing to do
with the decision to open the gates in the Berlin Wall, which he
said was an internal affair.
   ``It was decided by the comrades in Berlin,'' he said. ``This
was a reasonable and sensible decision,'' he said, and he described
the developments as ``a normal process'' toward greater democracy
in East Germany.
   ``The new course in East Germany echos the mood among the people
in East Germany. It also corresponds to our own interests,'' he
said, according to a report by the Swedish national TT news agency
and Swedish Radio in Stockholm.
   Shevardnadze, who met the reporters accompanying Foreign
Minister Sten Andersson, said people should be helped to reunite
with relatives or to travel abroad for other reasons, and said he
was undisturbed by the sight of tens of thousands of East Germans
flooding across the frontiers.
   ``Its not abnormal for people to leave their countries.
Sometimes they return,'' he said. ``Twenty thousand people leave
the Soviet Union every year. That in itself is not unusual.''
   He also said Moscow was not worried that the swift pace of
events in East Europe would threaten global stability.
   The events in East Germany have been covered on Soviet
television and in the press but with little editorial comment.
   Tass, the Soviet news agency, reported the opening of the
borders without delay.
   The Soviet Union in the past two years has eased the strict
control of its borders and now grants thousands of exit visas a
month to Soviet citizens wishing to travel abroad or emigrate. But
relatively few Soviets are eligible to emigrate under present law.
   A bill before the legislature would grant all citizens the right
to come and go as they please _ except in cases when the state
determines national security might be threatened. But the measure
is still up for debate.
</TEXT>
