<FIRST>r a PM-ErieMayor     11-10 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Erie Mayor,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longtime Erie, Pa., Mayor Steps Down Because of Rare Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly a quarter-century in office and
more than two years of battling an incurable disease, Mayor Louis
Tullio is stepping down and has appointed an aide to fill the
remaining seven weeks of his term.
   Aides delivered a letter to the Erie city clerk today saying the
six-term mayor has appointed Patricia Liebel, a longtime assistant,
acting mayor effective immediately.
   ``We'll do the best we can. This is the way the mayor wants
it,'' Ms. Liebel said late Thursday.
   Ms. Liebel, who lost a bid to win the Democratic mayoral
nomination in the May primary, will fill the post only until Dec.
31. Two-term Councilwoman Joyce Savocchio, who was elected mayor
Tuesday in this northwestern Pennsylvania city of 120,000, takes
over then.
   Tullio suffers from amyloidosis, a rare and fatal disease that
deposits proteins in the heart, kidneys and other major organs. The
illness has weakened Tullio's heart and lungs amd confined him to
his home since May. Pittsburgh Mayor Richard Caliguiri died of the
same illnesss in May 1988.
   Over the summer, several City Council members called for Tullio
to appoint an acting mayor because of his illness.
   ``He had held off on naming an acting mayor because he hoped to
return one day to the job he so loved,'' Grace Tullio, the mayor's
wife, said late Thursday. ``But now he wants the work on the budget
and the transition to Joyce Savocchio's administration to go as
smoothly as possible.''
   Tullio technically will continue as mayor, receiving full pay
and benefits, and said he would provide input into matters of city
business.
   Ms. Liebel, who has been Tullio's top aide since he took office
in 1966, was to meet today with Mrs. Savocchio to discuss the
transition.
   ``I promise to work with Pat Liebel and the administration over
the budget in this difficult time for the city,'' said Mrs.
Savocchio, a Democrat.
   Tullio assumed office 24 years ago after defeating incumbent
Republican Mayor Charles Williamson.
</TEXT>
