<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     11-10 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Group Calls for Probe of Soldiers Behavior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN SCHECHET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An civil rights group has asked the army to
investigate reports of soldiers forcing Palestinians to perform
``ridiculous and humiliating tasks'' such as singing army songs and
sweeping the streets.
   The Association for Civil Rights in Israel has asked the army's
legal adviser to stop the ``manifestly illegal'' practice in the
Ein Bet al-Ma refugee camp in the Israeli-occupied West Bank, said
Dan Simon, the group's lawyer.
   ``They force the inhabitants to perform ridiculous and
humiliating tasks such as sweeping streets, washing the streets,
and so forth,'' said Simon.
   ``It's usually done in the middle of the night,'' he said. ``The
people are called out, their ID cards are taken away from them and
returned at the end of the work.''
   Israeli officials said today that a preliminary check indicated
soldiers made residents of the camp clean up rubble from tires set
on fire demonstrators.
   ``There's no initial indication of improper behavior by the
soldiers, but the story is being investigated,'' said an army
spokesman, who by Israeli army regulations cannot be identified.
   Simon said the army legally can force Palestinians to remove
roadblocks put up by demonstrators and to erase graffiti and can
confiscate their identification cards while they do the work.
   But forcing Palestinians to clean streets and pick up cigarette
butts and pebbles is ``manifestly illegal,'' he said. He also
complained that six residents were made to march around the camp
singing an Israeli army song one night last month.
   ``What we expect to hear is what the army is doing to make sure
these things do not reoccur,'' he said.
   Simon said he probably will petition Israel's Supreme Court if
the army does not take action. He said the practices were ``a local
kind of initiative'' and were not widespread.
   Also today, Arab reporters said Israeli soldiers wounded a
12-year-old boy in the Gaza Strip. Army officials said they were
unaware of any such incident.
</TEXT>
