<FIRST>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0486,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Reject Sandinistas' Opening Offer at Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with talks reopening. Pickup 4th
pvs, `Neither proposal...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan rebel leader today spurned a
government proposal for his forces to disband and instead vowed at
the first peace talks in 16 months to ``put an end' to the regime
in Managua.
   Chief Contra negotiator Enrique Bermudez, just before heading
into the second day of talks today, said he had reason to ``doubt
the sincerity'' of the Sandinista offer of a truce and amnesty.
   Bermudez said the Sandinistas did not offer a true amnesty but
merely offered to release political prisoners from jail, stopping
short of restoring their civil and political rights.
   Talks between the U.S.-backed Contra rebels and the Sandinista
government opened Thursday. Nicaragua's foreign minister said
before the talks that if the rebels agreed to demobilize, his
government would meet their demands for a truce and amnesty.
   The Contras countered with a plan to restore the cease-fire with
the government, which was called off last week, and discuss other
conditions _ such as demobilization _ later.
   Neither proposal was accepted, despite the urging of U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to renew the cease-fire
that President Daniel Ortega ended.
   An estimated 12,000 people have been killed in the 8-year-old
war.
   Perez de Cuellar and his Organization of American States
counterpart, Joao Clemente Baena Soares, turned the mediation
effort over to aides.
   An election campaign is under way in Nicaragua under a regional
peace accord signed in August. The plan calls for free and fair
elections.
   Voting is set for Feb. 25, and U.N. observers say the campaign
is proceeding smoothly.
   Foreign Minister Miguel d'Escoto of Nicaragua said before the
meeting that key Contra demands would be met if demobilization
began by the end of November.
   Documents obtained by The Associated Press showed the Contras'
opening position calling for an immediate truce. The Sandinistas
would then declare a amnesty for the rebels by Nov. 20.
   The estimated 12,000 Contras camped in Honduras would then move
into Nicaragua, with their weapons, to join their comrades there in
secure zones.
   Diplomats said this would remove the pressure placed on Honduras
under the Central American peace plan to shut down the Contra camps
by Dec. 5.
   Only after these steps had been completed would discussion of
disbanding the Contras begin, under the rebel proposal.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco, who leads
Nicaragua's delegation to the U.N. meeting, rejected the Contra
proposal as presented.
   D'Escoto, waving a copy of Sandinista proposals, said the
Contras say ``they require three things; the three things are met
by what we are offering.''
   D'Escoto said the Nicaraguan delegation was willing to stay in
New York beyond the two days allotted for the talks and would be
flexible. ``This is a proposal, not an ultimatum,'' he said of the
Sandinista document.
   In Miami, the Contras announced formation of a new
``civilian-military commission'' to replace the old directorate,
several of whose members have resigned and returned to Nicaragua.
   Contra military spokesman Alejandro Acevedo said the U.N.
negotiating team led by Contra military commander Enrique Bermudez
had recognized the new commission, which includes only one of the
former directors, Aristides Sanchez.
   Ousted civilian Contra leaders compared the action to a coup.
   When Bermudez arrived for the U.N. meeting, he said: ``We expect
to re-establish the cease-fire and put an end to the totalitarian
government in Nicaragua.''
   In refusing to renew the cease-fire after 19 weeks, Ortega cited
increased Contra attacks in Nicaragua. Contra leaders denied the
rebels were attacking, which is forbidden by Congress while they
still receive U.S. aid.
   Congress ended U.S. military aid to the Contras in 1988, but has
continued non-lethal aid.
   Honduras, where most of the 12,000 Contras are encamped, and
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo of Managua are attending the peace
talks as observers.
   The last direct talks between the Sandinistas and Contras broke
down in June 1988. They agreed to a 90-day cease-fire during that
session, in March, and Nicaragua had extended it on a monthly
basis, with tacit agreement from the Contras.
</TEXT>
