<DOCNO> AP891110-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Avtex     11-10 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avtex,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plant Accused of Polluting Says Closure Would Hinder Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operators of a rayon plant that supplies
the Pentagon say it must remain open in defiance of the state's
revocation of its waste water discharge permit so that it can clean
up pollutants.
   The State Water Control Board voted 6-0 Thursday to revoke the
permit of Avtex Fibers Inc.'s Front Royal plant effective
immediately. The water board said Avtex violated the permit by
discharging polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, into the Shenandoah
River.
   David A. Tousignant, the plant's president, told reporters an
orderly shutdown of the plant would take months and would halt the
company's efforts to clean up the toxic chemical.
   ``We can't let this happen. It's not in anybody's best
interest,'' he said.
   He maintained that an immediate shutdown is impossible and that
the company could not clean up the PCBs without continuing to
operate Avtex's waste water treatment facility, which discharges
into the river.
   ``If you're not operating, then you have no resources to do
anything,'' he said.
   Avtex lawyers failed to persuade Richmond Circuit Judge Theodore
J. Markow to stay the order and were considering an appeal to the
state's Court of Appeals, which was closed today for Veterans Day.
   Markow is to preside over a trial Wednesday of a state lawsuit
seeking closure of the plant and fines and damages against Avtex.
The permit revocation followed Markow's rejections of two state
requests to close the plant pending the trial.
   The company could be liable for as much as $10,000 a day in
fines for making illegal discharges, said Bert Rohrer, a spokesman
for the state attorney general's office.
   During two days of hearings last week, the attorney general's
office said state testing found as much as 3{ pounds of PCBs
flowing toward the river daily in August. The state said PCBs have
contaminated the plant site since a December 1985 leak of some 500
gallons of the highly toxic oils from an electrical transformer.
   The state has accused Avtex and the federal government of
knowingly allowing the pollution to continue, which Tousignant
denied.
   ``When we found out ourselves that we had a problem, we took
immediate action,'' he said.
   The federal government has worked for years to keep various
pollution and worker safety problems from shutting the more than
50-year-old plant, which is the only supplier of a carbonizable
rayon fiber used in rocket nozzles for the space shuttle and
nuclear missiles.
   Water board members said they were concerned about the nearly
400 employees at Avtex who could lose their jobs, but they were
more worried about the pollution.
   ``This was all brought about by actions and inactions on the
part of Avtex,'' said Donald M. Plotkin, a board member.
   Velma M. Smith, board chairwoman, said the board's investigation
showed Avtex knew it had violated its permit by discharging PCBs
long before it began cleaning up the toxins this year.
   ``Avtex did not take the issuance of a permit seriously,'' she
said.
   The public found out about the pollution in May, when state
officials warned people not to eat fish from the river.
</TEXT>
