<FIRST>r a PM-WallStreet-Fire 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 11-10 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street-Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0546,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Openings Delayed Because of Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf with 2 grafs to add detail on height of
building, quote from the computer-processing company on why operations
were suspended. A version moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening of trading was delayed an hour today
at the New York and American stock exchanges because of a fire
beneath a building that houses a key computer system.
   A spokeswoman at the American Stock Exchange said a fire at the
building housing the Securities Industry Automation Corp. in lower
Manhattan's financial district made it impossible to process
information, delaying the usual 9:30 a.m. opening of stock trading.
   Trading at both the American and New York exchanges finally
opened at 10:30 a.m.
   A Fire Department spokesman said the blaze erupted in an
electrical vault below the building. The first alarm sounded about
8 a.m. and the fire was under control by about 9:45 a.m. It was
extinguished shortly after, the spokesman said. No injuries were
reported.
   The lobby and the second floor of the 53-story building were
evacuated, and some tenants on higher floors lost power. Light
smoke filtered into the building from the fire underneath, the fire
department said.
   John Lafayette, a spokesman for the Securities Industry
Automation Corp., said the fire did not affect trading systems, but
uncertainty about the power supply led the company to suspend
operations and switch to an emergency power source shortly before
stock exchange trading was due to begin.
   The fire disrupted trading in stock index futures at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange and the Chicago Board of Trade, but other
trading went on as scheduled at the two exchanges.
</TEXT>
