<DOCNO> AP891110-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-EastGermany 3rdLd-Writethru a0548 11-10 1280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-East Germany, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0548,1200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lauds East German Lifting of Travel Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts new quotes by Baker, Bush declining questions in top
7 grafs, picking up at pvs 5th graf, Baker acknowledged; inserts one graf
after pvs 12th graf, The White, with no new aid asked or offered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, lauding East Germany's lifting
of travel restrictions as a dramatic advance for freedom, is
ordering ``all possible assistance'' to help West Germany cope with
the flood of refugees from its communist sister state.
   And Secretary of State James A. Baker III, reflecting today on
Thursday's border-opening decree by East German authorities, said
he hoped it would lead to greater freedoms. ``Hopefully, now
they'll move in the area of other freedoms. Hopefully we'll see
movement toward free and open democratic elections,'' he said on
``CBS This Morning.''
   Bush, boarding his helicopter today for a trip to Texas, waved
off questions about the fast-moving developments. Spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said, however, that the president intended to talk to
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl by telephone later today.
   In another TV interview, on ABC's ``Good Morning America,''
Baker said it was premature to talk about the reunification of
Germany because East Germany had a long way to go before becoming
truly democratic.
   ``There are some steps that have to be taken between just giving
people one of the basic human rights, the freedom to travel,
between that and addressing the question of reunification of
Germany,'' he said.
   Baker also linked Western financial aid to East Germany to
greater freedoms, including ``free and open'' elections. ``I think
it's going to be the view, frankly, of some of our other allies
that assistance will be much more forthcoming if the German
Democratic Republic (East Germany) moves toward true reform, in
terms of political pluralism across the board,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, the secretary said, ``I think it's the most
dramatic event in East-West relations since the end of the war.''
   Baker acknowledged that the speed of the East German action
caught U.S. officials off guard.
   ``Were we surprised by the speed of it? You bet your life, and
so was everybody else as far as I can determine,'' he told CBS. ``I
don't know anybody who suggested that they predicted this was going
to happen. It's a very good development. I'm not the least bit
ashamed of saying that the rapidness of it came as somewhat of a
surprise.''
   If East Germany fully implements the promise to open its
borders, Bush told reporters Thursday, ``this (Berlin) Wall built
in '61 will have very little relevance.''
   It was just 6{ months ago in a speech in Mainz, West Germany,
that Bush added his voice to the chorus of U.S. presidents who have
demanded that the Berlin Wall be torn down. He called it then a
``brutal wall'' that ``stands as a monument to the failure of
communism. It must come down!''
   Former President Reagan said on the ABC television show ``Prime
Time Live'' that ``If the wall isn't torn down immediately, at
least they could keep the gates open.''
   East Germany said it was opening its borders to the rest of the
world and that its citizens may travel or emigrate anywhere,
including through the 28-year-old Berlin Wall, erected at the
height of the Cold War between East and West.
   ``It's a dramatic happening for East Germany and, of course, for
freedom,'' Bush said.
   The White House announced Thursday night that Bush had ordered
U.S. military units and U.S. Ambassador Vernon Walters to give
``all possible assistance'' to the West German government
struggling to cope with the flood of refugees. The Pentagon said it
was making available housing for 980 people in three off-base
installations.
   Defense Department spokesman Glenn Flood said today there has
been no new West German request for additional assistance, and
there have been no new Pentagon offers of military assistance
beyond what was made Thursday.
   Other U.S. leaders reacted with a mixture of joy and surprise.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine called it a
``symbolic destruction of the Berlin Wall'' and urged East Germany
to ``take the final step and tear that wall down.''
   ``The events of today are truly remarkable,'' said Vice
President Dan Quayle.
   Bush, with Secretary of State Baker at his side and a map of
Germany open on his desk, said, ``We salute the people in East
Germany, whose aspirations for freedom seem to be a little more
down the road now.''
   Bush seemed subdued in an exchange with reporters summoned to
the Oval Office to hear his reaction to the latest startling news
from the East Bloc.
   ``I am not an emotional kind of guy,'' he explained. But he
added, ``I feel very good about it.''
   Bush said he was prepared to give ``maximum help'' to Bonn to
cope with refugees. Some 200,000 East Germans have fled their
country this year through Hungary, Czechoslovakia or other routes
West.
   But recalling his advice last spring to Poles to stay in their
homeland to work for democratic reforms, Bush said:
   ``These are Germans. And Germans love their country. And at some
point, I think a lot of Germans who have felt pent-in and unable to
move are going to say, `Look, we can move but wouldn't it be better
to participate in the reforms that are taking place in our own
country?'''
   Bush said that when he meets with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev next month in the Mediterranean, he would discuss
additional steps the United States might take to help spur change
in East Europe _ including possible restoration of long-denied U.S.
trade benefits.
   Sounding a note of caution, Bush said, ``I don't think any
single event is the end of what you might call the Iron Curtain,
but clearly this is a long way from the harshest Iron Curtain
days.''
   At a state dinner for Philippine President Corazon Aquino, Bush
told reporters he has sent a message to the West German government
saying he wants to talk to Chancellor Helmut Kohl when he returns
from a visit to Poland.
   Secretary of State Baker said East Germany's action is ``a very
welcome and positive and significant development. ... I don't think
anybody would have predicted (it) three or four days ago.''
   ``Hopefully, we'll see more steps toward freedom in East
Germany,'' said Baker. ``Once people taste the fruits of freedom,
you don't put the genie back in the bottle.''
   At the Pentagon, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the odds of
military forces from East Germany being used against the West
appeared to be ``significantly lower now than at any time in the
postwar period.''
   Retired Army Gen. Bernard Rogers, who was supreme allied
commander in Europe from 1979 to 1987, gave a similar assessment on
NBC-TV's ``Today'' show this morning.
   ``I think that all indicators from at least 1987 on are that the
threat of war is reduced. At least that should be our perception at
the present time,'' Rogers said.
   Dean Rusk, who was President Kennedy's secretary of state when
the wall was erected, said, ``I never thought I would live to see
the day. The implications of it are very far-reaching.
   ``The West Germans may have a problem absorbing all the East
Germans who will want to move there, but that's something the West
Germans will just have to struggle with, said Rusk, now a law
professor at the University of Georgia.
   ``But it's obvious that in Eastern Europe several things have
been set in motion that are irreversible and that cannot be taken
back to the worst of the Cold War days.''
</TEXT>
