<FIRST>r a AM-WarGame     11-10 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Game,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army War Game Near Scares Residents, Riles Sheriff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORVALLIS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pre-dawn Army shoot-'em-up _ complete
with machine gun fire, flares and soldiers racing through
civilians' yards _ has the sheriff, well, up in arms.
   The mock military attack came on Thursday at 4:30 a.m., a time
Sheriff Jay Printz said was totally inappropriate.
   Calls from terrified residents came in so quickly ``my lone
dispatcher couldn't get everybody's name,'' Printz said.
   ``One woman was so scared she was calling from the bathroom,
where'd she'd locked herself in,'' the sheriff said.
   Callers told of unidentified men firing automatic weapons and
shooting flares and warriors racing across the deck of a private
house, Printz said.
   The Army was ``essentially having a little war'' in an area just
outside Corvallis, which is south of Missoula in western Montana,
Printz said.
   Complaints focused on rude disruptions in the pre-dawn, trespass
on private property, spooked livestock bouncing off barbed-wire
fences and potential fires from flares on roofs, the sheriff said.
   Army officials refused to say anything other than there would be
an investigation of the complaints.
   Margaret Searle said her family thought it was a ``war zone''
outside. Her husband got his rifle and fired a round into a wood
pile to scare off the soldiers, she said.
   The woman said military investigators came by later and told her
the special forces troops were making a mock attempt to blow up a
fuel depot. She noted there are some fuel storage tanks a few
hundred yards from the family residence.
   Printz said he was told last summer that parts of ``Exercise
Knife Blade 90'' would occur in Ravalli County this fall. He was
never informed about specific operations but was promised they
would not be near residential areas, he said.
   He told military officials that if there's another similar
occurrence, deputies will be making arrests, Printz said.
</TEXT>
