<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Observers     11-10 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Observers,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observer Groups Swarm Nicaragua; Elections Good Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of observers from the
Organization of American States dashed out of the voter
registration station and scrambled into a caravan of waiting
vehicles.
   In the confusion, some of them jumped into a U.N. jeep at the
curb and ordered the bewildered driver: ``Follow that caravan!''
   When the string of vehicles screeched to a halt at the next
station and the observers again jumped out, the U.N. driver peeled
off and returned to his employers, hoping they hadn't missed him.
   ``There are so many observers in this little country, you find
them in the soup,'' said a Latin American diplomatic source who
requested anonymity. ``But that is good. We'd rather have too many
than too few.''
   Foreign observers are swarming all over Nicaragua in such
profusion that the Foreign Ministry felt compelled to call a news
conference to explain who is doing what.
   There are observers for the electoral process leading to general
elections Feb. 25; observers to make sure the anti-Sandinista
rebels known as Contras disband; observers to a regional accord not
to arm guerrillas; and self-appointed observers of foreign
contributions to political parties.
   A 625-member force approved by the U.N. Security Council is the
latest addition to the battalions of observers in Central America.
They are to verify that Contras don't slip across the border from
Honduras into Nicaragua.
   ``Observing elections has become an industry,'' said British
government observer David Browning of Oxford University. ``But
who's observing the observers?''
   There are observer teams from the OAS, the United Nations, joint
commissions from both organizations, the European Parliament,
former President Jimmy Carter, one U.S. government foundation and
one private U.S. foundation.
   Apart from that, there are individuals and groups representing
the political spectrum descending on Nicaragua in droves. U.S.
congressmen come down singly or in clusters.
   ``It seems like we get one every weekend,'' said a Western
diplomatic source. ``I don't know the last time we had a full
weekend off.''
   OAS Secretary-General Joao Baena Soares headed his
organization's mission to observe the first Sunday of registration,
Oct. 1. He and his retinue visited 35 voter registration stations
in five communities within 12 hours.
   The confusion over the jeeps happened at one of those stations.
   In Nicaragua's severely depressed economy, observers are good
business. They need housing, food, transportation. They need office
space, drivers and secretaries.
   Housing in the Managua area, the center of operations for all
these groups, is scarce. The laws of demand and supply take over.
   Property rental agents are delighted. But the observer staff
members are not.
   ``I was shown the same house three times in one day, by three
different agents,'' said a U.N. observer. ``Every time the (rental)
price was different _ each time it was higher.''
   The observers' first job was to watch over voter registration
during the first four Sundays in October. It ended Oct. 22. The
United Nations and the OAS released reports calling the
registration process largely free and fair.
   Now their job is to keep watch over the campaigning and ensure
every one of the 21 legally registered parties in Nicaragua has a
chance to spread its message freely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SecretTaping 1stLd-Writethru a0485 11-10 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secret Taping, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Class-Action Lawsuit Filed Against Connecticut State Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with taping also done in Torrington, Conn. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police were warned by the state's
chief justice six years ago to stop taping private conversations
between attorneys and their clients, but the taping continued, and
led to a federal lawsuit.
   The class action lawsuit filed Thursday names the state and 19
high-ranking state police officials allegedly involved in secret
taping as far back as 1980. ``Hundreds of thousands'' of
conversations may have been taped at about a dozen state police
barracks around the state, said Michael Koskoff, a lawyer who
called a news conference to announce the lawsuit.
   In 1983, former state Chief Justice John A. Speziale warned
police to stop tape-recording suspects' telephone conversations
with their lawyers.
   ``Eavesdropping by the police or their agents makes a mockery of
the right to consult counsel before being interrogated,'' Speziale
wrote in a 1983 ruling on a 1980 tape recording of a lawyer talking
to his client.
   The taping resurfaced inadvertantly Oct. 24 when a state trooper
testified at a hearing in a manslaughter case that a conversation
between the suspect and his attorney had been taped.
   Gov. William A. O'Neill on Tuesday ordered an investigation into
the taping policy, and Thursday, federal prosecutors asked Chief
State's Attorney John J. Kelly to turn over the 763 state police
tapes _ containing 18,000 hours of conversations _ that were
impounded when O'Neill opened the probe.
   State police claim the taping was done to ensure that emergency
telephone calls to the barracks could be replayed in case the call
was unclear or if someone had a complaint about the way a call was
handled.
   The taping posed a political problem for O'Neill, a Democrat up
for re-election next year. His adversaries in both parties called
on him to fire State Police Cmdr. Lester J. Forst, the lead
defendant in the case.
   The lawsuit seeks damages of at least $10,000 for each person
who joins the class action, and punitive damages under federal
racketeering statutes.
   ``If anybody made a phone call from the state police barracks
and spoke to someone other than a police officer, they can pretty
well assume their phone call was intercepted,'' Koskoff said at the
news conference. ``We even had information there were police
officers who didn't even know these phones were being tapped.''
   The lawsuit could overturn criminal convictions if the court
found an illegally taped conversation led to the conviction, said
Joseph Keefe, president of the 200-member Connecticut Criminal
Defense Lawyers Association, which filed the suit.
   ``People make the most damaging admissions when they're arrested
because they're upset,'' Keefe said, adding, ``I suppose nothing
should should shock us. But to violate the right to counsel, to do
that knowingly ...''
   Normally, police must obtain warrants to conduct secret wiretaps
or tape conversations. The taping also appears to have violated
privileged lawyer-client conversations.
   Forst has been on a hunting vacation in Alaska. O'Neill said
Wednesday he was not inclined to fire Forst, whom he hired in 1981,
before speaking with him.
   The state police is not the only department in Connecticut to
stand accused of secret taping. The Waterbury Republican reported
today that police in Torrington, a town north of 30,000 of
Waterbury, routinely taped conversations between prisoners and
lawyers and at least once refused a lawyer's demand that the taping
be stopped.
   Attorney John Logan said he helped another lawyer, John Del
Buono, get charges against a client reduced because tapes had been
made of Del Buono's conversations with the client a year ago even
though Del Buono objected.
    Torrington Police Chief Mahlon C. Sabo said he was unaware of
the taping until Thursday and it would be stopped. The department
makes tapes of all calls on the department's main business line,
and because of equipment shortages, the telephone that prisoners
use is hooked up to that line, he said.
   ``I'm embarrassed I didn't know,'' said Sabo, who's been chief
about 3{ years. ``I don't know why, and this (phone system)
certainly has been here a lot longer than I have.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Philippines 2ndLd-Writethru a0442 11-10 0878</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0442,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Leader Meets With Quayle, Nicaraguan Challenger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with meeting, picks up at pvs 2nd graf, Bush
was</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine President Corazon had breakfast
today with Vice President Dan Quayle and U.S.-backed Nicaraguan
opposition candidate Violeta Chamorro, and a Quayle aide said the
administration hoped some of the visiting leader's popularity would
rub off.
   Mrs. Chamorro is in the United States this week seeking to raise
funds for her February election against leftist President Daniel
Ortega.
   A Quayle aide, Carnes Lord, said the two women _ both the wives
of slain national leaders _ discussed their common experiences in
entering politics.
   Asked if Mrs. Chamorro hoped to cash in on some of Mrs. Aquino's
popularity, Lord said, ``That was the idea, obviously.''
   He said the three-way meeting at the vice president's residence
had been suggested to Mrs. Aquino during Quayle's recent visit to
the Philippines.
   Mrs. Aquino is not dropping any clues about the fate of U.S.
military bases in her country, but President Bush says he is
confident an agreement will be reached for a ``long-term security
partnership.''
   Bush was effusive in his praise for Mrs. Aquino during meetings
at the White House on Thursday despite her reluctance to discuss
continued U.S. access to Clark Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base.
   ``From Main Street to Wall Street, America loves the
Philippines. And America loves Cory Aquino,'' Bush said in
welcoming remarks.
   ``You deserve our help and you will get it. I pledge our
continuing assistance to your government, and that means security
assistance as well as aid to economic development,'' Bush said.
``And it means cooperating in your important debt-reduction
programs.''
   The future of the two massive bases is the most important _ and
most controversial _ issue on the U.S.-Philippine agenda.
   Leases for the facilities expire in September 1991, and the
United States regards them as a vital for projecting American
military power throughout Southeast Asian sea lanes and for
stability in the Pacific. They serve as a counterpoint to Soviet
naval forces based in Vietnam.
   Mrs. Aquino faces pressure at home to end the U.S. access. An
influential minority of Filipinos view the continued U.S. military
presence as an infringement on Philippine sovereignty and a vestige
of the former U.S. colonial administration.
   Before leaving Washington today, Mrs. Aquino planned to meet
with Defense Secretary Dick Cheney. Then, she was heading to Dallas
to meet with officials of the large retailing chain, J.C. Penney, a
major importer of Philippine products.
   In a toast at a state dinner Thursday night, Bush lauded her
``monumental'' political and economic accomplishments and said her
country's revolution had inspired ``freedom-loving people
everywhere.''
   Mrs. Aquino, in a poignant reply, said, ``The Philippines is a
small country and cannot claim to affect directly events beyond its
borders; certainly not across half the world in Europe.''
   But, after reciting the ``startling'' changes underway in the
East Bloc, she said: ``Yet it is not too much to say that the
images of heroism spawned by our people power revolution gave
dominated peoples throughout the world a glimpse of certain
possibilities that they are now exploring _ the possibility, for
example, that armor and infantry do not exhaust the varieties of
power.''
   Mrs. Aquino told reporters after the dinner, ``Many times people
approach me in my travels abroad and say they are truly inspired by
what happened in the Philippines in 1986. I'm very glad we're
identified with something so noble and so pure.''
   Earlier at the White House, Bush noted that preliminary talks on
the bases will begin next month and said, ``We are confident we'll
mold a new and mutually beneficial long-term security partnership
in the future.''
   Steering clear of the basing issue, Mrs. Aquino emphasized the
themes of trade and investment.
   ``We will raise particularly the means by which the Philippines
and the United States can cooperate in more ways to our mutual
economic benefit. We shall explore the means to increase trade
between two countries with long historic ties and deep cultural
affinities.''
   It was her first visit to the White House since 1986 when she
received a tumultuous welcome after leading the successful campaign
to depose President Ferdinand Marcos, ending years of authoritarian
rule.
   ``Your leadership has made the Philippines a beacon of
democracy, worthy of imitation throughout the world,'' Bush told
Mrs. Aquino.
   In their talks, Bush mentioned the bases only in ``a passing
reference'' to next month's talks, said Richard Solomon, assistant
secretary of state for East Asian affairs. He said Mrs. Aquino
expressed no sentiment one way or the other.
   Mrs. Aquino pressed Bush for greater access to U.S. markets,
help in debt relief and U.S. investment in the Philippines, Solomon
said. He said she specifically mentioned U.S. quotas on textile and
sugar imports.
   U.S. and Philippine officials signed a $25 million aid agreement
Thursday to lay the groundwork for telecommunications,
transportation, energy and other infrastructure projects.
   While Congress rushed through a $200 million aid package for the
Philippines after Mrs. Aquino took office, there is less eagerness
now because some lawmakers believe economic reform and increased
trade would improve living standards there more than additional
economic aid.
</TEXT>
