<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Soviet     11-10 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Soviet,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Inaugurates Exhibit of Russian Icons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II inaugurated the first
Vatican exhibit of Russian religious art Friday and said the icons
symbolized the roots of Christianity in Europe.
   He was guided through the exhibit of 107 medieval works by J.S.
Meldev, minister of culture for the Russian republic.
   Meldev noted that the exhibit opened ``on the eve of an historic
meeting,'' a reference to pope's scheduled audience with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev during the Soviet president's visit to Italy on Nov.
29-Dec. 1.
   John Paul nodded and smiled at the remark. In his speech, he
said:
   ``The art of the East and of the West is the expression of the
unique Christian spirit, and, in a manner of speaking, the
`breathing' of those `two lungs' of European Christianity, Western
and Eastern, which should contribute equally ... to the recovery of
the Christian roots of the European people.'' He also linked the
exhibit to last year's 1,000 anniversary of the introduction of
Christianity in what now is the Soviet Union. He said the
celebrations prompted ``a spontaneous ray of light, rich in further
promise and developments, which lead to hope of a deeper accord
between East and West.''
   Works on display, dating from the 13th to 18th centuries,
include faces of Christ, the Madonna and child, saints, and scenes
of Christmas and other religious celebrations. The exhibit, at the
Braccio de Carlo Magno in St. Peter's Square, opens to the public
Saturday and runs through Jan. 30.
