<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Aquino     11-10 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Aquino,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adulation in Washington Contrasts With Problems at Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans have lavished praise on
President Corazon Aquino during her visit to the United States, but
at home she faces declining popularity.
   ``From Main Street to Wall Street, America loves the
Philippines,'' President Bush told Mrs. Aquino at the White House
on Thursday. ``And America loves Cory Aquino.''
   But a recent survey of 300 Manila residents showed that only 35
percent were satisfied with their president. Two years ago, a
survey by the same pollster, the Social Weather Stations, indicated
a 77 percent approval rating for Mrs. Aquino.
   Bush's remarks were typical of the reception Mrs. Aquino has
received during her North American tour. She arrived in Canada on
Nov. 4 and traveled Tuesday to New York. After Washington, she is
to visit Dallas and Los Angeles.
   ``The attentive observer with an eye constantly cocked for
exquisite ironies would not miss this one: of apparent cheers for
the president on foreign soil and tears and jeers on her home
base,'' wrote columnist Rosario Garcellano in The Manila Times.
   Columnist Luis Beltran, traveling with Mrs. Aquino, noted the
enthusiastic welcomes she has received from Filipino expatriates in
North America.
   ``It is as if Filipinos abroad are caught in a time warp,''
Beltran wrote in The Manila Standard.
   National leaders often enjoy a more favorable image abroad than
at home, and Mrs. Aquino's aides routinely dismiss criticism as the
carpings of opposition groups jealous of power.
   But even her supporters acknowledge growing public disaffection
because of rising prices, crime, corruption, lack of basic services
and a failure to fulfill many of promises of the ``people power
revolution'' that ousted Ferdinand Marcos and brought Mrs. Aquino
to power.
   Much of the dissatisfaction stems from economic problems.
Despite a 6 percent economic growth, inflation has reached more
than 13 percent, with the greatest increases in food.
   The country's electric power system is in such deplorable
condition that the state-run National Power Corp., has begun a
system of two-hour rotating brownouts throughout Manila and Luzon
island to cope with the shortage.
   Public school teachers, Supreme Court staffers and other
government employees began a series of strikes this week over pay
demands and delays in receiving promised salary differentials.
   Crime is widespread, due in part to corruption within the police
and armed forces. There have been so many robberies of buses in
western areas of Mindanao island that the military has begun
providing armed escorts for vehicles.
   Police say the crime rate between January and September was 1.4
percent above the figure for all of last year. More than 15 percent
of all crimes reported took place in Manila.
   Critics also claim Mrs. Aquino tends to make grandiose promises
without keeping them. She promised justice to victims of a January
1977 incident in which troops killed 12 protesters. No one was ever
charged in the incident after the commission she established to
investigate effectively exonerated the troops.
   The senior officer at the scene, Brig. Gen. Ramon Montano, was
later promoted to major general and placed in command of the
national police.
</TEXT>
