<DOCNO> AP891110-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AmistadConference     11-10 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amistad Conference,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Conference at Historic Repository Looks to Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights conference this weekend was
named in commemoration of an uprising on a slave ship 150 years ago
but is as concerned with the future as it is with the past, an
organizer said.
   ``We've achieved great advances in expanding citizenship rights.
But we still have a long ways to go in achieving educational equity
and economic first-class citizenship,'' said Lawrence N. Powell, a
Tulane University history professor and chairman of the Amistad
Civil Rights Conference.
   The west African tribesmen who took over the Spanish schooner La
Amistad _ ironically meaning ``Friendship'' _ won the first U.S.
legal victory for freedom for African slaves in 1841, two years
after their revolt in Cuban waters.
   The conference is the first major event of the Amistad Research
Center, keeper of the nation's foremost collection of black and
ethnic manuscripts and records, since it moved to Tulane University
in 1987.
   Speakers are to include Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, former U.S.
Labor Secretary Ray Marshall, Democratic National Committee
Chairman Ron Brown and senior Judge John Minor Wisdom, who wrote
landmark civil rights rulings for the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in the mid-1960s.
   ``We thought of having some kind of family reunion, but decided
there's been enough of that and what we really need to do is
rededicate ourselves. ... We can't sit around and pat ourselves on
the back,'' said Powell.
   New Orleans became host of the conference as a result of former
Mayor Ernest Morial's success in persuading the city's colleges and
universities to form a consortium to support bringing the Amistad
collection to Tulane.
   The collection started when the American Missionary Association,
which traces its history to the Christian abolitionists who carried
the Amistad case to the U.S. Supreme Court, asked a young history
teacher to organize the files he'd used for his doctoral
dissertation.
   Clifton Johnson organized the files in 1966 and remains
Amistad's executive director.
   ``We probably have the largest collection in the world on
African-Americans in civil rights in the United States. Our
collection of manuscripts numbers more than 10 million pieces,''
said Johnson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
