<FIRST>u a PM-MilitaryJetCrash 4thLd-Writethru a0549 11-10 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Jet Crash, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0549,0950</SECOND>
<HEAD>1 Missing and Feared Dead In Debris of Apartments Where Jet Crashed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with search concentrating on clues, not
missing man, and SUBS 8th graf, `An initial...', to give detail. Picks
up 9th graf, `The crash...'. SUBS 12th graf, `He was...', to add detail
on pilot's condition. DELETES 24-26th grafs to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AX1,4,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers picked through the rubble of a
suburban Atlanta apartment complex today, looking for clues to the
crash of a Navy jet fighter that exploded and slammed into the
buildings, leaving one man missing and feared dead.
   Four people were injured, including the pilot of the A-7E
Corsair II who ejected just before the crash Thursday evening, and
a pregnant woman and her 5-year-old child who were critically
burned.
   ``All the people are accounted for, except one occupant,'' Cobb
County Medical Examiner Joseph Burton said today. ``Unfortunately,
we're pretty sure he's in there.'' Four other people who had
originally been listed as missing were accounted for today.
   Earlier, Burton had said, ``If there are no fatalities, I'd call
it somewhat of a miracle.''
   The unarmed A-7E Corsair II crashed 2{ miles short of the runway
at NavalAir Station Atlanta, 15 miles north of Atlanta adjacent to
Dobbins Air Force Base, said Navy spokesman Kerry Honore. The pilot
was attempting to land at the air station when the crash occurred
at about 6:30 p.m.
   About 30 people at the Pine Hill Village Apartment complex were
left homeless. Burton said the missing man was believed to be the
sole occupant of an apartment, but he said he could not rule out
the possibility that a visitor also could have been with him.
   ``My first officer on the scene said he heard screams, but the
building was engulfed in flames and he couldn't get in,'' Police
Lt. J.L. Martin said.
   An initial sweep today looking for the missing man yielded
nothing, Burton said at midmorning, adding, ``He's not where you
can see him.'' Later, Smyrna Fire Chief Larry Williams said local
search crews had yielded for the time being to military searchers
who were looking mainly for clues.
   The crash site remained sealed off with police tape and Marine
Reserve guards. Police officer Frank Durrance, who had been inside
the complex, said the Navy jet struck the edge of a building before
crashing into a car and coming to rest by a chain link fence about
30 yards away.
   ``It's completely burned. It's just a big piece of metal. ...
The car was completely burned. You could tell it was a car, but you
can't tell that it was a plane,'' Durrance said.
   The Navy today identified the pilot as reservist Lt. Cmdr.
Robert M. Conlyn Jr. of Marietta, a veteran pilot both for the
Naval Reserve and Delta Air Lines.
   He underwent brain surgery at Kennestone Hospital on Thursday
night. He was still listed in critical condition today, unconscious
and breathing with the aid of a ventilator, although he showed
``some slight improvement,'' said hospital spokeswoman Laurel
Fredlake.
   A witness, Terry Scott, said he saw the pilot's parachute deploy
about 100 feet above the ground. The pilot plunged into a street,
where he was given cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
   ``I saw the plane pop and all the lights go off,'' said Charles
Feather, a maintenance supervisor at an adjacent apartment complex
who said he helped a pregnant woman and her child escape the
burning building.
   ``I found the baby girl, and she was burnt,'' he said. ``Then I
found the pregnant woman, and the paramedics showed up.''
   Margie Padovani, 28, and her 5-year-old daughter, Jacquelyn,
were in critical condition today with burns over about half their
bodies, said Grady Memorial Hospital spokesman Jim Driscoll. He
said Ms. Padovani also had a broken leg. Troy Kraemer, who said he
was Ms. Padovani's fiance, said she was pregnant. He said doctors
told him the fetus might not survive.
   Holly Alfredson, 24, was treated for cracked ribs she suffered
while fleeing her apartment, hospital officials said.
   The commander of the Naval Air Station, Capt. Peter Hunt, said
today that he had no information on the cause of the crash. A Navy
review board would study the wreckage and maintenance and pilot
records, he said.
   The plane did not carry the ``black box'' flight recorder
required on commercial airlines, and Hunt said air traffic
controllers received no distress messages from the pilot.
   The crash confirmed the worst fears of residents who hear
military planes and helicopters roar above them daily.
   ``I'm not surprised,'' said Tim Head, a resident of the damaged
apartment complex. ``Not a week goes by that I don't think, `When
is a jet going to crash here?'''
   ``What I want to know is why they do maneuvers in such a
populated area?'' said Tony Clark, who lives nearby.
   Military officials last year canceled performances by the Blue
Angels stunt aircraft because of the concentration of businesses
and residences near the base.
   The A-7E, which entered service as the A-7 in the 1965 and was
widely used in Vietnam, is a single-seat attack aircraft used for a
variety of bombing missions on land and at sea.
   The current version has undergone a number of modifications. The
A-7E has a 20mm gun and can carry payloads of up to 15,000 pounds
of bombs and missiles.
   Two years ago, a crippled A-7D Corsair, an earlier version of
the plane, slammed into the lobby of the Ramada Inn-Airport in
Indianapolis, killing 10 people.
</TEXT>
