<FIRST>r a AM-Koop-AIDS     11-10 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop-AIDS,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Surgeon General Warns Against `Politicization of AIDS'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who
sought a plain-spoken campaign against AIDS while in office, says
it's a mistake for homosexuals to mix the fight against the deadly
disease with the politics of the homosexual rights movement.
   In a health address and news conference Thursday, Koop said that
``the plea for compassion and care for people with AIDS, if it gets
mixed up with the homosexual rights movement, would fail.''
   Koop, who put the condom in the front-line of the AIDS battle,
declared, ``In the beginning, because AIDS was politicized, we lost
precious time and lives. I hope Hispanics and blacks don't make the
same mistake.''
   The leaders of both those communities, he urged, should say
publicly, ``we have a number of people who, through no fault of
their own, are sick and need our health care and sympathy. They
should not say we should be treated differently from anyone else.''
   Black ministers, Koop declared, should warn from their pulpits
of the perils of unsafe sex and drugs.
   It was inevitable that an AIDS anti-discrimination ordinance,
such as that repealed in Concord this week, would be unpopular,
said Koop.
   Asked whether he supported AIDS anti-discrimination legislation,
he declined a direct answer, saying, ``that's a political issue,
not a public health issue.''
   But, he added, ``People who are sick deserve all the help and
care they can get and shouldn't be discriminated against.''
</TEXT>
