<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-10 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The garden clubs in this wealthy,
suburban city are banding together against what they see as an
unsightly enemy: ``For Sale'' signs, which residents consider tacky.
   The 11 clubs have decided to embark on a letter-writing campaign
to persuade real estate agents to stop using the signs, once
unheard of in Greenwich, where George Bush grew up and where many
New York City corporate titans live.
   Garden club members say burglars may see the signs as hints the
owners are absent. They also worry that the signs hurt property
values.
   ``It's the effect of a fire sale,'' said Nadine Von Storch, a
real estate broker and member of the Hortulus garden club.
``Everything must go. People get panicky. Why is everyone on North
Street selling their house?''
   One real estate agent, David Ogilvy, said his firm simply won't
stoop to using signs.
   ``I think signs are very ugly,'' Ogilvy said. ``I see people
spending tons of money and time landscaping their yards beautifully
to have it ruined by their next-door neighbor whose house is for
sale for nine to 11 months and all you see is signs.''
   But Tom Gorin, vice president of the 700-member Greenwich Board
of Realtors, said: ``In a tough real estate market, it's very
difficult to tell a homeowner that he can't use any means available
to sell.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifth-graders who got a whiff of the
city's waste water treatment plant said they preferred touring it
to spending the day in the classroom.
   ``This was better than going to reading class any day,'' said
Megan Russell, 10.
   The visit was arranged after 25 students in Sue Kellerman's
class at Hampton Elementary School wrote Mayor Delbert Schrems to
say they wanted Saginaw to stop raw-sewage discharges.
   Many pupils held their noses during much of the tour Wednesday,
but most agreed they learned a lot about Saginaw's dumping of
untreated sewage into the Saginaw River.
   About 600 million to 800 million gallons of raw sewage and storm
water finds its way into the Saginaw River annually. Saginaw
Assistant City Manager Robert Dust told the students that the city
will spend $72 million to stop most of its raw-sewage discharges by
1994 by building six retention basins.
</TEXT>
