<FIRST>u a PM-WarehouseFire     11-10 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warehouse Fire,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warehouse Burns Near Downtown Oklahoma City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sparks from a welder's torch today ignited
100,000 pounds of recycled plastics in a nearby warehouse, sending
thick smoke over downtown and threatening to force the closure of
an interstate highway, authorities said.
   Sixty workers in nearby buildings were evacuated as a precaution
after the the blaze broke out in a warehouse next to Interstate 40.
   Deputy Fire Chief Jon Hansen said authorities were concerned
that the burning material might release toxic vapors, and people
were warned to avoid walking into smoke. There were no reports of
injuries, he said.
   The fire broke out about 10 a.m. and was still burning out of
control an hour later, Hansen said. Welders were working on a
billboard with other workers on the ground with fire extinguishers
to put out any sparks that fell. Somehow, a spark ignited the
plastics in the warehouse nearby, officials said.
   The heavy, black smoke boiled up from the blaze, blanketing
downtown Oklahoma City. It could be seen as far as five miles away.
   The Oklahoma Highway Patrol reported several accidents on
Interstate 40, primarily because of people slowing to look at the
fire. Dispatcher Joseph Dukes said troopers would have to close
I-40 if winds blowing the smoke to the north shifted direction.
   Hansen said firefighters were trying to keep the fire from
spreading to nearby buildings, including a huge U-Haul warehouse
across the street.
</TEXT>
