<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland     11-10 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Changes Prompt Kohl to Suspend Polish Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland said it understood Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's decision to break off a visit Friday after the
dramatic opening of East Germany's borders, and officials tried to
salvage the future of the trip.
   The stunning developments in East Germany were the main topic of
talks when Kohl met with Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki on
Friday and said he planned to go back to West Germany, according to
Kohl spokesman Hans Klein.
   ``The prime minister showed understanding for the decision of
the chancellor to cut short his visit,'' Klein said, adding that
Kohl ``wanted to do everything to create the impression that West
German interest in Poland had not decreased.''
   ``Kohl has bigger problems and everybody must understand that.
It would have been politically unwise for him not to return,'' said
Jerzy Osiatynski, head of the central planning office.
   Government spokeswoman Malgorzata Niezabitowska said Kohl told
Mazowiecki that he needed to break the six-day visit for ``about 24
hours'' to go to Berlin and Bonn.
   Making light of the events sweeping Eastern Europe, a senior
government official remarked, ``Kohl will be back if Germany
doesn't reunify in the meantime.''
   Klein said Kohl was planning to return Saturday night and would
travel to the Silesian town of Krzyzowa to attend a Roman Catholic
Mass with Mazowiecki. Ethnic Germans also are planning to gather
there.
   Despite the departure, the two sides managed to sign six
agreements.
   The documents include the important investment promotion and
protective agreement, which provides West German guarantees for
private enterprise investments in Poland. The economic assistance
amounted to about $1.5 billion in two years, including a $250
million loan to help stabilize the zloty.
   Mazowiecki's government says massive Western economic aid is
needed to secure the fragile democratic process under way.
   West Germany is Poland's largest Western trading partner and
Kohl brought a delegation of businessmen with him to start
developing projects between the two countries.
   On Thursday, the nations agreed to establish consulates in
Hamburg and Krakow, and to extend contacts between their foreign
ministries.
   Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski said his talks with West
German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher had been ``very
good'' and all the bilateral issues had been resolved before the
East German developments propelled the talks to an international
level.
   Thousands of East Germans streamed into West Berlin late
Thursday after the decision by East Berlin to open border
crossings, and a massive and emotional street party continued
through the night.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told PAP that the changes in East
Germany ``should have been taken much earlier.''
   ``The drama of the events in East Germany is the result of
earlier neglect, as usually happens when someone misses the train
of history,'' Walesa said.
   The developments in East Germany have fueled Polish fears about
German reunification and forced long-simmering border issues to the
forefront of Kohl's visit, which was intended to move the former
World War II adversaries closer to reconciliation.
</TEXT>
