<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Assets     11-10 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Assets,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Rejects Linking Returned Assets With Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran Friday reiterated the U.S. release
this week of $567 million in frozen Iranian assets won't affect the
status of Americans held hostage in Lebanon.
   Tehran television reported Eftekhar Jahroomi, legal adviser to
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani, rejected any link because the
U.S. decision Monday complied with a U.S.-Iranian claims commission
in the Hague set up in 1981 after talks in Algiers.
   ``The payment was solely in line with the Algiers agreements,''
Jahroomi was quoted as saying by the broadcast, monitored in
Cyprus. ``Iran's claims against American banks were similarly
paid.''
   Nowbari Heirani, Iran's representative at the international
court also said the released assets ``have nothing to do with the
hostages,'' the report said.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Mahmoud Vaezi said Thursday repayment of
the assets had ``nothing to do with good will.''
   President Bush said Tuesday he hoped the U.S. move will prompt
Iran to obtain freedom for the eight American hostages in Lebanon.
The State Department said the decision itself was not influenced by
the hostage issue.
   Rafsanjani, leader of the so-called pragmatists in Iran, told a
news conference last month Iran would help secure the release of
the 18 Western hostages held by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon if
Washington unblocks Iranian assets.
   Iran claims the assets frozen a decade ago are as much as $12
billion, including the value of weapons purchased before the 1979
Islamic revolution but never delivered.
   The assets were blocked after militants stormed the U.S. Embassy
in Tehran Nov. 4, 1979, and held American diplomats and other
personnel hostage. Fifty-two captives were released 444 days later.
   The longest-held hostage in Lebanon is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
