<FIRST>r p AM-YonkersMayoral     11-10 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yonkers Mayoral,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Result of Bitter Mayoral Race Suddenly in Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surprising numbers that turned up in
verifying the vote count for Yonkers mayor cast doubt on results of
a bitter election won by an opponent of court-ordered housing
desegregation, officials said Friday.
   With five of the city's 12 wards recounted in the official
canvass, Democratic incumbent Nicholas Wasicsko had picked up 1,663
votes, cutting by more than a third the margin by which he trailed
Republican Henry Spallone.
   ``This makes it close and there is a possibility the results
could change,'' said Marion Oldi, one of two Westchester County
elections commissioners.
   The canvass was suspended Friday for Veterans Day and was to
resume Monday.
   Commissioner Antonia D'Apice said the error discovered Thursday
was unnerving because of its size, but that she considered a
reversal unlikely.
   Wasicsko acknowledged the chance was remote, but obtained a
court order to have the remaining machines impounded under state
police guard.
   ``The whole direction of the city hangs in the balance,'' the
mayor said.
   The race for City Hall was a pivotal one for Yonkers, a city of
195,000 on the Hudson River north of New York, where a
court-ordered housing desegregation plan has divided the city for
years. The election was basically a referendum on the issue, with
Spallone urging continued defiance and Wasicsko calling for
compliance.
   In addition, the mayor will be the seventh vote on a City
Council that apparently shapes up as evenly divided on the issue.
   ``There's always a possibility I might wake up and not be mayor
of Yonkers. But I think the numbers will hold,'' Spallone said.
``Everything's in the hands of the Lord.''
   Unofficial Election Night tallies had Spallone defeating
Wasicsko by 4,466 votes, 29,025 to 24,559. Vote totals generally
change slightly in the official canvass that verifies the voting
machine tallies phoned in from the polling places Tuesday night.
</TEXT>
