<FIRST>u a PM-Bush-EastGermany     11-10 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-East Germany,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Change in Eastern Europe Offers Hope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today the rapid, dramatic
change in East Germany and elsewhere in Eastern Europe ``offers us
all much hope and deserves our continued encouragement.''
   In comments at the beginning of a speech on housing, Bush took
note of East Germany's decision to open its borders for the first
time in decades and pledged to ``seize every opportunity to
contribute to lasting peace and to extend democracy.''
   Referring to his planned December summit with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Bush said ``the Malta meeting, given recent
events, takes on even more'' importance.
   In words that were greeted by applause, Bush said,
``Twenty-eight years after the desperate days of 1961, when tanks
faced off at Checkpoint Charlie and that terrible barrier was
built, now the East German government has responded to the wishes
of its people.''
   ``The changes in recent months make clear that the process of
reform initiated by the Eastern Europeans and supported by Mr.
Gorbachev, by America and by our allies is real, offers us all much
hope and deserves our continued encouragement,'' Bush said.
