<FIRST>r a AM-CokeDrums     11-10 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coke Drums,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Finish Counting Cocaine Bags Hidden in Lye Strong Enough to
Eat Concrete</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a week of sifting through barrels of lye
in a warehouse, federal drug agents announced Friday they had
turned up 10,648 pounds of cocaine _ one of the largest seizures in
U.S. history.
   The cocaine _ valued at nearly $852 million, or $80,000 a pound
_ was wrapped in plastic and topped with 6 inches of powder that
turned out to be a 98 percent concentration of sodium hydroxide, an
extremely caustic lye.
   To extricate the cocaine, scores of law enforcers wore ``moon
suits'' _ oxygen masks, 40-pound air tanks, and protective suits,
the sleeves sealed with tape to two pairs of gloves.
   The gloves had to be changed twice an hour because the lye ate
through them that quickly.
   Sodium hydroxide at that concentration can eat through concrete;
it is nearly 25 times more concentrated than household drain
cleaner.
   The cocaine was discovered Nov. 3 during a raid on the
three-story warehouse. Investigators were searching for five
suspects believed linked to the Cali drug cartel of Colombia.
   Drug Enforcement Agency officials said a ship, the New York
Senator, brought the cocaine to Philadelphia from Panama late last
month; it was then trucked to New York.
   The investigation, begun by U.S. Customs, soon encompassed city
and Nassau County police, the DEA and the Emergency Medical Service.
   The teams worked around the clock, painstakingly opening the
drums and decontaminating, repackaging and removing the cocaine _
except on Sunday, when New York Marathon participants ran past the
cordoned-off site.
   DEA spokeswoman Mary Cooper said it was one of the five largest
cocaine seizures in the nation's history.
   Customs Special Agent Rick Mercier said the drug could be
tainted with the lye despite its wrapping.
   ``We strongly suspect other smuggling has occurred using this
method,'' said Mercier. ``The potential is there that cocaine on
the street may have been contaminated. From a user's standpoint,
how do they know they're getting cocaine that hasn't been tainted?''
   The chemical can irritate the skin and respiratory tract and can
cause blindness. The damage is compounded when it's smoked or
injected.
   Mercier said Thursday's rain caused ``major safety concerns''
for the workers because slight dampness, such as from rain or
sweat, can activate the lye's caustic properties. Still, no
injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
