<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Moldavia     11-10 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Moldavia,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters, Police Clash in Moldavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd demanding the release of protesters
arrested during a Revolution Day gathering clashed with police in
the capital of the southwest republic of Moldavia on Friday night
and people were injured, a witness said.
   Vladimir Solonar said he saw police fire in the air after
members of the Moldavian People's Front political organization
stormed Interior Ministry headquarters in downtown Kishinev, the
capital.
   Solonar, a history lecturer at Kishinev State University and
member of another political group, said by telephone that some
people were injured in ensuing clashes but he had no details.
   A police duty officer, speaking by telephone from the offices
that were stormed, confirmed a demonstration took place, with
casualties. He said some policemen were seriously hurt and the
Health Ministry was determining whether demonstrators were also
injured.
   The officer refused to give his name or details. He said his
superior was busy consulting with Moscow about the clashes.
   At one point during the protest, the crowd stopped and
overturned an ambulance, Solonar said.
   The protesters were demanding the release of about 20 people
arrested Tuesday as they gathered at a monument to a national hero
near the route of a scheduled parade to mark the 72nd anniversary
of Communist power. Activists said police beat people in that crowd.
   A military parade was canceled but a demonstration of workers
went off as scheduled. Thousands of People's Front supporters later
marched the same route with slogans condemning the police and the
republic's leadership.
   Moldavia, with a population of 4.3 million on the border with
Romania, is among the restive Soviet republics where people are
clamoring for more independence from Moscow and preservation of the
local language and culture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
