<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     11-10 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Namibian Election is `Commendably Dull'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 90 percent of eligible voters
have cast ballots in a pre-independence election that appeared
headed for a successful conclusion, the United Nations said Friday,
the second-last day of voting.
   ``The situation in Namibia is commendably dull,'' said U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard. ``The process seems to be going extremely
well.''
   Also Friday, a 12-member U.S. delegation appointed by President
Bush and led by former Secretary of State Edmund Muskie arrived to
observe the election being watched by representatives from around
the world.
   The five-days of balloting, whose results are expected by
Wednesday, will determine a constituent assembly that will write a
constitution paving the way for independence after 74 years of
South African rule. No date for independence has been set, but it
is expected to be early next year.
   Around 90 percent of the 701,483 registered voters cast ballots
through Friday, Eckhard said. U.N. and territorial officials said
the turnout could near 100 percent by the time the balloting ends
Saturday evening.
   As of Friday, no reports of serious political violence were
reported and there were few instances of intimidation. Officials
reported some election code violations such as anonymous smear
pamphlets aimed at discrediting the South-West Africa People's
Organization, the favorite at the polls.
   A Namibian journalist covering the elections, Martin Erastus,
has been missing since Monday when he was seen near the
Namibia-Angola border. Police are investigating.
   The key election issue is whether SWAPO will win two-thirds of
the vote necessary to write a constitution without consulting the
other nine parties. The left-leaning organization waged a 23-year
bush war against South African rule.
   SWAPO is challenged by the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a
multiracial coalition that favors a capitalist economy, was part of
the transitional government installed by South Africa.
   The U.N. has more than 7,000 military and civilian personnel
monitoring the election in the sparsely populated, mineral-rich
territory.
   Assembly seats will be allocated according to the proportion of
votes received by each party, and the assembly is to convene one
week after the results are final.
   South Africa captured the territory from Germany in World War I.
It resisted U.N. efforts to get it to leave but finally agreed to
grant independence under U.N. supervision.
   An estimated 60 percent of Namibia's voters are illiterate. The
318,252-  square-mile territory had a population of 1.3 million in
1981, when the last census was taken.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
