<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BookAuction     11-10 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Book Auction,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blake's First Edition Sells for $1.32 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A first edition of William Blake's ``Songs of
Innocence and Experience,'' printed by the English poet and artist,
sold Friday at auction for $1.32 million.
   An anonymous collector bought the book, which had a presale
estimate of $300,000 to $400,000, said Laura Stewart, a spokeswoman
for Sotheby's auction house.
   On Thursday, a set of the first four successive editions of
Shakespeare's collected plays was sold for $2 million, a record for
what are known as the ``Four Folios,'' Sotheby's said.
   A two-day sale total of $16.3 million was achieved for The
Garden Ltd. collection of books and manuscripts relating to the
history of ideas, which was amassed by Haven O'More and Michael
Davis over more than 25 years.
   Other lots sold Friday included an autographed manuscript of
John Locke, sold to an anonymous London dealer for $907,500.
   A presentation copy of Thomas Jefferson's 1781 Notes on the
State of Virginia, estimated at $35,000 to $50,000, went to a
California dealer for $165,000.
   All prices include a 10 percent premium.
</TEXT>
