<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     11-10 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Reports More Active Discussions of Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discussions of the possible release of
the 18 Western hostages held in Lebanon have become more active, a
magazine said Friday.
   In a report that cited no sources, the weekly Ash-Shiraa said
the U.S. release of Iranian assets this week while Iran's foreign
minister was in Algiers indicated the matter was getting more
attention.
   ``It is known that the issue of foreign hostages in Lebanon has
been put on the front burner and developments could come up
concerning the release of some of the hostages very soon,'' the
magazine said in a two-paragraph story.
   It has made similar predictions regularly since November 1987,
when it broke the story of the arms-for-hostages deal between the
United States and Iran. None of its recent hostage reports have
been accurate.
   Eight of the Western hostages in Lebanon are Americans,
including the one held longest: Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Iran repeated on Friday that the U.S. release this week of $567
million in frozen Iranian assets would not affect the status of the
American hostages, most of whom are held by Shiite Moslem
kidnappers loyal to Iran.
   Tehran television quoted Eftekhar Jahroomi, legal adviser to
President Hashemi Rafsanjani, as saying the U.S. action Monday
merely complied with a decision of the U.S.-Iranian claims
commission set up in 1981 after talks in Algiers.
   ``The payment was solely in line with the Algiers agreements,''
Jahroomi said. ``Iran's claims against American banks were
similarly paid.''
   Algeria was the main mediator in negotiations that led to the
release in January 1981 of 52 Americans held hostage 444 days at
the U.S. Embassy in Tehran.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency had said the
purpose of Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati's 3-day trip to
Algeria was to discuss relations between the two countries.
   President Bush said Tuesday he hoped return of the assets would
encourage Iran to seek release of the hostages, but U.S. officials
also insisted the transfer was not related to the hostage issue.
   Rafsanjani, leader of the ``pragmatists'' who seek to end Iran's
isolation, told a news conference last month he would help secure
freedom for the hostages if the United States released all Iranian
assets frozen after the embassy was stormed in 1979.
   Iran says the assets now are worth $12 billion, including the
value of weapons purchased by the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlevi,
who was overthrown by the Islamic revolution in February 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
