<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Mindszenty     11-10 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Mindszenty,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Orders Retrial Investigation in Mindszenty Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors are examining the case of
Cardinal Jozsef Mindszenty, one of the Cold War's most famous
victims, and he may be cleared of treason charges, the official
news agency MTI said Friday..
   Officials ordered earlier this year that the prosecutor
general's office review the case against the late Roman Catholic
primate, who was convicted at a show trial in 1949.
   The reform movement sweeping Hungary already has brought the
posthumous rehabilitation of Imre Nagy, who led the anti-Stalinist
uprising that was crushed by Soviet tanks in 1956.
   Mindszenty was sentenced to life in prison for high treason
after confessing, presumably under duress or drugs, to most of the
charges against him.
   ``It was established during the re-examination that the relevant
authorities committed law violations which also affected the
sentence passed,'' MTI said.
   ``Presumably, the persons interrogated during the criminal
procedure made their confessions under the impact of violence or
compulsion,'' it reported, without elaboration.
   A ``major proportion'' of the material proof on which the
verdict was based was missing from files, according to the report.
MTI did not say how long the investigation might take.
   Mindszenty had been appointed head of the Hungarian church with
the Communist government's assent, but was arrested at the end of
1948 as tension grew between the church and state.
   He was freed during the 1956 uprising and took refuge in the
U.S. Embassy. Mindszenty stayed there until 1971, when he left
under an agreement worked out with the Vatican.
   He died in 1975 at age 83, while living in self-imposed exile in
Vienna.
</TEXT>
