<DOCNO> AP891110-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Lantos-Bulgaria 300   11-10 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lantos-Bulgaria, 300</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Leader `No Democrat,' Lantos Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said Friday that
Bulgaria's new leader Petar Mladenov was ``no democrat,'' although
he might surprise the world just as Egon Krenz has in East Germany.
   Lantos, who has known members of the Bulgarian leadership for
many years, said he met with Communist Party leader Todor Zhivkov
at his Black Sea summer palace in August.
   Zhivkov, the Soviet bloc's longest-serving party leader,
resigned Friday in a surprise move. But Lantos said he wasn't
surprised.
   ``I expected this,'' the Hungarian-born lawmaker said in an
interview from his California office.
   ``The Bulgarian people have always looked to the Hungarians as
their role model. Once democracy started breaking out in Hungary,
Bulgaria could not be far behind.''
   Hungary will be the first East European nation to hold free
elections, probably next spring. A fledgling pro-democracy movement
has sprung up in Bulgaria in recent months.
   Lantos said he found Zhivkov ``in good shape and good spirits.
He never seems to age.''
   ``He spoke of reform, and I urged him to match his words with
actions,'' Lantos said, adding that Zhivkov urged him to help bring
about U.S. investments and joint ventures in Bulgaria.
   ``This is largely a generational change,'' Lantos said of the
power shuffle in Bulgaria. ``Mladenov was Zhivkov's boy in the
foreign ministry. He's no democrat, although he sounds more
moderate.''
   But Lantos noted that when East Germany's ailing ruler Erich
Honecker stepped down last month, everyone said Krenz, his
successor, was just a younger version of the hardline leader.
   However, Krenz this week opened East German borders, allowing
residents to travel freely.
   ``You might see a parallel development in Bulgaria, too,''
Lantos said.
</TEXT>
