<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-ChildNutrition     11-10 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Child Nutrition,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Child Nutrition Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Friday that will
require all states to use competitive bidding to buy food and
formula for poor women, children and infants.
   Bush, in a statement released here by the traveling White House,
said the 28 states that already use competitive bidding in the
Womens, Infants and Children (WIC) program have saved $300 million
this year alone and been able to serve 500,000 more people.
   Bush signed the Child Nutrition and WIC Reauthorization Act on
Air Force One while flying here to speak at a Realtors' convention.
   The measure ``will save an additional $40 million and allow
68,000 more needy pregnant women, infants and children to
participate in WIC,'' Bush said in a statement.
   Bush said he is ``firmly committed to helping nutritionally
deficient children obtain improved nourishment that will give them
a better start in life.''
   He repeated the lament from his inaugural address that ``we have
more will than wallet,'' and added:
   ``This is the kind of action we must pursue _ obtaining better
value for each dollar of federal spending _ if we are to make
progress on pressing national concerns.''
   The White House also announced that Bush had signed an $8.6
billion military construction appropriations bill for the
Department of Defense for fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
