<FIRST>u i AM-EastBlocLeaders     11-10 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Bloc Leaders,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newest in List of Leaders in Eastern Europe is Bulgaria's Zhivkov</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bulgaria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of current leaders of Eastern European Communist
nations and the length of their tenure as key leaders:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION _ Mikhail S. Gorbachev became Communist Party chief
March 11, 1985. Gorbachev came to power after a transitional period
following the 1982 death of Leonid I. Brezhnev, who ruled for 18
years.
   BULGARIA _ Communist Party leader Todor Zhivkov stepped down
Friday after 35 years in power, longer than any current Eastern
European leader. He was replaced by Foreign Minister Petar Mladenov.
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA _ Milos Jakes was named head of the Czechoslovak
Communist Party on Dec. 17, 1987, replacing Gustav Husak.
   EAST GERMANY _ Egon Krenz became East Germany's leader Oct. 18,
replacing his mentor, Erich Honecker, an orthodox Communist who was
ousted in the face of escalating protests for reform and mass
flight to the West.
   HUNGARY _ On Oct. 7, the Communists dissolved the party,
reconstituted themselves as the Hungarian Socialist Party and
elected reformer Reszoe Nyers as party chief. Nyers replaced Karoly
Grosz, a centrist who had been party chief since longtime leader
Janos Kadar was ousted in May 1988 by party reformers. Kadar came
into power in 1956, during the bloodshed of the Soviet-supressed
1956 revolt.
   POLAND _ Newly elected Solidarity government headed by Tadeusz
Mazowiecki took over Aug. 24. Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, who became
Communist Party chief in October 1981 and declared martial law two
months later, is president under the new system.
   ROMANIA _ Nicolae Ceausescu has been in power since 1965.
   YUGOSLAVIA _ Under a system of rotating the presidency among
members of the nine-man presidency, the federal president serves 12
months. The nine-member collective presidency includes
representatives from all six of Yugoslavia's republics, its two
autonomous provinces and the country's Communist Party chief. The
system was devised by former leader Josip Broz Tito who ruled from
1945 until his death in 1980.
   ALBANIA _ Ramiz Alia assumed power in 1985 upon the death of
Enver Hoxna, who ruled for 41 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Germany-USView     11-10 0854</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-US View,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Experts: Germany's Upheaval Likely to Remake Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's upheaval will rattle all Europe,
impelling the two Germanys toward political and economic
association and throwing into question the NATO and Warsaw Pact
alliances, American experts said Friday.
   ``It is probably the most important strategic change since the
war,'' said Gregory Treverton, senior fellow for Europe at the
Council on Foreign Relations.
   ``The center of Europe, the Germanys, still are the most
strategic landscape in the world. This change there is the most
important thing to happen in Europe certainly for the last 30
years,'' Treverton said in an interview.
   While reforms in Poland and Hungary initiated the process,
Treverton said, East Germany was ``the place where we've always
presumed change would come last. Now we find it coming very soon,
and very quickly.''
   The lifting of travel restrictions and promised political reform
there ``means the successful self-liberation of the German
Democratic Republic, which in itself is a momentous event,'' Prof.
Fritz Stern of Columbia University said, also in a telephone
interview.
   Moreover, in its aftershocks, ``it is likely to change the
politics of Europe, and the political climate of Europe,'' said
Stern, a historian specializing in Europe. ``It's an astounding
historical development.''
   East Germany said Friday it was permanently lifting travel
restrictions on its citizens, and tens of thousands of East Germans
streamed into West Berlin through the newly opened Berlin Wall.
Many, however, are expected to return.
   The events were sparked by pro-reform demonstrations across East
Germany _ and the flight to freedom of thousands of East Germans _
that forced the Oct. 18 ouster of hard-line leader Erich Honecker.
His successor, Egon Krenz, swept aside the old guard in the ruling
Politburo and has promised political reform, including free
elections.
   Allied conquerors sliced Germany into the democratic West and
communist East after World War II, and forces of the Warsaw Pact,
on the East, and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, on the
West, have faced each other across the two Germanys every since.
   Now, Treverton said, the question for the short term is whether
East Germany will produce economic and political reforms sufficient
``to build for itself some legitimacy.'' The conundrum is that if
it fails it loses all legitimacy, he said, but if it succeeds,
``then it's difficult to see what basis there is for a separate
state.''
   ``Then the question is whether some sort of reassociation in
stages can happen and how than would be regarded by the rest of
Europe,'' Treverton said. ``It's no so much reunification as what
form association of the states takes, and over what time period.''
   Stern held a largely similar view: ``It sounds to me as though
the East German government is trying desperately to find some
stability, and that it might be able to satisfy its citizens with
the promises made and the deeds committed, and then enter into
negotiations with the Federal Republic (West Germany) for vast
economic aid.
   ``And then you would have two German states, in the short run,
in very close association. That's not yet reunification, and I
could imagine that it wouldn't become reunification for many
years.''
   The response of other European states is critical, Treverton
noted, because of their fear that a reunited Germany would
contribute to the kind of political instability that preceded the
world war.
   ``Most of the rest of Western Europe is exhilarated and nervous
in about equal proportions,'' he said. ``Nobody knows whether the
nature of the European state system has changed enough that a
Germany that was always destabilizing before may not be so this
time around.''
   With that concern, Treverton said, ``NATO and probably the
Warsaw Pact ought to stay in place a long time as a kind of
residual insurance policy.''
   John Vessey Jr., former chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, also said there was reason for caution amid the jubilation.
   ``East Germany is not appearing to be in control of its own
destiny,'' Vessey said from his home in Garrison, Minn. ``I would
hope there isn't a crackdown.''
   Stern, however, wondered if the East Bloc alliance had not
already largely crumbled. ``What is left of the Warsaw Pact?'' he
asked. ``Would the Soviets really be able to count on the Poles and
the Hungarians, even if they could count on the East Germans, or
maintain their troops there?''
   One possible outcome, he suggested, was ``a breathing period''
in which the Americans, Soviets, British and French, along with the
two Germanys, might reach agreements reducing their troops there.
   On the economic front, Treverton suggested that the European
Economic Community promptly open negotiations with East Germany and
the other changing Eastern European states in order to cement its
position as the economic framework for the new Europe.
   Stern, for his part, said the impact of the upheavals on
Europe's economy, particularly on Western Europe's economic merger
in 1992, remain to be seen.
   ``Nobody could have predicted what has occurred so far,'' he
said. ``So it's foolhardy to make any predictions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
