<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     11-10 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divided Parties Propose Their Solutions to Political Deadlock</HEAD>
<HEAD>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former socialist Premier Andreas
Papandreou received a presidential mandate Friday to try to form a
government, but all three major parties were offering conflicting
solutions to end the political deadlock.
   Conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis earlier Friday
returned his mandate to President Christos Sartzetakis and proposed
a short-term administration to tackle pressing economic problems.
   Underscoring the crisis, the central bank Friday ordered
commercial banks to limit credit extended to the private sector
because of a cash shortfall.
   ``There is a need for a government with international prestige .
.. made up of personalities which will be supported by all
parties,'' Mitsotakis told a news conference.
   He said the government members should not be politicians and
elections should be held early next year.
   The deadlock arose after Mitsotakis' New Democracy Party won the
most votes in last Sunday's elections but missed a majority in the
300-seat Parliament.
   New Democracy won 148 seats in the elections, Papandreou's
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, took 128, and the
Communist-led Coalition of the Left and Progress won 21. Three
seats went to independents.
   Papandreou, who governed from 1981 until June, proposed a
long-term alliance between PASOK, the leftist Coalition, and two
independents.
   He said now was not the time to consider Mitsotakis' proposal
for a government supported by all parties, but did not rule out
such an eventuality.
   The leftist Coalition supports the idea of a broad-based
government of personalities, but its conditions for backing it
include a freeze on negotiations on the future of U.S. military
bases in Greece.
   If Papandreou fails to form a government by Monday, he will
return the mandate to the president and it will be given to
Coalition leader Harilaos Florakis.
   The last government, administered by a conservative-Communist
alliance, dedicated itself only to investigating and indicting
Papandreou and five of his former ministers on corruption charges.
   Papandreou, who has denied all charges, is to be tried by a
special high court early next year.
</TEXT>
