<HEAD>Protest Over Weinberger's Honorary Degree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-nuclear activists on Friday protested a Leeds
University decision to award former U.S. Secretary of Defense
Caspar Weinberger an honorary degree.
   Bruce Kent, the chairman of the Campaign for Nuclear
Disarmament, called on the university in northern England to
reverse its decision. In a letter to Alan Wilson, acting head of
the university, Kent said Weinberger ``has a record as a promoter
of the arms race and of the Cold War which must have few equals.''
   The university's Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament coordinator,
Eddie Goncalves, said he delivered 2,000 letters and postcards to
the administration calling for a reversal of the decision to honor
Weinberger, defense secretary from 1981 to 1987.
   Weinberger, 72, who was knighted by Queen Elizabeth in February
1988, is scheduled to receive his honorary degree Monday night.
