<FIRST>r p AM-VaGovernor'sRace     11-10 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Governor's Race,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confident Wilder Takes a Vacation; Opponent Looking for Mail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Douglas Wilder, confident that his claim
of victory in Virginia's gubernatorial race will stand, went on
vacation Friday while his opponent sought an explanation for why
some campaign mail wasn't delivered.
   Wilder, with about a 6,500-vote lead over Republican J. Marshall
Coleman in unofficial returns from Tuesday's balloting, is taking a
few days off before planning his administration, said B.J.
Northington, the Democrat's deputy press secretary.
   Coleman aides, meantime, claimed that 20,000 pieces of campaign
mail destined for the 10th congressional District in northern
Virginia were not delivered.
   ``We're expecting a thorough investigation of postal employees
will take place, and we will be interested in the results,'' said
Jay Timmons, a spokesman for Coleman.
   The missing mail cleared the area's Post Office, was given to
satellite post offices on Saturday and was put into the hands of
carriers on Monday, Timmons said.
   ``We're not sure if they had them for lunch or someone is not
telling the truth,'' he said.
   Another 2,200 pieces of Coleman mail destined for the Petersburg
area was mistakenly placed in a truck full of empty equipment by
someone who thought the mail sacks were empty, said Deborah
Yackley, communications manager for the Richmond division of the
U.S. Postal Service.
   The Petersburg literature, which Timmons said was mailed Oct. 6,
was found Wednesday, the day after the election. Ms. Yackley said
the Post Office expressed regrets to the state Republican Party.
   Coleman has promised to seek a recount if the election's final
results as certified Nov. 27 by the State Board of Elections show
him losing by a half percent or less.
</TEXT>
