<HEAD>With AM-US-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister of West Germany thanked
the United States for its help over the years in a telephone call
Friday that Secretary of State James A. Baker said ``almost brings
tears to your eyes.''
   Describing the call on ``The MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' on public
television, Baker said when he took the phone he was greeted by the
secretary to the foreign minister, Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   ``She said, `Just a moment sir, and thank you for everything.
God bless America. Here's the minister.'''
   And Genscher came on the line and said: ```I'm calling to
express to you, and through you to the American people, our
gratitude for what America has done for Germany, and particularly
for what America has done for Berlin.' Now I find that very moving.
It almost brings tears to your eyes,'' Baker said.
   The United States, Britain and France, the western allies that
defeated Nazi Germany in World War II, sustained West Berlin by
flying in food and fuel when the Soviet Union blocked all land,
rail and water transport to the city in the winter of 1948-1949.
   When the Soviet Union threatened action against West Berlin
after the building of the Berlin Wall in 1961, President John F.
Kennedy stood at the wall and proclaimed: ``Ich bin ein Berliner''
_ I am a Berliner.
