<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ArtsFunding 1stLd-Writethru a0663 11-10 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arts Funding, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beleaguered Art Director Predicts Blacklists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Artist Space's...,' to clarify board's action
regarding grant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An art gallery director fighting to keep a
$10,000 federal grant in a test of a new anti-obscenity law said
Friday she fears a return to the blacklists of the 1950s.
   ``And I do not think blacklists are a good thing to have in this
country,'' said Susan Wyatt, executive director of Artists Space in
downtown Manhattan.
   ``Last June, Artists Space sponsored an exhibition of Eastern
European art. From that show, we learned a great deal about the
aesthetic poverty of official vs. unofficial art,'' Wyatt said at a
news conference. ``I sincerely hope that this country is not moving
in that direction.''
   In a Nov. 3 letter, National Endowment for the Arts Chairman
John E. Frohnmayer revoked the grant for the gallery's upcoming
AIDS art exhibition. He said later the exhibition catalog indicated
the show was political rather than artistic in nature.
   Artist Space's board on Wednesday unanimously rejected the
request to relinquish its claim to the grant. The board's decision
``is our way of defending the American public's right to form their
own opinions on artistic expression,'' Wyatt said.
   The endowment is withholding the $10,000 pending a legal opinion
from the Justice Department.
   Wyatt said she had not yet obtained a lawyer and would not
speculate on what actions might be taken.
   ``We're kind of in a crisis situation,'' she said.
   The show will open Nov. 16, ``exactly as we had planned,'' she
said.
   It features works by 23 painters, sculptors and photographers
that portray the effects of AIDS on the artistic community. An
apparent sticking point was a catalog essay by David Wojnarowicz, a
photographer who has AIDS, which assails Cardinal John J. O'Connor,
Rep. William E. Dannemeyer, R-Calif., and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
   ``It would be extremely naive to publish a catalog with strong
language and references to public figures and not expect some kind
of comment or controversy,'' said Wyatt.
   Still, she said, ``We didn't decide to do a catalog that was
politically charged; we are publishing a catalog with artistic
texts and writing.''
   Wyatt said that although the show includes some images of male
and female nudity, ``This is not a show about politics; this is not
a show about sexuality; this is a show about AIDS.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
