<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     11-10 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Gov't Gives Visas to 1st Foreign Reporters Since Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government has granted the
first visas to foreign reporters since it arrested opposition
leaders in July and began rounding up thousands of activists
supporting democratic reform.
   ``Foreign journalists' visas are being considered on a
case-by-case basis,'' Col. Ye Htut, a government for the ruling
junta, told a news conference Friday.
   ``Genuine journalists, who will report the truth objectively
without bias, will be permitted when their credibility is vouched
and guaranteed by a responsible person or organization,'' he said.
   A Cable News Network television crew visited Burma this month,
ending a ban on foreign reporters that coincided with the military
junta's crackdown on the opposition.
   Burma has been a one-party state since Ne Win toppled the
elected government in a military coup in 1962 and instituted a
rigid socialist system that impoverished what had been considered
one of Asia's most prosperous states.
   Ne Win resigned in July 1988 after hundreds of thousands of
Burmese took to the streets to demand democracy, but armed forces
chief Gen. Saw Maung seized power two months later and troops
killed thousands of people in a crackdown on dissent.
   In January, Burma officially granted visits by foreign
journalists for the first time in 26 years.
   But the journalists were banned in July, when authorities
rounded up thousands of political activists and put opposition
leaders Aung San Suu Kyi and Gen. Tin Oo under house arrest.
   The United States said it has ``credible'' reports that many of
those imprisoned have been tortured, some until death.
   The state press recently has stepped up attacks on foreign
journalists, accusing them of bias and of assisting allegedly
subversive groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
