<FIRST>r w AM-US-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0700,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Completes Washington Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDs one graf with Bush pledge from Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino ended her
visit here Friday with pledges of U.S. economic support but no
outward sign that she will back continued American use of military
bases in her country.
   Before departing, Mrs. Aquino breakfasted with Vice President
Dan Quayle and U.S.-backed Nicaraguan opposition candidate Violeta
Chamorro.
   The two women _ both the wives of slain national leaders _
discussed their common experiences in entering politics, said
Quayle aide Carnes Lord. Asked if Mrs. Chamorro hoped to cash in on
some of Mrs. Aquino's popularity, Lord said, ``That was the idea,
obviously.''
   Mrs. Aquino, accompanied by members of her Cabinet and aides,
later left for Dallas, where she planned to resume what she has
described as the main purpose of her mission to the United States _
encouraging trade and investment needed for the Philippines'
economic recovery.
   Before departing, she agreed during a 30-minute talk with
Defense Secretary Richard Cheney to start exploratory talks in
Manila in mid-December on the future of the Philippine bases,
Philippines Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said.
   Manglapus, who attended the Aquino-Cheney meeting at a downtown
hotel, told reporters, ``It all depends on the results of the
exploratory talks'' whether the December meetings lead to
negotiations on a new bases agreement after the existing pact
expires in 1991.
   ``If both sides see after the talks that negotiations are
worthwhile towards a new treaty, then those negotiations will begin
soon afterward,'' Manglapus said during a National Press Club
appearance.
   Manglapus, who will lead the Manila talks, said there must first
be exploratory meetings to determine if ``negotiations are
worthwhile towards a new treaty'' _ opening the possibility that
the basing arrangement might not be renewed.
   President Bush and administration officials, however, have
voiced optimism that the process will lead to a new agreement.
   Manglapus said the exploratory talks should deal with use of the
bases, jurisdiction over criminal cases and compensation.
   He mentioned no payment amount. In talks a year ago, Manglapus
had demanded $1.2 billion worth of aid during each of the last two
years of the current agreement. Negotiators finally settled on $480
million annually.
   Various opinion polls show that the Philippine public supports
keeping the U.S. military presence. Aquino's reluctance to take a
stand is regarded by some Bush administration officials and members
of Congress as both a negotiating tactic and recognition of strong
opposition to the bases in the Philippine Senate.
   In his welcoming remarks Thursday, Bush said: ``You deserve our
help and you will get it. I pledge our continuing assistance to
your government, and that means security assistance as well as aid
to economic development. And it means cooperating in your important
debt-reduction programs.''
</TEXT>
