<HEAD>Defendant Named Savage Will Be Called Moore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for James Hudson Savage got a
judge's permission to call him by another name after arguing that
his last name might negatively influence the jury at his murder
trial.
   Defense attorneys had argued that Savage's last name might cause
a jury to think of him as an ``uncivilized primitive.''
   Instead, the defense will call the 25-year-old man Russell
Thomas Moore, the name given to Savage by his mother.
   Prosecutors, meanwhile, must refer to the defendant as Mr.
Savage, Brevard Circuit Judge Lawrence Johnston ruled Thursday.
   ``We are not going to mock his name,'' Assistant State Attorney
Russ Bausch promised.
   Savage will stand trial Monday on charges of first-degree
murder, sexual battery and robbery in the November 1988
strangulation of Melbourne interior designer Barbara Ann Barber.
