<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BloodDisorder     11-10 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blood Disorder,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>State and Federal Workers Investigate Outbreak of Rare Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and state health officials on
Friday worked to discover what caused an outbreak of a rare and
sometimes fatal blood disorder.
   Thirty-one cases had been reported by Friday in six widely
scattered states, including 21 in New Mexico, as health authorities
sought to determine if the outbreak was linked to the use of
L-Tryptophan, an amino acid dietary supplement.
   The disease, eosinophilia, is characterized by high counts of
eosinophils, a type of white blood cell. Symptoms may include sharp
muscular pain, fatigue, fever and rashes.
   Dr. Millicent Eidson, environmental epidemiologist with the
state Health and Environment Department, said 21 cases of
eosinophilia have been confirmed in New Mexico, and an additional
case involving a nearby Arizona resident was reported.
   Eidson said 16 of the 17 women patients and one of the five men
had taken L-Tryptophan, which is often sold in health food stores
to promote relaxation and to ease premenstrual syndrome and
sleeping disorders.
   Medical officials also reported four cases in Oregon, three in
Texas and one each from Missouri and Mississippi by Friday.
   At least five of those nine patients also used L-Tryptophan,
said Nancy Hunter, spokeswoman for the Health and Environment
Department.
   Health officials have requested that New Mexico retailers impose
a voluntary ban on sales of L-Tryptophan while the investigation is
under way.
   Teams from the federal Food and Drug Administration and the
Centers for Disease Control came to New Mexico Thursday to assist
in the investigation.
   Personnel from health department's Office of Epidemiology and
the FDA will be working during the weekend to contact the confirmed
cases, Ms. Hunter said on Friday.
   ``They will be getting the patients' Tryptophan and then going
back to the location where they purchased it and getting samples of
the product for testing,'' Ms. Hunter said.
   ``The FDA will be doing a broad spectrum of tests,'' she said.
``Some of the things they might be looking for are heavy metals or
other organic contaminants.''
   Eosinophilia occurs when there is an abnormally high number of
eosinophils, a type of white cell, in the blood.
   Sixteen people died in 1986 nationwide as a result of
hypereosinophilic syndrome, a form of eosiniphilia, and 12 died in
1987, said Sandy Smith of the National Center for Heath Statistics
in Washington, D.C.
   All of the eosinophilia cases in New Mexico suffered severe
muscle pain. Ten of the patients required hospital treatment and as
of Friday one patient, a 51-year-old woman from Gallup, remained
hospitalized in Albuquerque.
   Dr. Gerald Gleich of the Mayo Clinic said both the Missouri and
Mississippi patients had taken L-Tryptophan.
   ``The thing that's unusual is seeing so many patients with the
same pattern,'' Gleich said. ``What's different is there are so
many at one time, and they're all taking L-Tryptophan.''
</TEXT>
