<FIRST>r a AM-Ford 1stLd-Writethru a0717 11-10 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Chairman Retiring March 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT Peterson's age to 63, sted 64; and
Poling's age to 64, sted 65. A longer version moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto DT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. Chairman Donald Petersen,
who shepherded the automaker from the gloomy financial days of 1980
to huge profits last year, said Friday he would retire March 1.
   Petersen, 63, will be succeeded as chairman and chief executive
officer by Vice Chairman and Chief Operating Officer Harold Poling,
who described his predecessor as a ``visionary leader.'' Poling,
64, will be chairman for three years.
   ``I have been chief operating officer or chief executive officer
for 10 years, and I think that it is time for me to make a change
in my life,'' Petersen said, his eyes misting as he spoke at a news
conference.
   During his decade at Ford, the nation's second-largest automaker
staged a remarkable comeback.
   Petersen was elected Ford president in March 1980. By the end of
the year, the automaker lost $1.5 billion. Eight years later, after
cost-cutting, streamlining and payroll shrinking, Ford posted a
$5.3 billion profit.
   ``I do want to thank the 367,000 Ford employees for everything
they have done these past 10 years to bring our company from the
depths of our difficulties at the beginning of this decade to the
sound footing upon which it stands today,'' Petersen said.
   During the 1980s, Ford embarked on ambitious and, at the time,
risky car development programs that resulted in the Ford Taurus and
Mercury Sable cars. They helped paved the way for modern
aerodynamic-looking cars.
   Succeeding Poling as chief operating officer will be Philip
Benton, who will become corporate president. That title was dropped
when Poling became vice chairman in October 1987.
   ``I'm surprised that Petersen is retiring early,'' said analyst
Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New
York City. ``I think he (Poling) is really going to sit there and
wait it out for the next chairman.''
   Petersen joined Ford in 1949 and held a variety of positions in
domestic and international product planning, design and marketing
before he became president. Poling's Ford career began in 1951 and
focused mainly on the financial side of the corporation.
   Poling said his goal during the next three years is to continue
current programs at Ford.
   During Petersen's tenure, the company branched out and became
heavily involved in financial acquisitions, capped last month with
the completion of the purchase of Associates Corp. for $3.35
billion.
   Ford's acquisitions spilled over into the automotive sector,
too. It bought Aston Martin in 1987 and bid $2.5 billion last month
for Jaguar. Ford officials have said they hope the Jaguar
acquisition is completed by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Reax 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0643,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Leaders Welcome Changes Yet Urge Caution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new graf 10 beg: `French President ...' with Mitterrand
quote. Picks up graf 10 pvs, `In Portugal ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's decision to open its borders to the West brought
accolades from world leaders, tempered with caution from some and
words of warning against too swift a move to reform.
   Hungary's Socialist Party annnounced its support of East
Germany's action and Ferenc Kosa, a member the party's presidium,
said ``the reforms now under way in East Germany will contribute to
the unfolding democratization in the whole region.''
   Hungary had been concerned about East German insensitivity to
Hungary's own reforms before the replacement of East Germany's
hard-line leader Erich Honecker last month by Egon Krenz.
   On Sept. 10, Hungary opened its borders to East Germans wishing
to emigrate to the West, and tens of thousands used this route to
flee their country before the dramatic announcement Thursday that
they would be permitted to travel straight to the West from East
Germany.
   In Warsaw, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told the Polish news
agency PAP the changes in East Germany ``should have been taken
much earlier.''
   ``The drama of the events in East Germany is the result of
earlier neglect, as usually happens when someone misses the train
of history,'' Walesa said.
   Czechoslovak Foreign Ministry spokesman Lubomir Marsik said the
opening of the East German border ``represents a positive
solution.''
   ``The situation was getting difficult for everybody, including
Czechoslovakia,'' he said, referring to the thousands of East
Germans who previously were forced to go West via a third country,
often Czechoslovakia.
   The United States, Britain and France offered their military
camps in West Germany to handle the expected flood of people from
the east.
   French President Francois Mitterrand said moves toward freedom
and democracy in Eastern Europe ``open a new phase in European
history'' and added he hoped to visit East Germany.
   In Portugal, the U.S. ambassador to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, William H. Taft IV, rejected speculation about
reunification and said the changes under way in Eastern Europe
increase the risk of instability.
   But Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnandze called the
border opening ``a reasonable and sensible decision'' and added
that Moscow was not worried that the pace of events in Eastern
Europe was a threat.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, however, said
the Soviet Union was concerned about instability brought on by the
exodus of East Germans to the West.
   Gerasimov stressed the border between East and West Germany
remained in force and that eased travel restrictions should not be
taken as heralding the imminent reunification of the two Germanies
split since the end of World War II.
   He warned that West Germany ``should take into account that
policies aimed at reconsidering borders would not suit any
government in Europe and would cause only mistrust.''
   It was ``a great day for freedom,'' said British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher. But the fast pace of reforms in East Germany
called ``for keeping a very cool head and being very steady and
being very practical about it,'' she added.
   Asked about the possibility of reunification, she replied, ``You
are going much too fast. You have to take these things step by
step. The first thing is to get a genuine multiparty democracy in
East Germany,'' the prime minister said.
   Prime Minister Harri Holkeri of Finland told Finnish radio, ``As
far as I can see, the final outcome of World War II still stands
and the situation will not change because of these developments.''
   The Belgian government, calling the move ``a victory for freedom
and democratic ideals,'' also urged caution.
   Mark Eyskens, the Belgian foreign minister, said: ``Those who
demand new frontiers are irresponsible. ... Measured progress is
required to avoid anarchy.''
   Also speaking in Brussels, the European Economic Community
External Affairs Commissioner Hans Andriessen said the East
European nations were not yet ready for EEC membership.
   But French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas said the thawing of
Eastern Europe creates obligations for the EEC.
   The West should reflect on ``these two or three new pieces of
data which are going to change the face of Europe and probably the
global balance,'' Dumas said.
   The West was now ``called upon to stretch out its hand even
further for cooperation to (remove) the economic deficit in East
Europe,'' said Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky.
   The Spanish government called for free elections and said East
Germany's decision ``opens a path of hope in the democratic
development of Europe.''
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said: ``We see this event
as part of an inevitable process which must lead to further reform,
free elections and full self-determination by the population.''
</TEXT>
