<FIRST>r a AM-WasteTrain     11-10 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waste Train,0343</SECOND>
<UNK>`Pooh Pooh Choo-Choo' Heading Back To Baltimore</UNK>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baltimore officials agreed Friday to take back
a trainload of sewage sludge after authorities in Louisiana and
Mississippi refused to let a disposal company unload the ``Pooh
Pooh Choo-Choo'' in their states.
   Mayor Kurt Schmoke felt that although Baltimore was not legally
obligated to take back the nonhazardous waste shipment, it did have
a moral obligation to do so, said George Balog, the city's public
works director.
   The first of the 63 carloads will begin arriving in about nine
days at the Back River waste treatment plant that produced the
sludge, he said. The 5,000 tons of sludge will be treated with lime
and then transferred to a facility that will mix the waste with
leaves and sell it as compost, he said.
   Back River is under a court order to reduce a backlog of sludge
at the plant.
   The cost of returning the sludge to Baltimore will be borne by
GSX Chemical Services of Columbia, S.C., Balog said.
   GSX contracted with the city to dispose of the sludge and
initially sent it to its waste treatment facility in White Castle,
La., but residents of Assumption Parish complained vehemently about
the stench.
   The company moved the train to Moss Point in southeast
Mississippi on Nov. 3, but Mississippi officials threatened to fine
GSX $2 million a day if the company didn't take it out of the state.
   GSX will get a chance to challenge the fines during a hearing
Nov. 21.
   Private landfills in a number of states were willing to accept
the shipment, but public officials refused to allow the waste in,
Balog said.
   ``The permitted landfills are there,'' he said. ``However,
because of this particular issue of this sludge train, it became so
controversial that state officials did not want to accept it.''
   In Arkansas, the Pollution Control and Ecology Department
obtained a temporary restraining order Thursday preventing a
landfill in Arkansas County from accepting the sludge.
</TEXT>
