<TEXT>
   }hzte administration
was too cautious, BAker said, ``We are extraordinarily happy about
it.''
   Comments in official Washington all day mixed caution with
exaltation.
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp, traveling
with the president, captured some of the exaltation in reporting on
a conversation with Bush during the flight to Dallas:
   ``We talked about East Germany and the thrill in our hearts and
minds of all people everywhere over what's happening with the
crumbling of the Berlin Wall,'' he said.
   ``We cannot house the world,'' said Kemp, ``but we can
definitely do our best to be compassionate'' and help West Germany
cope with the flood of refugees from the East.
   While some analysts predicted that some possible changes in
Europe could mean the breakup of NATO, U.S. officials like Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney did not go that far _ but conceded there
would be changes in the alliance.
   Meanwhile, important senators welcomed the changes in East
Germany and called for further liberalization, including free
elections.
   East Germany's ambassador, Gerhard Herder, said he found
President Bush's reaction to the events in Berlin ``encouraging''
but warned that any miscalculation in the Western reaction could
lead to ``bigger conflicts.''
   In a speech at the National Press Club, Herder promised that
East Germany would be ``a predictable partner'' for the West.
   He noted that the East German armed forces are only a short
distance away from the American, British and French forces
stationed in West Berlin.
   ``By any miscalculation, they could be involved. This could lead
to a conflict,'' he said.
   Asked whether he could foresee a unified Germany, Herder
replied: ``In my dreams, yes. But being a politician, I don't see
any prospect for a united Germany,'' because the two Germanies are
members of opposing alliances.
   The only action taken by the Bush administration has been an
offer of ``all possible assistance'' to the West German government
as it struggles to cope with the flood of refugees. The Pentagon
said it was making available housing for 980 people in three
off-base installations.
   ``Were we surprised by the speed of it?'' Baker asked in a
separate interview on CBS. ``You bet your life.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said in a statement, ``East Germany should
also hold truly democratic elections.''
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a former committee chairman, said
the East German authorities may be intent on getting rid of ``the
bad eggs'' before moving to restore the hard-line system.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the ``very positive''
changes, if they led to non-Communist governments in the East,
would mean ``less of a threat'' and that in turn ``might portend
some changes on our side.''
   One change, said retired Gen. Bernard Rogers, a former NATO
commander, would be fewer U.S. troops in Europe _ there are 340,000
now _ and a revision in the ``forward strategy'' that puts fighting
units close to the border.
</TEXT>
