<DOCNO> AP891110-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-India-RuralVote Adv17   11-10 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Rural Vote, Adv 17,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Nov. 17 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rural Vote Most Important in Indian Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, note elections are Nov. 22-26.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANOLI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 45-year-old Savitri Devi, the routine
of cooking, drawing water from the well, cleaning her one-story
brick house and taking an afternoon nap soon will be broken _ but
only for a time.
   Later this month, millions like Devi in India's farming villages
will decide who should govern their country.
   The burden of choosing rests lightly on Devi's shoulders.
   ``I'll vote for whomever my husband votes for,'' she says in
Hindi, sitting in the warmth of the sun on a rope cot outside her
home.
   More than three-fourths of India's 498 million voters live in
villages, making the rural vote the most important electoral bank
for any party in the elections for Parliament and prime minister
Nov, 22, 24 and 26.
   Devi expresses resentment at the governing Congress Party, which
she blames for the high price of sugar and the cutting down of the
forest outside the village.
   The men of Sanoli, a village of 2,000 people 70 miles southwest
of New Delhi, talk of wider issues, but their political leanings
soon escalate into arguments.
   The village is in the northern state of Rajasthan and has
usually been considered a Congress Party stronghold.
   ``These people do not know what they are talking about,'' says
72-year-old Hari Krishan Sharma, the village priest, referring to a
group of villagers who derided his support for the Congress Party.
``I am a wise elephant surrounded by barking dogs.
   ``What will you give water to? To a tree firmly planted in the
soil or to a sapling which will be blown away in the next storm?''
   The question was intended to illustrate Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's promise of stable government _ the firmly planted tree _
if he and his Congress Party are returned to power.
   But others sitting on a raised platform outside the village
temple were unconvinced.
   Budh Ram, a wiry mustachioed farmer, said two years of rule by
the opposition had given more to the village than the 39 years of
rule by the Congress Party.
   ``We voted the Congress to power in the last elections. The
candidate is my sister's brother-in-law. But he hasn't visited the
village once in these five years. He'll be routed this time,'' Ram
said.
   ``Only senile old men like him will vote for the Congress now,''
he said, gesturing toward Sharma.
   Usually divided opposition parties have united for the second
time in history to fight the Congress Party.
   The previous attempt was briefly successful, when the opposition
dislodged the Congress Party from power in 1977, ousting Rajiv
Gandhi's mother, Indira Gandhi, from the prime minister's office.
But the fragile unity soon disentegrated and midterm polls were
called in 1980, which were won by the Congress Party and Mrs.
Gandhi returned and was assassinated four years later.
   The opposition is focusing this year on its charges of
corruption and inept leadership by Rajiv Gandhi, who succeeded his
mother in 1984.
   The viewpoint has been brought to Sanoli by word-of-mouth or
read in newspapers by the few literate people in the village.
Television and radio are controlled by the state and little
anti-governement news is broadcast.
   ``The people tilling the fields go to sleep hungry,'' Ram said.
``The Congress lives luxuriously and spends fortunes in hotels.
Where has the money from Bofors gone?''
   The reference was to opposition charges that senior Congress
politicians and government officials received millions of dollars
in kickbacks from the Swedish firm, AB Bofors, for a $1.4 billion
contract to supply artillery to the Indian army.
   The charges have become a rallying cry for the opposition.
Gandhi has denied the charges and says he is not personally
involved.
   Another issue is the government's involvement in the ethnic
strife in neighboring Sri Lanka, where at least 1,100 Indian
soldiers sent to restore peace have been killed in fighting Tamil
rebels.
   The issue is live in Sanoli because five young men from the
village have died in Sri Lanka.
   ``Gandhi sent our children to Sri Lanka,'' said Sher Singh, who
runs a small grocery store. ``Why did we have to go to another
man's home? I don't blame the Sri Lankans. I'll kill anyone who
interferes in my home.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday PMs, Nov. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
