<DOCNO> AP891110-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Britain-Heseltine Adv16   11-10 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Heseltine, Adv 16,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Nov. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Michael Heseltine Seen as Thatcher's Successor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost four years after he stomped out of a
Cabinet meeting and resigned from Margaret Thatcher's government,
Michael Heseltine remains the man voted most likely to succeed her
as Britain's prime minister.
   Despite tumbling opinion polls, Mrs. Thatcher shows no signs of
slowing down after 10 years in power, however, and says she hopes
to lead the Conservatives into one more general election before
retiring.
   Heseltine, who is 56 years old and has a huge personal fortune,
can afford to wait.
   In the meantime, the lean, 6-foot-3 Heseltine with his
movie-star good looks is in big demand as a public speaker.
   He speaks with a slight lisp, suffers from the reading
impairment dyslexia, has great personal charm and, despite the
years out of office, ranks among the half dozen best-known
politicians in Britain.
   His thick mane of blond hair and sometimes swashbuckling
escapades earned him the nickname ``Tarzan,'' and it has stuck. He
once lifted the ceremonial mace in the House of Commons and swung
it around his head, and as defense secretary donned fatigues to try
out new weapons firsthand, usually in front of the television
cameras.
   Other Conservatives in Parliament _ who will eventually select
Mrs. Thatcher's replacement as the party leader _ in particular
want him to speak to their local party gatherings.
   That will one day enable him to ``call in the IOUs,'' the
Spectator magazine said.
   Heseltine has been careful not to attack Mrs. Thatcher directly.
   His usual response when asked whether he wants to succeed her is
the bland observation that there are 350 Conservative members of
Parliament who want to lead the party.
   He also has avoided public recriminations about the dispute over
an obscure helicopter-maker, Westland PLC, which led to his
resignation as defense secretary in January 1986.
   Heseltine favored a European consortium's rescue bid for the
ailing company over the eventual winner, the American Sikorsky
company. But when ordered by Mrs. Thatcher to clear his statements
with the Cabinet, he walked out.
   She, too, was nearly forced out, when the dispute escalated over
the leaking by government officials of documents designed to
discredit Heseltine's argument.
   Heseltine, who is pro-European, while Mrs. Thatcher is combative
toward the European Economic Community, and to the left of her
within the party, indulges in coded criticisms of her policies.
   He has called for more money to be put into inner city and
educational reforms and has said Mrs. Thatcher's property tax,
which taxes individuals rather than households, will become known
as an unpopular ``Tory tax.''
   He said the government's last interest rate increase was
necessary to combat inflation, but he told a recent luncheon of
American journalists that ``whether we should have got into that
situation is really the issue.''
   At the Conservative Party's annual conference, he told the
government ``not to let the medicine drag out, dissipating our
economic strength and dispersing our political support.''
   Perhaps most significantly, Heseltine believes Britain should
join the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System,
which limits swings in nine other European currencies.
   Opinion polls indicate Heseltine is the voters' choice to
replace Mrs. Thatcher as the Tory leader.
   A National Opinion Poll conducted for the newspaper The Mail on
Sunday said 31 percent of 1,043 voters questioned believe Heseltine
would be the best person to succeed her. The next closest candidate
was Sir Geoffrey Howe, the deputy prime minister, with 17 percent.
   British Broadcasting Corp. television surveyed Conservative
lawmakers and found 22 percent would like Heseltine to succeed Mrs.
Thatcher, followed by 14 percent for party Chairman Kenneth Baker.
   Heseltine was born in Swansea, Wales, the son of an army
officer, and educated at a private boys' school and Oxford
University.
   At Oxford, he told friends he would be a millionaire by the age
of 30 and then go into politics. He made a fortune in the
publishing business before being elected to Parliament in 1966.
   He and his family own 51 percent of Haymarket Press, and British
news reports estimate he is worth 60 million pounds ($94 million).
He divides his time, with his wife, Anne, between an 800-acre
estate north of Oxford and an elegant townhouse in London's
exclusive Belgravia neighborhood. They have two grown daughters and
a son.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Nov. 16</NOTE>
