<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     11-10 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0847</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in October
as the biggest spurt in food costs in 22 months offset the positive
effects from moderating energy prices, the government reported.
   The 0.4 percent October rise in the Labor Department's Producer
Price Index on Thursday was down from a 0.9 percent September
increase. Some economists predicted the news will continue to
improve in coming months as a slowing economy takes more pressure
off prices.
   For the first 10 months of the year, prices at the wholesale
level have been rising at an annual rate of 5.2 percent, compared
to an increase of 4 percent in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Governor Wayne D. Angell
said the central bank needs to reduce inflation to about 3 percent
in 1990 and he expects to meet that goal in the first half of the
year.
   Inflation has been falling since the Fed began tightening credit
in 1988 to slow the economy. The Fed began easing credit in May and
nudged short-term interest rates lower earlier this week. Angell
made his comments Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers are completing a corn harvest
estimated at a three-year high of 7.59 billion bushels, up 54
percent from last year's drought-reduced crop and up 2 percent from
the forecast a month ago, the Agriculture Department said.
   Drought reduced the 1988 corn crop to 4.92 billion bushels, the
department said Thursday. In October, the department estimated this
year's production at 7.45 billion bushels, a 51 percent increase
from last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Treasury Secretary Donald Regan told a
House panel a planned bill to limit program trading doesn't go far
enough and suggested a total ban on one form of the market
strategy: index arbitrage.
   Regan, head of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. before becoming Treasury
secretary under Ronald Reagan, on Thursday was part of a panel of
investment company executives that called for restraining program
trading, but split over what action Congress should take.
   ``The problem we're addressing is volatility, not the program
trading problem,'' Philip J. Purcell, chairman of Dean Witter
Financial Services Inc., told a subcommittee of the House Energy
and Commerce Committee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Stock Exchange President John J. Phelan
Jr. said the Big Board had begun ``major investigations'' into
potential violations involving computerized stock trading
strategies.
   Phelan said Thursday the probe involves trading in both the New
York securities and Chicago futures exchanges and is focusing on an
illegal financial market strategy known as ``front-running.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Wang Laboratories Inc., declaring
computers no longer represent a boom industry, announced his
company would undergo a ``fundamental reordering'' and cut 2,000
more workers from its payroll.
   The cutback, announced Thursday, was the latest sign of a
high-tech industry slowdown that has contributed to a softening of
the region's economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has approved a smoking ban for
nearly all domestic airline flights, a broadening of restrictions
that signals a victory by health advocates over tobacco interests.
   The prohibition, fought strenuously earlier this year by the
cigarette industry and lawmakers from tobacco states, was adopted
on a voice vote Thursday with no comments by outnumbered opponents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police charged 10 men and two major investment
firms with fraud in a $1.3 billion stock sale connected with Blue
Arrow PLC's 1987 takeover of Manpower Inc., the world's largest
temporary employment firm.
   The charges Thursday apparently stem from the investment firm
County Natwest's failure to properly disclose that it retained a
13.4 percent stake in Blue Arrow after a sale of Blue Arrow stock
flopped.
   County Natwest, a unit of Britain's largest bank, National
Westminster PLC, had helped arrange the sale of Blue Arrow shares
to existing Blue Arrow shareholders to finance the $1.34 billion
takeover of Milwaukee, Wis.-based Manpower.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. may sell some of its businesses
or other assets in a bid to streamline the company and strengthen
its bottom line, Campbell's two-man interim management team said.
   Campbell's five-year plan also includes a $2 billion investment
in plant modernization and aggressive moves to grab more of the
convenience-food market, executive vice presidents Herbert M. Baum
and Edwin L. Harper said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back Thursday after the rally of the two
preceding sessions faltered amid worries about corporate earnings.
The Dow Jones industrial average, which had risen more than 41
points Tuesday and Wednesday, dropped 19.67 to 2,603.69.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies except the
Japanese yen and Canadian dollar.
   Bond prices finished slightly lower.
   Copper prices continued a surge; grain was mostly lower and
soybeans higher; energy and sugar futures were higher; gold was off
while silver gained; livestock and pork futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
