<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-Inflation     11-10 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Inflation,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Governor Expects Inflation to Drop to 3 Percent in 1990</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Layoff Jitters, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Governor Wayne D. Angell
says the central bank needs to reduce inflation to about 3 percent
in 1990 and he expects to meet that goal in the first half of the
year.
   Inflation has been falling since the Fed began tightening credit
in 1988 to slow the economy. The Fed began easing credit in May and
nudged short-term interest rates lower earlier this week.
   But Angell's comments, made to reporters after a speech Thursday
to the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, appeared
to indicate the Fed might not be prepared to cut interest rates
further in the immediate future.
   Angell told the accountants he supports a pending House bill
that would mandate that the central bank eliminate inflation by
1994. Fed Chairman Allan Greenspan endorsed the proposal last month
in an appearance before the House Banking monetary policy
subcommittee.
   Inflation as measured by the Consumer Price Index had dropped to
an annual rate of 4.3 percent by September, a level Angell told
reporters still was too high.
   The bill calling for zero inflation was introduced by the
monetary policy subcommittee chairman, Rep. Neal L. Smith, D-N.C.
It does not include any penalty for failing to reach that level.
   It was supported at a subcommittee hearing Thursday by former
Fed Gov. Lyle E. Gramley, who called it a ``desirable'' statement
of priorities for monetary policy. He added, ``I would not hold out
hope that its passage would greatly simplify the achievement of a
noninflationary economy.''
   The subcommittee also is considering a bill introduced by Reps.
Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., and Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., designed to reduce
the independence of the Fed.
   That bill would require the Fed's policy-setting Open Market
Committeeto meet three times a year with the Treasury secretary and
the president's budget director and chief economic adviser, allow
the president to appoint the Fed chairman a year after taking
office, immediately disclose any changes in monetary policy
targets, permit Government Accounting Office audits of Fed
operations and require publication of the Fed budget.
   The Hamilton-Dorgan bill has been criticized as ``politicizing''
the central bank but Hamilton described it at Thursday's hearing as
a ``responsible way'' to make the independent Fed accountable to
the public.
   Gramley, however, said he generally opposes the Hamilton-Dorgan
bill because ``the Federal Reserve's independence from the
administrative branch needs to be preserved.''
   James Tobin, a Nobel laureate and economics professor at Yale
University, endorsed several of the Hamilton-Dorgan proposals
including presidential appointment of the Fed chairman a year after
taking office. Tobin said he would expand administration
participation in Fed policy-making to all meetings of the Open
Market Committee.
   But he rejected mandating immediate announcement of policy
decisions and said terms of the central bank governors should be
reduced from 14 years to 10, and board membership cut from seven to
five.
   Tobin also recommended that the president name the heads of the
district Fed banks, subject to Senate confirmation. The district
presidents now are selected by the directors of the member banks,
subject to approval by the Fed governors, and alternate as members
of the Open Market Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 0127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Barley-Oats     11-10 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barley-Oats,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Rejects Price-Support Boost For Barley, Oats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has rejected as too
costly proposals to boost government price supports for barley and
oats, which have been in declining production despite increased
consumer demand.
   Health concerns have triggered consumer demand for cereal
grains, particulary for oat products, including oatmeal, bran and
flour.
   As a result of smaller harvests in recent years, the United
States has had to import oats from Canada and other foreign
suppliers to meet demand.
   Bills Congress is considering would cost the government $130
million in higher payments for barley and an additional,
unspecified amount for oats, said Keith Bjerke, administrator of
the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service.
   Selected increases in target prices for barley and oats could
``lead to detrimental effects for producers and consumers of other
program crops and lead to expanded federal outlays,'' Bjerke told a
House Agriculture subcommittee.
   Target prices are goals set in the government's crop programs to
help determine direct subsidies to farmers when market prices are
down.
   Bjerke said Thursday the Agriculture Department is taking some
steps to stimulate oats production, which has not kept pace with
the demand generated by the grain's reported health benefits,
forcing the United States to import nearly 30 percent of its
production.
   Congress should wait to change target prices until it rewrites
the government's multiyear farm program next year, Bjerke said.
   Producers claim subsidies for barley and oats are relatively low
in comparison to price supports for wheat, corn and sorghum. The
cost of producing barley and oats actually exceeds the price
farmers can get, one economist testified.
   ``Farmers have had strong incentives to produce crops that have
high target prices relative to costs,'' said Martin Abel, who
represented the National Association of Barley Growers.
   ``Conversely, they have had much less incentive to produce crops
with low target prices relative to costs, namely barley and oats.''
   The subsidy for barley is too low because the Agriculture
Department calculates it by combining the market prices for malting
barley and feed barley, which brings up to 50 cents less per
bushel, producers say.
   Lagging oats production is blamed both on low target prices and
planting restrictions in the farm program that discourage farmers
from switching to oats from other crops.
   In addition, the Conservation Reserve Program, which pays
farmers not to plant crops on highly erodible land, has taken a
disproportionate amount of oats acerage out of production, said
John Bollingberg, a Bremen, N.D., farmer representing the American
Oat Association.
   The U.S. imported 60 million bushels of oats, or 28 percent of
its production, last year during the drought, he said in testimony
prepared for the committee. While U.S. oat production is expected
to rebound slightly this year, imports are still expected to reach
40 million bushels, he said.
   The government does not expect to make any deficiency payments
for oats next year because market prices are expected to be higher
than the $1.45 target price, Bjerke said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
