<SECOND>PM-Viacom-Stations,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Viacom Buying Radio Stations In Denver, Los Angeles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Broadcasting Inc. has agreed to buy the
radio stations KJOI-AM in Los Angeles and KSYY-FM and KHOW-AM in
Denver for $101.5 million from Command Communications, the
companies announced.
   Viacom Broadcasting, a unit of the entertainment and media giant
Viacom International Inc., already owns and operates five
television and nine radio stations in various markets and has
purchases of two other radio stations pending.
   Command Communications was formed by Carl C. Brazell Jr. and
Robert F.X. Sillerman, who is president and chief executive of the
media group Sillerman Companies.
   The sale, announced Thursday, leaves Command with KRLD-AM in
Dallas and the Texas State Network, a radio broadcasting network.
Sillerman Companies has extensive interests in other radio
broadcasting companies as well as a non-voting stake in Command.
   Henry S. Schleiff, chairman and chief executive of Viacom's
broadcasting and entertainment groups, said the acquisitions of the
three stations were made under Viacom's strategy of buying
properties in major radio markets nationwide.
   Bill Figenshu, president of Viacom Broadcasting's radio
division, said the company did not expect to make management or
format changes in any of the three stations.
   The purchase was expected to be completed later this year,
pending approval by the Federal Communications Commission and the
boards of the respective companies.
