<FIRST>r f PM-Penney-Philippines Bjt   11-10 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penney-Philippines, Bjt,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Penney Ready To Benefit From Repositioning as it Welcomes Aquino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDISON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino isn't
exactly hawking J.C. Penney Co. wares today, but the nation's
fourth-largest retailer is enjoying the attention brought by her
interest in its ``Festival of the Philippines'' promotion.
   Mrs. Aquino is scheduled for an afternoon tour of an exhibit
hall featuring some of the $110 million worth of Filipino products
Penney will market during the promotion next May.
   Since learning of the Texas-based retailer's plans, she has been
anxious to be involved in the campaign, said W. Barger Tygart,
Penney's director of merchandising.
   Penney has invited about 2,000 people to the reception at a posh
Dallas hotel. Joining Penney Chairman William G. Howell as hosts
will be multimillionaire developer Trammell Crow and Texas Gov.
Bill Clements.
   On Saturday, Mrs. Aquino, who is in the United States on a
political visit, will tour a Penney store in an upscale north
Dallas mall it anchors along with such stores as Neiman-Marcus and
Lord &amp; Taylor.
   The ``Festival of the Philippines'' is the latest international
promotion for Penney. Such events are becoming annual affairs for
the company, with previous promotions centering on Great Britain,
India and Italy.
   The Filipino promotion also reflects the new emphasis at Penney:
apparel and soft home furnishings.
   In 1983, Penney began eliminating automotive, electronics and
hard goods from its stores, a decision that cost $1.5 billion in
revenue, Howell said, but put the company ``more in sync with what
American consumers expect at J.C. Penney's.''
   ``J.C. Penney is truly positioned as the middle income
department store of the country,'' said Thomas Tashjian, a retail
analyst at Seidler Amdec Securities Inc. in Los Angeles.
   ``The company is the largest occupant of mall space in the
country and what it has done is it has adjusted its merchandising
strategy to serve that mall customer,'' who is mainly female and
mainly looking for clothes, Tashjian said.
   Although founder James Cash Penney's original Golden Rule stores
focused on soft goods, ``they had taken a detour for a time into
hard goods ... when they saw Sears being very successful in hard
goods,'' Tashjian said.
   Apparel now accounts for 82 percent of Penney sales, with
women's apparel at 42 percent of total sales. In 1981, apparel was
63 percent, with women's at 30 percent. Home and leisure goods have
fallen from 37 percent in 1981 to 18 percent last year.
   Howell has predicted that by 1993, overall apparel sales will
make up 72 percent of total sales.
   Despite an industry-wide slump in apparel sales, Penney sales so
far this year have rebounded to $10.13 billion through Oct. 28, an
8.2 percent increase from the same time last year.
   With the busy holiday season upcoming, the company already has
reached 68 percent of last year's retail sales, and 66 percent of
its record 1987 sales.
   And when third-quarter earnings are released Tuesday, ``I don't
think we're going to disappoint anybody,'' Howell said in an
interview this week at the company's temporary headquarters in
Addison, a corporate suburb on Dallas's northern border to which it
moved from New York last year before it settles in nearby Plano.
Analysts are looking for earnings of $1.40 to $1.50 per share
compared with last year's $1.16.
   ``They're doing very well,'' said Jeffrey Edelman, a retail
analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York. ``Last year
they were cleaning out the store of merchandise they didn't want,
and this year they're filling it up with merchandise they want.''
   Led by Howell, analysts said, Penney's management has become
aggressive and pays more attention to market research than some of
its competitors. Howell frequently recites those findings in
explaining his company's operations.
   ``We're going to change, because the American consumer is going
to change,'' he said. But he believes Penney already is ahead of
its competition in the race for future sales.
   ``We have faith that we have a competitive advantage, that J.C.
Penney will be one of the survivors, with a triple threat of
retail, catalog and television,'' Howell said.
   While about 80 percent of Penney's sales come from in-store
purchases, its Shop Television Network on cable TV presents
well-known celebrities hawking J.C. Penney products. Its
shop-by-mail catalog provides the rest of its sales.
</TEXT>
