<FIRST>u f PM-TravelinginStyle Bjt   11-10 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Traveling in Style, Bjt,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luxury Train Completes Inaugural Run</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first luxury passenger train in
decades rolled into town three minutes late, but its owner said the
enterprise wouldn't leave him a dollar short.
   ``This is kind of like the country club without the golf
course,'' said William Spann. ``If this doesn't work, the message
will be loud and clear: Americans don't care how they travel. I bet
a considerable sum of money they do.''
   The American-European Express completed its 17-hour inaugural
run to Chicago from Washington, D.C., on Thursday.
   The fur- and silk-clad guests rode in grand style by invitation,
but regular passengers will pay a grand and more for the privilege
of sinking into overstuffed chairs in the lush club car and tucking
in seven-course meals served from plates that ring when flicked
with a manicured fingernail.
   Kevin Keefe, associate editor of Trains Magazine and an expert
on passenger-train travel, said the American-European Express may
prove to be a financial success.
   ``It's ... an exciting prospect for people traveling by train in
the grand manner,'' he said in an interview from Milwaukee. ``It
harkens back to a time when traveling on a long-distance train .. .
was an experience to be savored.''
   He added: ``It's much fancier than what you get on Amtrak.''
   A jazz band blared ``Chattanooga Choo-Choo'' as the guests
disembarked at Union Station.
   Most seemed suitably impressed.
   ``Instead of the hurry-itis we usually have, I feel like I've
been on a little vacation,'' said North Carolinian Bonnie
McElveen-Hunter as she clutched her full-length fur to shield her
from a chilling Chicago wind. ``It's a return to yesteryear. We
need that.''
   ``This was the perfect opportunity to do something different,''
said Washington attorney Patrick Keeley.
   ``It was a European travel experience,'' said his wife, Regina,
who nonetheless acknowledged, ``putting on mascara was kind of
difficult.''
   American-European Express will run two five-car trains between
Chicago and Washington _ one going each way _ six days a week. The
first regular run will be Wednesday.
   Most of its rail cars were built in the 1940s and '50s, many by
the Pullman Co. The interior decorating is anything but plebeian.
   Pianist Bill Andrew will play requests on the grand piano in the
Art Deco-inspired club car, where the brass window trim is
complemented by ``faux tortoise'' leather wainscoting. Dinner is
served on fine china with damask table linens.
   As could be expected, luxury travel doesn't come cheap. A
double-occupancy fare runs about $1,042, while booking the train's
Presidential Cabin will cost $1,450.
   The fancy trains will be pulled behind Amtrak trains for a
``fancy fee'' _ an example of Amtrak's creativity in raising money,
Keefe said.
   Spann said American-European Express invested about $1 million
per car in refurbishing but expects to turn a profit.
   ``We have 26 rooms with an average price of $1,000,'' he said.
``On an average night, what you really want to achieve is somewhere
between $18,000 and $24,000 in sales. If you do that, you can pay
for this investment.''
   Spann said there are still a few wrinkles to iron out.
   ``There's no Kleenex in the rooms,'' he reflected. ``You spend
millions of dollars and forget the Kleenex.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
