<FIRST>r f PM-CampbellSoup     11-10 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campbell Soup,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convenience Food, Perhaps Sale of Food Groups Ahead for Campbell</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-year plan for Campbell Soup Co. calls for
aggressive moves to grab more of the convenience food market and
the possible sale of some food subsidiaries, the company's interim
management team says.
   ``Business is an evolving thing,'' said Edwin Harper, who serves
with Herbert Baum as executive vice president. ``There are some
assets we don't really need.''
   Campbell owns Pepperidge Farm, Vlasic Foods, Mrs. Paul's
Kitchens, Godiva Chocolatier and Casera Foods.
   ``Some businesses in my opinion are near the borderline,'' Baum
added during a news conference here Thursday, the two officials'
first since being named to oversee Campbell's day-to-day operations
Nov. 1.
   Convenience-food marketing and plant-modernization will require
a $2 billion investment over the next five years, they said.
   Baum and Harper took over temporarily for R. Gordon McGovern,
the company's president and chief executive, who stepped down after
nine years. Campbell's board had been unhappy with the company's
performance in recent years, and there had been rumors that it
might be sold.
   Both Baum and Harper are candidates to succeed McGovern. Baum
said board Chairman Robert J. Vlasic has indicated the selection
process would be completed by early next year.
   In September, Campbell reported fiscal 1989 earnings of $13
million on sales of $5.72 billion compared to earnings of $274
million on sales of $4.87 billion the previous year. The company
attributed the earnings decline to a $343 million charge related to
a corporate restructuring that involved the closing of
manufacturing plants in New Jersey, Maryland and Tennessee,
eliminating 2,800 jobs.
   Harper called the restructuring ``a pretty thorough
housecleaning'' but both he and Baum indicated further cuts may be
needed.
   Campbell, based in Camden, N.J., is the nation's largest
soupmaker. It sells about 5 billion cans a year, which represents
about 65 percent of the $2.2 billion retail soup market.
   Harper, who was promoted from executive vice president and chief
financial officer, is overseeing Campbell's foreign operations. He
said the company is developing a strategy for modernization of its
facilities worldwide.
</TEXT>
