<FIRST>r f PM-ChemicalMove     11-10 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Move,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>3,000 Jobs May Go to New Jersey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks are underway between the city and Chemical
Banking Corp. to try to persuade the company not to move 3,000 jobs
to New Jersey.
   ``I think we've made perfectly clear that Chemical is a very
important corporation here in the city of New York and that we will
make available our entire array of people and resources to keep
them in New York,'' said Stanley E. Grayson, the deputy mayor for
finance and economic development.
   He said Thursday that discussions began anew after Chemical
pulled out of the multibillion-dollar Times Square redevelopment
project last spring.
   The bank's lease at its Park Avenue headquarters and offices in
Rockefeller Center expire in 1994. Chemical officials have been
studying various options for 18 months, including a new building in
nearby Secaucus, N.J., said Charles Salmans, a bank spokesman.
   ``For some of our staff we have examined New Jersey sites as
well as New York sites,'' he said.
   The city has battled recently to keep companies such as Chase
Manhattan Corp. and NBC in the city. Earlier this year, Merrill
Lynch announced it would move 2,500 back-office employees to Jersey
City, N.J., and Exxon Corp. said it would move 300 employees from
its New York headquarters to Dallas.
   In an Oct. 25 letter to city officials, Chemical senior vice
president Peter Brooke said the bank has enjoyed below-market
rents, but would face ``an extraordinary increase in expenses'' if
it wanted to renew.
   ``Consequently, a plan has been developed which retains a small
`flagship' headquarters facility in Manhattan containing staff who
have an absolute need to be located there,'' the letter said. ``All
other staff would be located in a second facility in New Jersey.''
   Salmans said the letter was written in response to a request
from city officials for ``a listing of all of the areas of the bank
that might potentially be relocated to New Jersey.''
   The list adds up to about 3,000 of the 4,700 employees at the
two sites, Salmans said.
   ``No decisions have been taken, but we did reach a point where
we needed to get an understanding from officials of the city of New
York for what incentives might be available to us to factor into
how we looked at the cost of various alternatives,'' Salmans said.
   Grayson said Chemical officials have indicated a willingness to
move operations to a borough outside Manhattan.
   The bank also has discussed a non-binding option with Hartz
Mountain Industries to construct in Secaucus a building of a
million square feet or more, Salmans said.
   The state and city put together a $235 million package last year
to keep Chase from moving 5,000 jobs to New Jersey.
   Asked if Chemical might expect a similar deal, Grayson said, ``I
don't believe that is a responsible way for us to act, where the
last deal becomes a starting point for the next deal. With
discussion with firms, I think they very much understand that.''
   He said the final package would depend on the site chosen and
``what's in the best interest of the city.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
