<FIRST>u f PM-Keating 1stLd-Writethru f0025 11-10 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Keating, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Keating Claim Against Government Heading For Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2, U.S. District Judge, to say first hearing to be
held Dec. 7-8. Subs last graf to CORRECT $2.5 billion to more than $150
billion.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phoenix financier Charles H. Keating Jr.'s
claim that federal regulators wrongfully seized the Lincoln Savings
and Loan Association apparently will get a full hearing in court.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin on Thursday ordered the
first of a series of hearings Dec. 7-8 on Keating's lawsuit
challenge of the federal takeover in April of the insolvent S&amp;L.
The takeover is estimated to cost the taxpayers $2 billion.
   Sporkin, the former enforcement chief of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, said Keating and government witnesses are
likely to be summoned to the hearing. He said the session will
enable him to ``test a few things'' on whether the case merits a
full trial, which could take two years or longer.
   Sporkin had said Wednesday that ``I need a chance to figure
things out. ... Mr. Keating's going to take the stand. You're
entitled to a day in court.''
   Government attorneys had initially opposed Sporkin's suggestion
that Keating be heard in court, asking instead that the judge
dismiss the lawsuit on the basis of the administrative record used
by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board in deciding to seize Lincoln.
   Under the arrangement ordered by Sporkin, testimony will be
taken on only a small sample of the real estate transactions
reflected by that 4,000-page record.
   James Murphy, an attorney for the Office of Thrift Supervision,
confirmed the government ``will call Mr. Keating and one or more of
our (bank) examiners.''
   Keating is chairman of the American Continental Corp., which was
Lincoln's parent company. The government argues American
Continental looted $94 million from Lincoln's depositors with bogus
land investments. Murphy called it ``one of the worst of the
worst'' cases of fraud and abuse in the nation's S&amp;L history.
   There have been estimates that the federal bailout of the thrift
industry may cost more than $150 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
