<HEAD>IBM Expected to Announce Shipments of Delayed Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is
expected to announce on Tuesday a new generation of data-storage
devices that have been delayed for months by expensive technical
problems.
   The disk drives for mainframe computers account for about
one-tenth of IBM's $60 billion in annual revenue. The delay in the
new models past the original July announcement date was blamed for
contributing to IBM's 30 percent drop in third-quarter profits.
   Stephen Cohen, an analyst at SoundView Financial Group in
Stamford, Conn., said he understood from talking to IBM customers
that IBM has not entirely solved the technical problem, so
large-scale shipments probably won't begin until the second quarter
of 1990.
   The problem apparently comes from inconsistent quality in a part
from an outside supplier, Cohen said today.
   IBM spokesman Amos Kerisch confirmed today that IBM was holding
a news conference Tuesday about data-storage devices for mainframe
computers, but declined to comment further.
</TEXT>
