<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet-Fire 3rdLd-Writethru f0057 11-10 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street-Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0057,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Openings Delayed Because of Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from SIAC; minor editing, no
pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading opened an hour late today at the New
York and American stock exchanges because of a fire beneath a
building that houses a key computer system.
   Trading in certain stock-related futures contracts in Chicago
also was temporarily disrupted due to the difficulties in New York.
   A spokeswoman at the American Stock Exchange said a fire in a
lower Manhattan building that houses the Securities Industry
Automation Corp. made it impossible to process information,
delaying the usual 9:30 a.m. EST opening of stock trading.
   A spokesman for the Securities Industry Automation Corp., which
processes trades for the exchanges, said the fire did not affect
trading systems. John Lafayette, the spokesman, said that
uncertainty about the power supply led the company to suspend
operations and switch to an emergency power source at 9:15 a.m. EST.
   Still, trading did not begin on the American and New York stock
exchanges until 10:30 a.m.
   A Fire Department spokesman said the two-alarm blaze erupted in
an electrical vault below the building. The first alarm sounded at
8:04 a.m.
   The fire was under control by 9:48 a.m. and extinguished shortly
after. Firefighters searched each of the building's 53 floors, and
the spokesman said a haze of light smoke had filtered through the
building.
   The lobby and the second floor of the building were evacuated
and some tenants on higher floors had lost power.
   No injuries were reported.
   In addition to the stock exchanges, the Chicago Board of Trade
and Chicago Mercantile Exchange, which trade stock-index futures,
also suffered trading disruptions.
   Trading in the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock index futures
contract on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange was delayed one hour
and reopened when stock trading began in New York.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, trading in the major market stock
index futures contract opened as usual but had to be halted for 40
minutes until trading opened in New York.
</TEXT>
