<FIRST>r f BC-AT&amp;T-International     11-10 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AT&amp;T-International,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Announces Cheaper International Toll-Free Feature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. is making it cheaper for
businesses to offer international 800 service, which allows their
customers to call them toll-free from outside the United States.
   As of Dec. 11, U.S. customers of AT&amp;T will be able to receive
toll-free calls from 41 countries on regular telephone lines
instead of through special, so-called ``dedicated'' lines, the
company said Thursday.
   MCI Communications Corp. has offered long-distance toll-free
service on regular as well as dedicated lines for about a year,
said MCI spokesman Steve Johnson in Arlington, Va.
   ``AT&amp;T is trying to catch up to us,'' he said. ``AT&amp;T has been
responding to this capability that's been in place for more than a
year at MCI.''
   MCI offers toll-free service from 15 countries, he said.
   Another competitor, US Sprint Communications Co., offers
toll-free service only from Canada, although it plans to expand to
other countries by mid-1990, said spokesman Greg Finch.
   AT&amp;T subscribers currently pay $266.50 to install a dedicated
line, plus a one-time $99 fee for each country included and a
monthly service charge of $36.70.
   Through the new feature, subscribers will pay a one-time
start-up fee of $43.50, which includes service to one country, $99
for each additional country and a $20 monthly charge.
   Fees for the actual telephone time will remain the same,
however. For example, it currently costs $96 for the first 10 hours
of calls from France, and $90 for the next 24 hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
