<FIRST>r f BC-ShipyardClosing     11-10 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shipyard Closing,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,500 May Lose Jobs Unless Shipyard Is Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacksonville Shipyards Inc. said it
will close in January, idling up to 1,500 workers, unless a buyer
is found within the next 60 days.
   The shipyard, owned by Green Bay, Wis.-based Terex Corp., began
notifying workers Thursday as required by the federal plant-closing
law.
   Terex said in a statement that it was negotiating with several
potential buyers but no firm bids had surfaced.
   ``We believe that a transaction may be concluded prior to the
end of the 60-day notice period,'' the statement said.
   Jacksonville Shipyards has been steadily losing money over the
past several years, according to Terex Controller Jim Kettinger.
   Terex acquired Jacksonville Shipyards in July when it purchased
the maritime and truck trailer divisions of Fruehauf Corp. for $231
million. Terex announced at that time it would sell the shipyards
but retain the truck trailer manufacturing division.
   Employment at the 106-year-old ship-repairing company fluctuates
between 1,000 and 1,500 workers.
</TEXT>
