<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-LayoffJitters Bjt   11-10 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Layoff Jitters, Bjt,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Say Recent Layoffs Don't Presage Recession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists say a recent wave of layoffs at
major U.S. companies reflects sluggishness rather than an imminent,
severe shakeout in the nation's economy.
   Wang Laboratories Inc., Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Chrysler
Corp., Unisys Corp. and Campbell Soup Co. have announced major
layoffs in recent days.
   But William D. Anderson, an economist at Penn State University's
College of Business Administration, sees evidence of only a
slowdown.
   ``I'm yet to be convinced that that slowdown is going to lead to
a recession,'' Anderson said.
   Many agree, at least for the near future.
   Only a third of 50 economists surveyed by Blue Chip Economic
Indicators of Sedona, Ariz., see a recession starting by the end of
1990. Another third see one in 1991 and the rest don't predict a
recession until 1992 or beyond.
   Ken Goldstein, a labor economist with the Conference Board, a
New York-based business group, sees the layoffs as part of a
continuum over the past 6{ years.
   ``Overall the number of layoffs doesn't seem to have
significantly increased,'' he said. ``What is unusual during the
last six or eight months is the number of layoffs that have been
highly publicized.''
   Goldstein attributes the publicity to nervousness about the
economy, a feeling he says that is ``not just limited to the
investment community.''
   An organized-labor economist who is among the nervous said
layoffs must be considered in re-examining trade and technology
policies.
   ``It's an economic problem in that we're losing a lot of
production and the associated earnings and income,'' said Markley
Roberts, assistant director of the AFL-CIO's Department of Economic
Research in Washington. ``And then in addition, you have the
tremendous dislocation ... that produces a whole lot of human costs
in terms of health and family.''
   Roberts is concerned about recent signs from layoffs.
   ``Purists would say you've got to wait for more numbers to come
in, but I feel certain we're on the verge of a slowdown or
recession,'' Roberts said.
   Historically, manufacturing is among the first sectors of the
economy hit during a downturn, but the past few years have left the
economy on a high plateau that can withstand some blows, Anderson
said.
   Unemployment in October and September was 5.3 percent, up from
5.1 percent in August but down from 5.4 percent in August 1988,
according to the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   The latest unemployment report showed a decline in manufacturing
jobs for the seventh straight month but a sharp increase in local
and state government hiring as well as in health services.
Employment in business services, finance and real estate was up
slightly or flat.
   Recent layoffs have been concentrated in a few industries,
notably auto manufacturing, computers and financial services.
   But they also have affected such far-flung companies as
aerospace and equipment supplier Trinova Corp. of Maumee, Ohio,
with 1,500 employees let go; the Los Angeles Herald Examiner
newspaper, which closed, eliminating 831 jobs; and the Braniff Inc.
airline, which could lay off up to 2,700 employees due to its
financial troubles.
   Elizabeth Baatz, a senior economist at Cahners Publishing Co. in
Newton, Mass., says the layoffs and voluntary severances in the
electronics industry _ including computer and office and
communications equipment makers _ do not indicate ``horrible times
ahead.''
   Electronics companies have held down on hiring even though
production has climbed sharply since the industry's 1985-86
recession, so they do not have many extra employees, she said. In
fact, employment remains below the 1984 peak.
   Everett Ehrlich, vice president for economic analysis for
Unisys, says the computer industry is a victim of its success in
making smaller, more powerful and less expensive equipment. It
takes fewer people to build and maintain the new machines.
   The result, he said, is ``the U.S. computer industry is not at a
precipice. The layoffs are a harsh human toll, but the layoffs
don't indicate that the industry is mature or that it's being
beaten by an influx of foreign machines.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891110-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Remy-Cointreau     11-10 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Remy-Cointreau,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remy Martin, Cointreau Plan Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family-held French spirits groups E. Remy
Martin and Cie. and Cointreau SA said Friday they plan to merge in
a deal that will give them a competitive boost against foreign
giants in the beverage market.
   The move is aimed at creating a ``premium French spirits group
... drawing on the synergies between the two companies while
respecting the identity of each one,'' the companies said in a
joint statement.
   The merger would create a company with annual revenue of more
than 6 billion francs, or about $1 billion, the companies said.
   The plan is to unite Remy Martin's cognac, champagne and premium
wine holdings under the same umbrella as Cointreau's liqueur,
armagnac, rum, fruit juice and luxury food products.
   Beyond obvious advantages in distribution, this move also would
give the family group new financial muscle to help protect it from
big publicly-traded competitors like Seagram Co. Ltd. and Grand
Metropolitan Plc, which have been competing to acquire the
dwindling number of quality beverage products still available.
   In this respect, the planned merger resembles previous alliances
that created other French family-controlled groups like
Moet-Hennessy and LVMH Moet-Hennessy-Louis Vuitton SA.
   Under the plan, the holding company of the Heriard-Dubreuil
family will transfer its 51 percent interest in Remy to Cointreau
and Cie., a holding company which controls 100 of Contreau SA. Each
company will retain management autonomy after the deal.
   Other details of the asset swap have not yet been completed, but
the companies said the Heriard-Dubreuil family will emerge with a
slight majority over the Cointreau family in the newly formed group.
   The deal requires shareholder approval which is expected in the
coming months, they said.
   The decision to unite the two companies follows years of close
cooperation in distribution throughout the Pacific and the United
States. Cointreau family interests have also been long-term
shareholders in Remy Martin.
   Recent earnings data for Remy Martin and Cointreau were not
available since neither of the companies is publicly traded.
</TEXT>
