<HEAD>Atari Finds Buyer for Federated Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atari Corp., the computer and video
game maker, said it has agreed to sell 26 of its struggling
Federated Group consumer electronics stores to Silo Inc., a
Philadelphia-based electronics retailer.
   The tentative agreement, announced Thursday, calls for Silo to
take over 21 Federated stores in Los Angeles and Orange counties
and five in San Diego. Terms of the deal weren't announced.
   Silo already operates 10 stores in San Diego.
   Atari officials said discussions continue with potential buyers
for its 14 remaining stores in Texas, Kansas and Arizona.
   Federated Group had 91 outlets when Atari bought it in August
1987 for $67.3 million. The chain immediately began losing money.
After announcing a loss of nearly $85 million in March, Atari put
Federated up for sale.
