<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Higher Despite Crop Estimates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, shrugging off increased
estimates of the nation's corn and soybean crop production.
   Corn prices were higher from the open as commercial buyers
entered the market on reports the Soviet Union may make a purchase
totalling 1.5 million metric tons.
   ``You can forget the production numbers,'' said analyst Mickey
Luth of Sherson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago. ``The figures have
no meaning at all. What matters is the news flow, producer sales
and export sales.''
   The crop report released Thursday by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture estimated the 1989 corn harvest at 7.59 billion
bushels, up 2 percent from the previous estimate, and soybean
production at 1.94 billion bushels, 1 percent above the October
estimate.
   Some analysts had predicted the crop report would trigger a
selloff, with export demand offering some support to prices.
   Soybean prices were higher on carryover strength from the corn
market and strong demand for soyoil. Prices also received support
from concern over delays in the planting of Brazil's soybean crop.
   Wheat prices were higher due to dryness in the winter wheat crop
areas.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents to 5{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.05 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.38 cents a bushel; oats
were } cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $1.43\ a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents to 8{ cents higher with November at $5.76 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
