<FIRST>r f AM-BancOne-MCorp     11-10 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banc One-MCorp,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banc One Announces Delay in MCorp Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banc One Corp. has announced a two-month delay in
closing its deal to acquire MCorp's failed banks from the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. because it's taking longer than anticipated
to review MCorp's loan portfolios.
   Banc One said Thursday that there have been ``no unusual
circumstances'' in the process, and the banking company hopes to
complete the acquisition by Jan. 17.
   The Columbus, Ohio-based banking company acquired Dallas-based
MCorp's 20 failed banks after federal banking regulators took them
over, saying they were insolvent.
   MCorp still owns five banks.
   The banks were merged into the Deposit Insurance Bridge Bank,
which Banc One agreed to acquire for $500 million.
   Banc One chairman John McCoy said in a prepared statement
Thursday that ``progress is being made in restructuring the bridge
bank under a management contract with the FDIC.''' He said the
company has installed its own management and information systems in
the bank and that the bank will be profitable in the first month
after the deal closes.
   The bailout is expected to cost the FDIC about $2 billion and is
the second most expensive in the agency's history. The bridge bank
was renamed Bank One Texas, and Banc One is managing it on the
contract with the FDIC until the deal can be closed.
   Banc One operates 53 affiliate banks and 563 branch offices in
Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
