<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-10 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises on East German Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher Friday as startling
reforms in East Germany and their uncertain affect on the economy
of West Germany fueled demand for the U.S. currency.
   Gold prices eased. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid for gold at 4 p.m. EST of $386.25 a troy ounce, down from
$386.30 late Thursday. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold lost
30 cents an ounce to close at $386.80.
   Traders said the dollar's biggest move came at the expense of
the West German mark. The dollar opened at 1.8520 marks and rose
steadily throughout the session, although it never broke through
the 1.8700-mark level.
   ``People are getting anxious to get out of marks,'' said Kevin
Lawrie, vice president at the Bank of Boston's New York office.
   ``They're not sure what the impact might be,'' he said,
referring to rapid-fire changes in East Germany, where travel
restrictions put into place 28 years ago have been lifted
permanently.
   The East bloc nation continued to shock the world Friday by
announcing the Berlin Wall would be opened in sections this weekend
to create more border crossing points.
   But for currency investors, the addage is: ``When in doubt, buy
dollars,'' Lawrie said.
   ``The historic events going on in East Germany have created a
`safe-haven' situation for the dollar,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a
vice president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   But, he noted, expectations that fresh economic data due out
next week would show continued weakening of the U.S. economy
limited the dollar's rise. ``There was reluctance to take the
dollar much higher,'' he said.
   Next week the government is scheduled to report on the trade
deficit, retail sales, business inventories and housing starts.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 142.75 yen, slightly higher than
Thursday's close of 142.70 yen. Later in London, the dollar traded
higher at 143.35 yen. In New York, the dollar finished at 143.40
yen, up from from 143.13 yen on Thursday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5765 from $1.5863 late
Thursday. In New York, one pound cost $1.5773, cheaper for buyers
than Thursday's $1.5823.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.8670 West German marks, up from 1.8523;
1.6440 Swiss francs, up from 1.6250; 6.3255 French francs, up from
6.2810; 1,362.50 Italian lire, up from 1,354.25, and 1.1696
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1670.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.8625 West German marks, up from 1.8475;
1.6370 Swiss francs, up from 1.6212; 6.3135 French francs, up from
6.2545; 2.0950 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0815; 1,354.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,351.50, and 1.1694 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1675.
   Gold prices moved lower. In London the metal slipped to a late
bid of $386.00 a troy ounce, from $386.25 late Thursday. In Zurich,
gold fell to a closing bid of $384.50 an ounce from $387.30. In
Hong Kong gold closed at $386.24, down 48 cents from late Thursday.
   Silver prices slipped. On New York's Comex, the metal finished
at $5.26 a troy ounce, down from $5.28 on Thursday. Earlier in
London, silver fell to a late bid of $5.25 a troy ounce, from $5.33
late Thursday.
</TEXT>
