<FIRST>r f AM-Montedison-Himont     11-10 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Montedison-Himont,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Montedison to Buy Remaining Shares of Himont</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montedison SpA, Italy's largest chemical
company, has signed an agreement to buy the 19 percent of Himont
Inc. it doesn't already own in a deal valued at $627.3 million, the
companies announced Friday.
   Montedison agreed to pay $51 cash for each of the 12.3 million
Himont shares it doesn't already own.
   Himont, based in Wilmington, Del., is a leading producer and
marketer of the chemical polypropylene. Montedison said this summer
it wanted to acquire full control in the subsidiary in order to
compete more effectively in the increasingly global market.
   In August, Montedison offered to buy the remainder of another
subsidiary, Erbamont NV of the Netherlands. Montedison offered $37
in cash and warrants for each of the 12.4 million Erbamont shares
it doesn't already own.
   Montedison's major shareholder is the Italian conglomerate
Ferruzzi Group, which owns around 46 percent of its outstanding
shares.
