<FIRST>r f AM-ResortsInternational     11-10 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Resorts International,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resorts Reports Quarterly Loss, Acknowledges Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International Inc., burdened
with massive debt, on Friday said it lost $34.9 million in the
third quarter and acknowledged it may be forced into bankruptcy
proceedings.
   The casino company, which owes investors $900 million, stopped
paying interest to bondholders in August. Resorts and bondholder
representatives have been negotiating a debt restructuring for
several months.
   Regardless of the outcome of those talks, Resorts said it
expects bondholders to file a petition to force the company into
involuntary bankruptcy by Nov. 15 _ the first anniversary of
entertainer Merv Griffin's purchase of the company.
   Under federal bankruptcy laws, bondholders have a year to
contend that company insiders wrongfully paid money to immunize it,
for their own benefit, from bankruptcy claims.
   Griffin initially put up $100 million to purchase Resorts from
developer Donald Trump. He later withdrew $50 million but gave
Resorts a $10 million credit line.
   ``We believe that there is ... probably a likelihood that a
petition would be filed by the 15th,'' said Alison MacDonald, a
Resorts spokeswoman in New York.
   Analysts said the bondholders' action was not unexpected.
   ``Certainly, the bondholders are trying to protect themselves by
having as much cash in the pot as possible,'' said Marvin B.
Roffman, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in
Philadelphia.
   In August, Griffin told bondholders of Resorts and its
subsidiaries _ Resorts International Finance Inc. and Griffin
Resorts Inc. _ that interest payments would be halted.
   Separately, in the third quarter ended Sept. 30, Resorts lost
$34.9 million _ interest alone accounted for $32.5 million _ on
revenues of $124.3 million. In the year-ago quarter, the company
posted a loss of $339.8 million on revenues of $123.9 million.
Per-share figures were not available.
   The company blamed lower casino revenue for the quarterly loss
but noted that capital improvment projects should help improve some
operations next year.
   First the first nine months, Resorts said it lost $81.5 million
on revenues of $347.9 million, compared with $357.4 million lost on
revenue of $353.6 million for the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
