<FIRST>u f BC-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   11-10 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Eastern Extension for Filing Disclosure Statement</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 2-3 to ADD that Dec. 29 deadline applies to both
disclosure statement and reorganization plan, CORRECT that revised plan
submitted to creditors sted court; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, Lifland
told ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge on Friday granted
Eastern Airlines an extension of the deadline for filing its
disclosure statement, which is intended to provide details of how
it intends to emerge from Chapter 11 reorganization.
   In a hearing, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland gave
Eastern until Dec. 29, a 45-day extension, to submit the disclosure
statement and a revised reorganization plan. The Miami-based
airline had requested that the Nov. 13 deadline for the disclosure
statement be extended for 60 days to Jan. 12.
   Eastern also had asked the court to extend to Jan. 12 its
exclusive right to submit a proposed reorganization plan. During
the exclusivity period, other parties to the case cannot make
reorganization proposals for Eastern, which recently submitted a
revised plan to its major creditors.
   Lifland told Eastern's attorneys that if the airline files its
disclosure statement by the new Dec. 29 deadline, it would
automatically receive a 60-day extension of the exclusivity period.
   Eastern's striking unions opposed the extensions, while
committees representing Eastern creditors and preferred
shareholders supported them.
   Eastern said the requests were motivated by the size and
complexity of its bankruptcy proceeding. Lifland previously had
granted Eastern two extensions of its exclusivity period and one
deferred deadline for filing the disclosure statement.
   The airline, which was struck by its pilots, Machinists and
flight attendants on March 4 in an ongoing walkout, has hired
replacement workers and is rebuilding as a smaller carrier.
   On Wednesday, Eastern posted a third-quarter net loss of $185.2
million after reportedly advising creditors' attorneys of a $200
million cash shortfall looming in its rebuilding plan.
   Also this week, the House gave final congressional approval to
legislation creating a congressional panel to investigate the
eight-month-old strike against Eastern, a measure the Bush
administration has threatened to veto.
</TEXT>
