<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Chartwell     11-10 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Chartwell,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Buys 5 Percent Stake in Avon, Rekindling Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group including Mary Kay Cosmetics
has amassed a 5 percent stake in Avon Products Inc., it was
disclosed Friday in an announcement that sparked speculation about
a renewed takeover advance on Avon.
   Avon earlier this year rebuffed overtures from Mary Kay Corp.
Vice Chairman John P. Rochon and rejected outright takeover
proposals from investor Irwin Jacobs and rival direct seller Amway
Corp.
   Avon's management repeatedly has insisted that the company is
better off remaining independent, free to carry out plans aimed at
improving the balance sheet.
   A limited partnership calling itself Chartwell Associates
notified Avon that as of Friday morning it held 5 percent of Avon's
outstanding voting stock, Avon said in a news release.
   Chartwell, in a letter, did not divulge its intentions, Avon
said.
   Avon spokesman John Cox said there hadn't been any direct
contact between Avon executives and members of the investment
group. He said Avon had no further comment to supplement its brief
announcement.
   Trading of Avon stock was temporarily halted Friday for the
announcement. The stock shot up when trading resumed, with the news
spurring speculative purchases as investors bet that a takeover
battle could be looming. Avon closed up $5.50 at $36.75 a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The general partners in Chartwell were identified as members of
New York's Fisher family, which own significant real estate
holdings, and Argonaut Partners, headed by Rochon. The Getty Family
Trust was listed as the sole limited partner.
   Attempts to contact the partners for comment weren't immediately
successful.
   In the spring, Rochon revealed that he and some investor allies
had been interested in Avon for some time.
   He said in a letter dated May 25 that if Mary Kay succeeded in
acquiring Avon, the company would be run by Argonaut Partners,
which he described as an investment arm of Mary Kay Cosmetics, the
Dallas-based door-to-door beauty products marketer that is the main
unit of privately held Mary Kay Corp.
   The possibility of renewed takeover interest in Avon has been
rumored on Wall Street for weeks.
   News last month from the company that direct sales in the United
States probably would be disappointing in the important fourth
quarter shopping season _ due largely to sagging gift and jewelry
sales _ intensified the speculation.
   There has been talk that disaffected shareholders might put
pressure on Avon's management to take a hard look at any new
takeover offers that come along.
   The management evoked considerable stockholder consternation
when it turned down two previous offers this year. A $41-a-share,
or $2.85 billion, takeover bid from Minneapolis-based investor
Jacobs was spurned as was an earlier one from Amway for $39 a
share, or $2.1 billion.
   In the wake of the rejections, Avon implemented new cost
controls and speeded up the sales of certain subsidiaries, mainly
in health care services.
   More recently, Avon has said it is looking into the possibility
of divesting its retail fragrance division, comprising Giorgio
Beverly Hills and Parfums Stern.
   The cosmetics company's latest financial results show a
continuing turnaround in profitability that analysts say could
suffer a slight setback by the prospective slump in fourth-quarter
U.S. sales.
   Avon earned $34.6 million, or 46 cents a share, in the three
months ended Sept. 30 compared to a loss of $405.9 million, or
$7.78 a share, in the third 1988 quarter, when the company took a
$425 million after-tax charge for discontinued operations.
</TEXT>
