<FIRST>u f AM-Bush-HousingReax     11-10 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Housing Reax,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Realtors Seek Increase in FHA Loan Limits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Housing Affordability listed on AMs digest.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the 800,000-member National
Association of Realtors offered the organization's support Friday
to President Bush's $4.2 billion plan to help the poor and homeless.
   ``We're very much in favor of all the things he said,'' outgoing
president Ira Gribin said after Bush unveiled the plan in a speech
to the association.
   ``This was the kind of thing we were looking for,'' Gribin said.
``It sounds like he has bought into ... a lot of the things''
suggested by Jack Kemp, secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
   Kemp, who accompanied Bush to Dallas, was given a standing
ovation by the Realtors when introduced to the 4,800 people at the
meeting.
   Earlier Friday, Gribin had called on the Bush Administration to
provide leadership to re-establish affordable housing as a national
goal.
   ``This country is fundamentally moving away from an
affordability situation and the reaffirmation of a national housing
policy,'' Gribin, a real estate agent from Encino, Calif., told
reporters.
   ``We need to get back on that because otherwise your kids and my
kids and our grandchildren are not going to be able to own houses.''
   Parts of Bush's program mirrors suggestions made by the
Realtors, including allowing money to be withdrawn without penalty
from Individual Retirement Accounts to make down payments on homes.
   Earlier Gribin had suggested grandparents, in-laws and parents
be allowed to dip into IRA savings to help the next generation of
first-time home buyers. Gribin said the Realtors would continue to
work on legislation to broaden the IRA availability.
   Also, Gribin called for replacing current limits on Federal
Housing Administration loans with a sliding scale tying them to
house prices in specific regions.
   Congress recently passed legislation raising FHA loan limits to
$124,878. Gribin said the limit still is too low in 10 of the
nation's largest 13 metropolitan areas, locking out first-time and
low-income home buyers.
   A study by the Realtors showed that more than half of FHA- and
Veterans Administration-backed loans are for entry-level buyers.
   Gribin said the limit should be set at 95 percent of the current
median price in a given market.
</TEXT>
