<FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv11-12   11-10 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 11-12,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 11-12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Events Outpacing Government in High Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Events raced ahead of would-be industrial
policymakers this past week as U.S. semiconductor companies made
deals with IBM and the Japanese.
   While Congress was holding hearings on the health of the vital
U.S. chip industry, the chip makers themselves were out fending for
themselves as best they could, with mixed results.
   The week's developments again raised the question of whether
government agencies and blue-chip industry panels were either quick
enough or patient enough to make a real contribution to the global
battle for industrial supremacy.
   Conservative skeptics say government-led industrial policy is
fated to failure, while supporters say it could work if Americans
only learned to do it right. So far, though, both sides agree that
the awkward early efforts are being outpaced by the real world of
business.
   Three things happened this past Wednesday that illustrated
different dimensions of the issue:
   _U.S. chip makers said they had reached an agreement with
Japanese electronics companies that eventually could allow the
Americans to make customized chips for the next generation of
Japanese televisions.
   _International Business Machines Corp. said it would license the
technology for making its most powerful computer memory chip to
Micron Technology Inc. of Boise, Idaho.
   _And in Washington, the head of the government-supported chip
consortium Sematech told a congressional committee that the U.S.
effort to regain supremacy in chips is in jeopardy. The statement
from Robert Noyce came as talk circulated that the Bush
administration wants to cut back on some research projects,
including Sematech.
   In part, the deal between U.S. chipmakers and Japanese companies
was a rare victory for U.S. government efforts to get a bigger
share of the Japanese chip market. But it also illustrated that the
United States continues to negotiate from a position of weakness.
   American companies will get from Japan the information they need
to design chips for the Japanese. But there is no guarantee that
Japan actually will buy American-made chips.
   The U.S. chip makers would like to make circuits for
American-made high-definition televisions as well, although the
Bush administration's decision not to make a full-fledged
commitment to HDTV could bog down development of that technology.
   ``Businesses are going to move forward whether the government
does or not,'' said Jeanne Alford, a spokeswoman for the
Semiconductor Industry Association.
   IBM made its deal with Micron Technologies to ensure that there
would be another source of U.S.-made memory chips. IBM said it also
intended to supply its technology to a chip-making consortium
called U.S. Memories Inc., of which it is a strong backer.
   Unfortunately for industrial policy mavens, U.S. Memories has
been slow to get off the ground since its inception in June.
Critics say a joint manufacturing venture won't work. And they say
that IBM through its deal with Micron has essentially made U.S.
Memories unnecessary, something IBM disputes.
   Most disheartening to the supporters of industrial policy were
impressions, perhaps unfounded, that the Bush administration's
commitment to Sematech and the U.S.-Japanese chip trade agreement
was waning at a critical time.
   Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif., said his office had gotten leaks
saying ``high administration officials are conducting a
slash-and-burn campaign seeking to systematically eliminate most of
the major initiatives designed to return this country to the
industrial cutting edge.''
   ``What I find marvelous about our government is that they
criticize business for being short-sighted, then they show
incredible volatility in programs that take five years or more to
play out,'' said William Finan, a managing director of the
Washington consulting firm of Quick, Finan &amp; Associates.
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _Ford Motor Co. Chairman Donald Petersen, who guided the company
to record profitability during the late 1980s, announced he will
retire March 1. Vice Chairman Harold Poling is slated to take the
helm of the nation's second-largest automaker.
   _The Federal Reserve eased credit to counter a slowdown in the
economy, which was marked by layoffs at several major companies.
But the signs of weakness were countered by a Labor Department
report that wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in October.
   _East Germany opened the Berlin Wall and gave its citizens
permission to freely cross the rest of its borders in a move that
experts said would have immediate benefits for American companies
in West Germany _ although the short-term prospects for U.S.
multinationals in East Germany were uncertain.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 11-12</NOTE>
