<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-10 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain and Soybeans Prices Jump Despite Bearish Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures surged higher Friday on the Chicago
Board of Trade as buyers shrugged off increased estimates of the
nation's corn and soybean crop production.
   On other markets, precious metals and copper declined, sugar
rose, energy futures were lower, and livestock and pork futures
were mixed.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 5} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.04{ a bushel; corn was a \ cent to 1{
cents higher with December at $2.38 a bushel; oats were } cent to
1\ cents higher with December at $1.43\ a bushel; soybeans were 4}
cents to 8{ cents higher with November at $5.75} a bushel.
   Corn prices were higher from the opening of trading as
commercial buyers entered the market on reports the Soviet Union
may buy 1.5 million metric tons.
   ``You can forget the production numbers,'' said analyst Mickey
Luth of Sherson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago. ``The figures have
no meaning at all. What matters is the news flow, producer sales
and export sales.''
   The crop report released Thursday by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture estimated the 1989 corn harvest at 7.59 billion
bushels, up 2 percent from the previous estimate, and soybean
production at 1.94 billion bushels, 1 percent above the October
estimate.
   Some analysts had predicted the crop report would trigger a
Friday selloff, with export demand offering some support to prices.
   Soybean prices were higher on carryover strength from the corn
market and strong demand for soyoil. Prices also received support
from concern over delays in the planting of Brazil's soybean crop.
   Wheat prices were higher due to dryness in the winter wheat crop
areas.
   Precious metals prices dropped on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold was 40 cents to 50 cents lower with December at $388.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 4.4 cents to 4.9 cents lower with December
at $5.26 a troy ounce.
   Copper settled lower on the Comex amid uncertainty over the
amount of stocks in London Metal Exchange-approved warehouses.
There were forecasts earlier in the week of lower stocks, which
were replaced Friday by expectations of increased stocks.
   Copper was .60 cent to 1.25 cents lower with the contract in
December at $1.145 a pound.
   Supply concerns and worry that Brazil may have trouble meeting
its export obligations again boosted sugar prices on New York's
Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange.
   Sugar was .17 cent to .24 cent higher with January at 14.50
cents a pound.
   Energy futures were lower in quiet trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. Heating oil led crude oil and gasoline prices
lower in a drop attributed to seasonal pressures.
   ``Consumers usually put heating oil in the tank in October, just
as the weather is getting cold,'' said analyst Peter Beutel, of
Elders Futures Inc. in New York. ``They usually don't fill up again
until December. Making this usually a disappointing month for
heating oil.''
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 8 cents to 15 cents lower
with December at 19.84 cents a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to
.47 cent lower with December at 58.45 a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .22 cent to .40 cent lower with December at 51.82 cents a
gallon.
   Livestock and pork futures were mixed in light trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle, although slightly higher, are in a holding pattern
because of a quiet cash market, said analyst Thomas Morgan of
Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Hogs and pork belly prices were mixed, getting support from
lighter slaughter activity but coming under pressure from lower
cash prices, Morgan said.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .17 cent higher with December at
74.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .17 cent
higher with November at 83.15 a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to
43 cent higher with December at 47.95 a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .40 cent lower to .13 cent higher with February at 63.30 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
