<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     11-10 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Little Changed in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished little changed Friday in
light activity as many traders stayed out of the market for
Veterans Day.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond ended unchanged from
late Thursday, with its yield at 7.89 percent.
   Analysts said bond prices were little changed after the Federal
Reserve entered the market for a second day to drain reserves from
the banking system.
   The intervention, which began on Thursday, suggested that the
Fed does not want the key federal funds rate to fall below 8{
percent, said Elizabeth Reiners, vice president for money-market
research at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``The Fed's move was a surprise. It will cause short-term yields
to rise because no one was forecasting'' the move, Ms. Reiners said.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 8] percent, unchanged from
late Thursday.
   Analysts said the Fed's draining action signaled a retreat from
a maneuver earlier in the week that had suggested the central bank
was relaxing its credit policy and encouraging lower interest
rates. On Monday and Tuesday, the central bank injected billions of
dollars of reserves into the market, pushing short-term interest
rates lower.
   Trading was light Friday, with many traders taking a long
weekend in observance of Veterans Day on Saturday.
   Bond prices also were unaffected by Friday's Treasury auction of
$10 billion in short-term debt, in the form of 36-day cash
management bills. The bills carried a discount interest rate of
8.14 percent and an equivalent coupon interest rate of 8.32 percent.
   ``You can't read too much into that,'' said Mitchell Held, chief
financial economist at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues edged down 1-32 point, intermediate
maturities were unchanged to 1-32 point lower and longer-term
issues were 1-32 point lower to 1-32 point higher, according to
figures provided by Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, slipped 0.22 to 1,193.35.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, edged
up 0.11 to 338.63.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds was at 9219-32, up 1-32. The average yield
to maturity was 7.34 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 7.96 percent as the
discount gained 2 basis points to 7.71 percent. Yields on six-month
bills were unchanged at 7.97 percent as the discount remained
stable at 7.57 percent. Yields on one-year bills were flat at 7.81
percent as the discount remained unchanged at 7.30 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
</TEXT>
