<FIRST>u f AM-TexasEastern-Resignations     11-10 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Eastern-Resignations,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Officials Resign After Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three senior executives of Texas Eastern Corp., a
subsidiary of oil company Panhandle Eastern Corp., announced Friday
they are resigning at year's end.
   Officials of Houston-based Panhandle Eastern said the
resignations had been expected after the company purchased Texas
Eastern last April.
   Dennis R. Hendrix, president and chief executive officer of
Texas Eastern, and Paul M. Anderson, senior vice president, said
they plan to pursue other interests after Dec. 31, but will
continue to assist with post-merger related activities. Executive
Vice President Derrill Cody will join the Oklahoma City law firm of
McKinney, Stringer and Webster.
   ``The resignations are of a routine nature as a result of the
acquisition of Texas Eastern into the Panhandle Eastern system,''
said spokesman Mack Price. Many other Texas Eastern employees have
been offered early retirement or severance packages to be taken by
Dec. 31, he said.
   Sixty-year-old Panhandle Eastern acquired Texas Eastern in April
to begin operating one of the largest interstate natural gas
pipeline systems in the United States. The company's operating
units provide natural gas to the Midwest, mid-Atlantic and
Northeast regions.
   Price said that since the merger, Panhandle Eastern has been
working to sell Texas Eastern's assets other than pipelines.
   ``Those assets have included, so far, the exploration and
production activities of Texas Eastern, their refinery activities,
their interests in liquid petroleum gas, their real estate
interests like Houston Center, and other investment activities,''
Price said.
   Hendrix and Anderson will act as consultants in those
negotiations, he said.
   ``Panhandle Eastern's success in absorbing Texas Eastern is
based in large part on the efforts of Dennis Hendrix and his
associates. They have agreed to continue helping Panhandle where
they can, and we will continue to rely on them,'' said R.D.
Hunsucker, chairman and chief executive officer of Panhandle
Eastern.
   ``Hendrix, Cody, Anderson and others have been key participants
in the asset sales which have contributed to the significant
reduction in Panhandle Eastern's acquisition-related debt,'' he
said. ``Under arrangements made in conjunction with their
departures, several of these executives will retain major
responsibilities for the continued success of Panhandle's
divestiture strategy.''
</TEXT>
