<FIRST>u f AM-Germany-Business     11-10 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Business,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Companies Watching Events In East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening of the Berlin Wall and lifting of
travel restrictions on East German citizens could have immediate
benefits for American companies in West Germany, although
short-term prospects for U.S. multinationals to expand into East
Germany are unclear, experts said Friday.
   Any move to the East by American and other multinationals won't
happen overnight without a change in the current political
structure of the communist nation, but sweeping changes could occur
in the next decade.
   ``Within the next five years, we will start to see noticeable
and significant flows of money and goods from west to east,'' said
Ed Yardeni, economist with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Woolworth Corp., the retailer that has done business in West
Berlin for 65 years, said the flow of thousands of East Berliners
across the border this week already had boosted sales of its West
German operations.
   ``They're already shopping at our stores. They've been very
crowded in the last 24 hours,'' said Roy L. Garofalo, Woolworth's
vice president of investor relations in New York.
   ``They're not wealthy people, but many may have savings because
there was nothing to buy in East Germany.''
   Woolworth has 225 general merchandise stores in West Germany,
including 24 in West Berlin.
   Woolworth stock rose $3.25 to $60.87{ a share Friday on the New
York Stock Exchange on what one analyst attributed to positive
sentiment about the political events in East Germany.
   Elsewhere on Wall Street, Germany Fund recorded one of the day's
biggest percentage gains. The fund finished up $2.75 at $13.50 a
share as the West German stock market, where the fund invests,
responded to the opening of the East German borders.
   Officials of Ford Motor Co., which has been in West Germany
since 1925, said they were watching closely as events unfolded.
   Vice Chairman Harold Poling, who will become chairman and chief
executive of Ford on March 1, said the world's second largest
automobile maker was looking at ``all the opportunities.''
   Ford has manufacturing and assembly operations throughout West
Germany that employ about 37,500 people.
   Analysts said the opening of East Germany and recent events in
Poland and Hungary point to tremendous opportunities for Americans
and other industrialists around the world. But any increased
business in the Eastern Bloc nations will depend on the timing of
political reforms, strategists said.
   ``They will need a new political structure before anyone will
know what to do,'' said Lawrence A. Veit, international economist
with Brown Brothers Harriman &amp; Co.
   ``It will be negative for the defense industry but positive, a
larger positive, for all other companies,'' Veit said.
   West German companies will have the competitive edge in the
Eastern Bloc once the reforms get under way, economists said.
Multinational companies already doing business in West Germany will
be positioned to enter the East German market behind the West
Germans but American companies will get a fair share of the market
if they move aggressively, Yardeni said.
   ``The rush to invest in Eastern Europe ... will depend on how
quickly Western money and Western capitalists are willing to move
in...,'' he said.
   Woolworth's Garofalo said that as recently as six weeks ago
Woolworth officials were in East Germany to explore future
opportunities.
   ``There was some writing on the wall even a few weeks ago,'' he
said.
   But any move into East Germany is still at least two years away,
Garofalo said.
</TEXT>
