<DOCNO> AP891110-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bicoastal-Bankruptcy     11-10 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bicoastal-Bankruptcy,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bicoastal Files for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bicoastal Corp., formerly Singer Co. headed
by onetime corporate raider Paul Bilzerian, filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection Friday following a tumultuous two years of
legal battles and divestments.
   A company annoucement said Bicoastal expects to file a
reorganization plan soon seeking to ``provide for the payment of
valid creditors and provide a method to resolve disputed claims.''
   Bicoastal said the filing does not affect its remaining
subsidiaries, which include makers of aircraft and nuclear plant
training simulators and weapons control systems.
   Officials at Tampa-based Bicoastal could not be reached late
Friday.
   Singer, renamed earlier this year, was acquired by Bilzerian in
January 1988 in a $1.06 billion takeover. Bilzerian sold off eight
of the company's 12 divisions, including some of the most
profitable, and sparked a flood of employee lawsuits and other
litigation, estimated to exceed $500 million.
   In June, Bilzerian was convicted on nine counts of securities
fraud, conspiracy to commit tax fraud and making false statements
to the government. Three months later, he was sentenced to a
four-year prison term and fined $1.5 million.
   It is uncertain how the bankruptcy filing will affect the
reported $75 million purchase of Mesa Limited Partnership's
interest in Bicoastal.
   The Wall Street Journal on Friday reported that New York-based
Leucadia National Corp. agreed in principle to buy the stock and
notes Mesa acquired in connection with Bilzerian's takeover.
   Mesa, an Amarillo, Texas-based partnership headed by raider T.
Boone Pickens, loaned Bilzerian's group $150 million and negotiated
an option to take control of the Singer board if the company failed
by pay the entire loan plus interest by April 1, 1989. The date was
later extended to July 1.
   The pact could give Leucadia control of the board of Bicoastal,
a 138-year-old company that grew from a sewing machine manufacturer
to a major defense contractor.
   There was no answer at Leucadia's New York office late Friday.
   In May, U.S. District Court Judge Herbert Murray in Baltimore
placed an injunction against transfer of any major Singer assets
without court approval.
   Murray's action came after the government filed a $231 million
defense-contract overcharge suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
