<DOCNO> AP891110-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-10-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 1stLd-Writhru   11-10 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writhru,f0326,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Pilots' Group Seeks Pilot Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with additional details, stock price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing United Airlines' pilots
said Friday it has urged its members to support its continued
efforts to gain control of parent company, UAL Corp.
   The pilots' union also disclosed that since a pilot-management
bid for the airline failed last month, it has ``had conservations''
with Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis, who previously bid for
UAL, New York investor Saul Steinberg, the investment firm Coniston
Partners and ``other financial investors.''
   The union also said spoken with the machinists' union and would
have further discussions.
   The letter did not elaborate on any of the discussions and a
spokesman for the pilots' union did not return calls Friday.
   UAL declined to comment on the latest development, said
spokeswoman Sara Dornacker.
   In trading Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, UAL rose $4.25
a share to $189.50.
   The Air Line Pilots Association leadership released a letter,
sent Thursday, urging members to strictly enforce their existing
labor contract beginning Nov. 22, when a self-imposed deadline on
voluntary labor concessions expires.
   The pilots are seeking a new contract to replace the one that
expired in April 1988. However, the pilots leadership stated in the
letter that continued takeover moves toward UAL made it doubtful an
agreement could be reached soon.
   ``Given that the company is obviously `in play' we see no way
that management will get serious about an equitable new contract
... unless it knows who is going to own the company,'' the letter
said. ``In our view, the piece of trash that the company recently
passed across the table clearly proves that fact.
   ``Unless the entire world clearly understands what we contribute
or don't contribute to the operation of the airline we will have
little chance of getting either an equitable new contract or an
appropriate new (employee stock ownership proposal) to be put to
the Board and accepted.''
   It called on pilots to prepare to stop flying United's new 747
model 400s and working four extra hours a month. The pilots had
been doing both as a show of good faith during its participation in
a pilot-management bid for the airline.
   Pilots and management signed a merger agreement with UAL's board
in September. As a show of good faith, pilots said they would fly
United's 747 model 400s they previously would not fly and work an
85-hour work-month, rather than the 81 hours stipulated in their
contract. The pilots had refused to fly the model 400s because of a
dispute over how many crew members should be used.
   When the deal fell apart in October when the group was unable to
obtain financing for its $6.75 billion offer, the employee group
again approached the board with a framework for a restructured
transaction, but the board at that time terminated the
negotiations, the union said.
   ``We intend to work intensively over the next two weeks ... to
put together a new transaction so that the new owners of UAL will
in fact be the employees and not some unwanted outsider,'' the
pilots' union said in the letter.
   Earlier this week, the UAL board reportedly authorized chairman
Stephen Wolf to explore new means of mounting a buyout or
recapitalization of the company.
   On Wednesday, Coniston Partners, which has accumulated a 9.7
percent stake in UAL, met with machinists of United to detail their
intentions for the company. Coniston has said it intends to oust
most of UAL's board.
   The machinists had declined to join an effort by United pilots,
flight attendants and management for employee ownership of the
airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
